<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cox Cable Reaches Deal With Fox  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- More than 400,000 Cox Communications cable customers will
once again be able to see Fox programming, including the National Football
League playoffs, because of a new transmission agreement reached Thursday, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
	   Fox had refused to let several Cox Communications systems in northern
Virginia, Cleveland, Dallas and Houston retransmit its programming after Cox
declined to add two other Fox networks as it upgrades to digital systems that
carry more channels.
</P>
<P>
	   At midnight on New Year's Eve, Cox subscribers could no longer receive Fox
over their cable connections, and those wanting the channel had to go back to
getting it over the air by antenna.
</P>
<P>
	   In a statement, Fox and Cox said they had "agreed in principle" to restoring
Fox local and national programming.
</P>
<P>
	   Both companies said they wouldn't disclose any terms of the agreement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
