<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Educational Trust Hires CEO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- A Hawaiian princess' multibillion-dollar estate has hired a
college administrator to run Kamehameha Schools, one of the islands' most
powerful private institutions that has been in turmoil the last several years.
</P>
<P>
	   Hamilton McCubbin, a former dean of the University of Wisconsin-Madison's
School of Human Ecology, was named chief executive officer, the schools
announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The hiring of a chief executive was one condition of a $9 million settlement
with the Internal Revenue Service allowing the $6 billion educational trust to
keep its tax-exempt status.
</P>
<P>
	   That status was jeopardized after allegations arose against the trustees in
1997 of mismangement, self-dealing and excessive pay.
</P>
<P>
	   Five trustees resigned their $1 million-a-year posts last year after a state
judge temporarily removed them, and five interim trustees have run the estate
since May.
</P>
<P>
	   McCubbin is a 1959 graduate of Kamehameha Schools, established by the 1884
will of Princess Bernice Pauahi Bishop for the education of native Hawaiian
children.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Dr. McCubbin brings to us a wealth of experience and knowledge in the area
of early education and child development,'' said Robert Kihune, chairman of the
interim board of trustees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
