<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Troops Fan Across Eastern Indonesia  </HEADLINE>
   By IRWAN FIRDAUS Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- Thousands of soldiers fanned out Thursday across a
group of islands in eastern Indonesia to try to quell violence between Muslims
and Christians that has claimed hundreds of lives in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday in Jakarta, an estimated 80,000 Muslim demonstrators demanded that
the government end the bloodshed, threatening to declare a holy war in defense
of Islam.
</P>
<P>
	   The rally, held after morning prayers at National Monument Square across the
street from the presidential palace, followed a series of smaller protests by
Muslims in the capital in recent days.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We give (President Abdurrahman Wahid) one month to stop the killings of
Muslims,'' said Husin Ali Al Habsy, one of the speakers at the rally.
``Otherwise, we are ready to send at least 10,000 people there to defend the
Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
	   Max Tamaela, military chief of Maluku province, said Thursday that the army
had re-established control of Seram Island, where fighting earlier this week
killed 17 people.
</P>
<P>
	   But the situation remained uncertain on Halmahera Island, where reports said
hundreds of people may have died in fighting Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   Thousands of people fleeing the violence continued to pour into the North
Maluku provincial capital of Ternate, about 1,600 miles east of Jakarta. Many
said the situation in Halmahera was out of control.
</P>
<P>
	   Tamaela said the military had sent in extra troops to try to stop the
violence on Halmahera, but he said he did not know if clashes had ended.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've deployed troops to the outlying islands,'' Tamaela said. ``But it's
hard to tell what is really going on.''
</P>
<P>
	   Officials estimate the death toll stands at about 500 for the past 10 days,
but unconfirmed reports put it much higher.
</P>
<P>
	   In Maluku's provincial capital of Ambon, the local military commander, Col.
Irwan Kusnadi, said his troops were preparing to secure the town before the
start Saturday of Eid al-Fitr, the Muslim holiday that celebrates the end of the
holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've confiscated thousands of illegal weapons in the past couple of
days,'' he said. ``We want to make sure the city is safe for the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Indonesia's navy has imposed a blockade around the islands in an
attempt to stop militia members from traveling between islands.
</P>
<P>
	   By the government's count, 1,300 people have died in Maluku and North Maluku
-- known as the Spice Islands during Dutch colonial rule -- since religious
fighting erupted a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   An influx of Muslims from Indonesia's other islands over the past two
decades has changed the religious makeup of the provinces, where the Christians
used to have a small majority.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0042 </TRAILER>
