<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Friday, Jan. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Police Use Tear Gas To Disperse Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- More than 50 officers in riot gear used tear gas to disperse
hundreds of people protesting the U.S. government's decision to return
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to his father in Cuba. Protesters blocked
intersections and cut off access to the Port of Miami. Police arrested at least
135 people, including two prominent Cuban exile leaders, for refusing to
disperse. The situation was expected to continue Friday. Brothers to the Rescue,
a Miami-based exile group that searches the waters off Florida for Cubans trying
to make it to the United States, called for supporters to drive 15 mph Friday
throughout Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Defends Actions on Behalf of Donor
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- At a campaign debate in New Hampshire on Thursday
night, GOP presidential candidate John McCain strongly defended his actions on
behalf of a political donor who was seeking action from the Federal
Communications Commission. "My job is to make the bureaucrats work for the
people," said McCain, who is chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee. "I would
do the same thing again, almost anytime." McCain wrote a letter on behalf of the
political donor. McCain's aides fretted that the issue of the letter could
seriously damage a candidacy based on a pledge of rooting out the influence of
special interests.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.S. Abortions Continue To Decline
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ATLANTA (AP) -- The number of abortions in the United States fell in 1997 to
the lowest level in two decades, despite new drugs that make it easier to
terminate a pregnancy. The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention reported
Thursday that 20 of every 1,000 women of reproductive age (15 to 44) had
abortions in 1997, the lowest since 1975. The CDC cited several factors for the
decline, including reduced access to abortion, an increased willingness to use
contraception and possibly different attitudes about the moral implications of
abortion.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sri Lanka Bomber's Parents Arrested
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- The parents and sister of a suicide bomber who
killed 13 people were among more than 700 Tamils detained in a two-day roundup
by Sri Lankan police, officials said Friday. All were arrested in the capital,
Colombo, and will be questioned about their possible involvement in Wednesday's
bombing outside the prime minister's office, authorities said. Police said they
had also arrested two Tamil Tiger rebels early Friday carrying explosives. The
rebels confessed that they intended to set off the bombs at bus stations in the
Buddhist temple town of Kandy, where Sri Lanka's majority Sinhalese Buddhist
believe a tooth relic of Buddha is kept, police said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Rejoins Mideast Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton plunged back into slow-moving
Mideast peace talks Thursday, meeting with Israel's prime minister and the
Syrian foreign minister after face-to-face negotiations between the two sides
ground to a halt. The U.S. aim is a treaty that would exchange the Golan
Heights, a strategic border territory Israel has held for more than three
decades, for diplomatic and economic relations with Syria. Clinton met
separately for an hour each with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Black Colleges Get Racist Threats
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Predominantly black colleges in Alabama and
Tennessee have received letters threatening the "total destruction of your race"
and bearing the image of the Confederate flag. Letters postmarked Fayetteville,
N.C., were sent to Oakwood College in Huntsville, Alabama A&AMP;M University in
Huntsville, Alabama State University in Montgomery, and Stillman College in
Tuscaloosa. They were also received by Fisk University and Meharry Medical
College in Nashville, Tenn. The anonymous messages said, "Eventually, we'll get
rid of you. The year 2000, the war escalates. ... We promise." Police have
alerted the FBI.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index posted a slight rise
Friday morning after opening the session lower. The Nikkei Stock Average gained
26.82 points to 18,195.09 at the end of the morning session. On Wall Street, the
Dow Jones industrial average rose 130.61 points to 11,253.26 at Thursday's
close. But the Nasdaq, dominated by technology stocks, fell 150.31, or 3.9
percent, to 3,727.23.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Flyers Defeat Islanders 3-2
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Rod Brind'Amour and Mikael Renberg each had a goal and
an assist as Philadelphia fought off the New York Islanders to increase the
NHL's longest active home unbeaten streak to 14 games Thursday night. Daymond
Langkow had a goal and Mark Recchi added three assists for the Flyers, who have
outscored their opponents 49-28 while going 11-0-3 during their streak.
Philadelphia is 4-0-1 in its last five overall.
</P>
