<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> LA Auto Show Has Crossover Vehicles  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Transportation of the future could combine the best
aspects of a sedan with those of SUVs and pickup trucks if the concept vehicles
being shown off at the Greater Los Angeles Auto Show catch on.
</P>
<P>
	   Three automakers -- the Saturn division of General Motors Corp., the Mercury
division of Ford Motor Co. and Subaru of America -- showed off concept vehicles
that promise the comfort and handling of a sedan, coupled with the ruggedness
and carrying ability of an SUV or pickup.
</P>
<P>
	   The Saturn CV1, inspired in part by Saturn Chairwoman Cynthia Trudell's
experience in London cabs, is strictly a concept car, she said following the
unveiling.
</P>
<P>
	   But the other two concepts -- the Mercury Mountaineer SUV and the Subaru
ST-X four-door truck -- appear much closer to reality. Ford designers said the
Mountaineer was a strong indication of what the next version of the vehicle
would look like, and how it would differ from its mechanical twin, the Ford
Explorer.
</P>
<P>
	   Subaru is thinking seriously of putting the more radical ST-X on production
lines in the next two or three years, George Muller, Subaru's president and
chief executive officer, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
	   "It depends on what kind of reaction we get," Muller said. "Right now the
market is really receptive to this type of vehicle, so it's a more serious
concept."
</P>
<P>
	   The notion that the traditional distinctions among autos are blurring -- a
process inspired by autos such as Subaru's Outback and the Lexus RX300 --
emerged as an unofficial theme at the show.
</P>
<P>
	   "We have to create new segments and redefine existing segments" in the auto
industry, Ron Zarrella, president of GM North America, said in a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The ST-X and CV1 both target mid-priced markets. The ST-X is aimed primarily
at Generation Xers who want to take bikes or snowboard gear to the mountains.
The CV1 seeks a broader audience: anyone who has kids or equipment to transport,
but doesn't want a traditional minivan or SUV, said Trudell.
</P>
<P>
	   The ST-X features four-passenger seating along with a 55.5-inch pickup bed.
The rear window can be rolled down into the back seat frame and folded down to
turn the ST-X into a two-seater with a 76-inch bed.
</P>
<P>
	   Other features include an independent suspension, all-wheel-drive,
roof-mounted lights and an 8.5 inch clearance for off-road travel.
</P>
<P>
	   Built from an Outback frame and a supercharged 230-horsepower version of the
Outback's 2.5 liter engine, the ST-X could move easily to mass production,
Muller said. If that happens, it probably would sell in a price range close to
the Outback, which goes for $23,000 to $28,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The ST-X stands out from other crossovers that have appeared so far, said
George Peterson, an auto industry analyst at Auto Pacific Inc. in Tustin, Calif.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's like a very nicely done four-door El Camino," he said. "It harkens
back to the old car-pickups of the 1960s and 1970s. With four doors it has a lot
of extra utility."
</P>
<P>
	   The CV1, Saturn's first concept vehicle, holds five adults in standard
seating. Two kid-sized, fold-down jump seats attached to the back of driver and
front passenger seats. Trudell suggested the jump seats after seeing them in
London cabs.
</P>
<P>
	   All seats except the driver's can be folded down flat.
</P>
<P>
	   At 177 inches, the CV1 is 1.1 inches shorter than the Saturn SL sedan and 2
feet shorter than Honda's Odyssey minivan.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mercury Mountaineer concept is slightly wider than the current version,
and has a cleaner, more straight-forward design, with larger headlamps and a
bolder grill. It's meant to help establish a separate look for Mercury, said J
Mays, Ford's design chief.
</P>
<P>
	   One striking exception to the truck/SUV theme was provided by Rolls Royce,
which debuted a new $360,000 Corniche convertible to live chamber music. The
sleek build-to-order auto revives the Corniche nameplate, which was discontinued
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
	   The two-door, four-seat Corniche features the classic Rolls Royce front
grill followed by a long, smooth lines that slope gently downward over the
trunk. The car is powered by a supercharged 6.75-liter engine and accelerates
from zero to 60 mph in eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
	   Rolls Royce expects to sell about 450 cars over its lifetime, including
about 100 in the United States, said Tony Gott, chief executive of Rolls Royce
and Bentley Motor Cars. The market is so exclusive, company executives already
know about 75 percent of their potential customers by name, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
