<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 7 More Players Named in Irish Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SOUTH BEND, Ind. (AP) -- Seven additional Notre Dame football players were
linked Thursday to a former booster convicted of embezzling more than $1.4
million from her employer.
</P>
<P>
	   The new names surfaced when Jerry Dominiack, the former employer of
convicted embezzler Kimberly Dunbar, filed an amended complaint in St. Joseph
Superior Court on Thursday, according to a report on ESPN's Web site.
</P>
<P>
	   The complaint says Bobby Taylor and Allen Rossum, former Irish players now
with the Philadelphia Eagles, accepted money or gifts from Dunbar.
</P>
<P>
	   The suit seeks $5,000 from Taylor, who allegedly was loaned the money to pay
back an agent, and $12,500 from Rossum, who allegedly was given the money to buy
himself and his girlfriend a camcorder and trips to New York and Las Vegas, ESPN
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Two other former Irish players, Ivory Covington and Tracy Graham, were named
in the suit. Also named were three players from this season's team -- Lamont
Bryant, Eric Chappell and Raki Nelson.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, the NCAA put Notre Dame on probation for the first time in the
school's history and said the university would lose two scholarships because of
the Dunbar case.
</P>
<P>
	   College football's sanctioning body, however, did not touch Notre Dame's
postseason eligibility. And the school's TV contract with NBC -- worth an
estimated $8 million to $9 million annually -- is not affected.
</P>
<P>
	   The university said last month it would not appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement ended an almost two-year investigation into the
relationships between Dunbar, 30, and several Irish players. Some of those
relationships were sexual, and Dunbar has a child with former player Jarvis
Edison.
</P>
<P>
	   Jack Friedenthal, chair of the NCAA infractions committee, said last month
the university was not penalized for gifts Dunbar gave players with whom she was
romantically involved, but her interaction with other players and their parents
was a factor in the decision.
</P>
<P>
	   The NCAA's report did not implicate anyone from the current Notre Dame
coaching staff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
