<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Urban Faculty Offered Incentives  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. (AP) -- Hoping to revitalize areas surrounding urban
colleges and universities, state officials are offering incentives for faculty
and staff to move into nearby neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
	   A program unveiled Thursday offers $10,000 for school employees who buy
homes in designated areas near New Jersey's state university campuses, said Jane
Kennedy, a commissioner in the state Department of Community Affairs. The money
is intended for use as down payments.
</P>
<P>
	   Faculty and staff who already own homes in the target areas can apply for
$5,000 to make exterior improvements, Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
	   ``One of the biggest challenges for cities is attracting and retaining
middle-income households,'' she said. ``But this isn't just about selling people
a house. We're looking for people to buy a community.''
</P>
<P>
	   The program, expected to cost $2.5 million for the fiscal year 2000, was
announced a year ago in Gov. Christie Whitman's budget address.
</P>
<P>
	   It has since garnered the support of college and university administrators
across the state, said Rutgers President Francis Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``When people think of higher education, it's natural for them to focus on
traditional missions, such as teaching,'' he said. ``But service to our
communities is also an essential element of our mission.''
</P>
<P>
	   A total of 13 campuses in nine institutions are eligible to participate in
the grant program. Faculty and staff must settle nearby the schools except for
in Camden, where all city locations qualify.
</P>
<P>
	   Participating schools range in size from Rutgers -- with nearly 11,000
full-time faculty and staff at three campuses -- to Cumberland County Community
College, which has 150 full-time employees at its campus in Vineland.
</P>
<P>
	   Kenny said household income will not be a factor in obtaining the basic
$10,000 down payment money, but families whose incomes meet restrictions set by
the state Housing and Mortgage Finance Agency will also be eligible for more
assistance, including a reduced rate mortgage.
</P>
<P>
	   New Jersey's program is modeled after a similar effort at the University of
Pennsylvania. That program is widely credited with beginning a renewal of West
Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
