<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fighting Bulls Bring Money to Kenya  </HEADLINE>
   By JOHN NENE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KHAYEGA, Kenya (AP) -- Smeared with traditional ointments that supposedly
protect him from harm, a brown-and-white dappled bull named Itionyi charged onto
the field and warily approached his opponent, another bull dubbed Chui.
</P>
<P>
	   Itionyi's supporters, intoxicated by a night of smoking marijuana and
drinking a home-distilled corn liquor, tightened their circle around the two
combatants. They blew clouds of the pungent smoke at their 750-pound hero --
hoping the dope would give him an edge in the fight.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is good, it gives him a lot of courage and stamina,'' said Henry
Bicha, Itionyi's owner, who had wagered $28 his bull would win. Bicha was
risking more than money -- Chui had killed three of his bulls in previous fights
and his already tattered pride was at stake
</P>
<P>
	   Prestige and the need for diversion from grindingly difficult lives are
fueling the growth of bullfighting in western Kenya. But bull owners and zealous
fans also believe the sport has a rosy commercial future as a draw for tourists
in this East African nation.
</P>
<P>
	   All those motives were evident when, with a squeaky fanfare from a battered
trumpet, Bicha recently summoned the residents of Khayega, a town 185 miles
northwest of the capital Nairobi, to watch his bull challenge Chui, the reigning
local champion.
</P>
<P>
	   Itionyi and Chui, their horns sharpened for combat, circled each other as
the crowd of men and boys surged to within three feet of the hulking animals.
Bicha's five-year-old bull lunged at Chui, locking his shorter horns with his
foe's longer ones.
</P>
<P>
	   They withdrew and circled each other, scraping the ground with their hoofs
and grunting. They then slammed into each other once more.
</P>
<P>
	   In less than 10 minutes, it was over. To the roar of the crowd -- and the
moan of losing bettors -- Itionyi knocked the champ on his back. The
seven-year-old Chui struggled to his feet and ran off defeated.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The ground was slippery, that's why my bull fell down,'' said Alfred
Milimo, Chui's humiliated owner.
</P>
<P>
	   Chui was consigned to the ranks of a has-been, perhaps to fight again one
day. Bulls who are impaled on the horn of their opponent and die go straight to
the butcher, later to adorn the tables of village elders.
</P>
<P>
	   Peter Mboyi, an official for the unofficial Federation of Bullfighting, said
the sport, with proper marketing, could become a big tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
	   ``What we need is to have rules governing the sport and make it safer for
the fans to watch. We're against the habit of the fans getting so close to the
bulls when they are fighting,'' he said, noting that over-enthusiastic,
over-intoxicated spectators have been gored.
</P>
<P>
	   Rogers Mulilio, who is researching bullfighting in the region around
Khayega, traced the start of the sport to the early 1900s.
</P>
<P>
	   British colonial officials first introduced wrestling to the Luhya, Kenya's
second-largest tribe. But rivalries between wrestlers of different clans
threatened to spill over into wider violence. So after World War I, the British
brought in bullfighting.
</P>
<P>
	   Even without betting, bullfighting is treated with the utmost seriousness.
Owners and trainers are not permitted to have sexual relations with women the
night before the fight.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It is a bad omen. The bull can be knocked down by a vehicle or something
else nasty can happen,'' Bicha explained.
</P>
<P>
	   Women remain on the periphery of the fighting, but they are the first to
celebrate victory with special bullfighting songs. The cultivation, sale and use
of marijuana are illegal in Kenya, but that doesn't stop people from indulging.
</P>
<P>
	   Until about two years ago, bullfights were held only to mark special
occasions. Today, the timing of big fights coincides with the period from
Christmas to the opening of school in mid-January when Luyhas who work in
Nairobi or in the Indian Ocean port of Mombasa return home for the holidays.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0130 </TRAILER>
