<HEADLINE> No. 3 NC State 62, Florida St. 58  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- North Carolina State keyed on Florida State's
Latavia Coleman on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
	   It almost backfired.
</P>
<P>
	   The Wolfpack held Coleman to six points, but April Traylor scored 23 and
Brooke Wyckoff added 12 points and 10 rebounds as the Seminoles gave
third-ranked North Carolina State a scare before falling 62-58.
</P>
<P>
	   Kaayla Chones and Tynesha Lewis scored 17 points each for North Carolina
State.
</P>
<P>
	   "To be in a position to win that basketball game against the third-ranked
team in the country shows the strides that we've made, especially with Tay only
scoring six points," Florida State coach Sue Semrau said. "I thought they really
keyed on her. And now you see that we have a really balanced team where a lot of
different people can score. We have a lot of different weapons."
</P>
<P>
	   The Seminoles (7-5, 0-2 ACC) erased a 12-point deficit in the second half,
tying the game 58-58 before fading down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
	   "What are we going to gain by getting all worried about them being the third
team in the country?" Wyckoff asked. "April said it all night, 'We have nothing
to lose."'
</P>
<P>
	   N.C. State's Summer Erb, held to six points and three rebounds, fouled out
with 1:18 remaining. Levys Torres, fouled on the play, made both free throws to
tie it 58-58.
</P>
<P>
	   Chones put the Wolfpack (13-0, 4-0) ahead 60-58 with a short jumper and
Florida State failed to keep pace when Angela Sutton missed two free throws with
47 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
	   Coleman gave the Seminoles one more shot, tying up a loose ball after N.C.
State's Terah James missed the front end of a 1-and-1 with 23 seconds left. But
Coleman couldn't handle a pass from Lakesha Springle on the next possession, and
Lewis sealed the outcome with two foul shots with 4.5 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
	   Traylor scored 11 points in a 16-4 run that tied the score at 56-56.
</P>
<P>
	   "She led us in a great way tonight," Semrau said.
</P>
