<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Farmers' Price for Raw Milk Drops  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) -- The basic price U.S. dairy farmers received for raw
milk fell in December to the lowest price since 1978, the Wisconsin Agriculture
Statistics Service reports.
</P>
<P>
	   The fall to $9.63 in December from $9.79 per 100 pounds in November can be
attributed to increased milk production, primarily on farms in the western
United States, said Ed Jesse, a dairy economist at the University of
Wisconsin-Madison.
</P>
<P>
	   Jesse said Thursday he does not expect prices to rebound to levels seen
during the last two years, believing raw milk prices will stay around $10 for
the first three months of 2000 before climbing to $13 later in the year.
</P>
<P>
	   "The $16 price, I think, is gone for a while," Jesse said. "We put in a
production engine that is pretty hard to slow down once prices drop. The good
news is we have bottomed out for the year and prices have only one place to
head."
</P>
<P>
	   Darwin Lawson, who milks 72 cows near Darlington, Wis., said he expected the
raw-milk price would drop but only to perhaps $11 per hundredweight, or about 12
gallons.
</P>
<P>
	   With premiums for the quality of his milk, he earned just shy of $20 per
hundredweight at times last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We had a good year last year," Lawson said. "We just hope the price doesn't
stay way down there too long. If it does, we will do like the hog farmer did
last year: Give up."
</P>
<P>
	   The basic formula price of $9.63 is the lowest since $9.33 per hundredweight
in July 1978, said SuAnn Hollewell, a dairy statistician for the Agricultural
Statistics Service in Madison.
</P>
<P>
	   Through November 1999, milk production was up 1 percent in Wisconsin
compared with the same period in the previous year, while nationally production
was up 3.4 percent, Hollewell said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The western production is really what is driving the downward trend in milk
prices right now," she said.
</P>
<P>
	   --------
</P>
<P>
	   WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Frustrated over lack of control over their checkoff
dollars, Kansas farmers are seeking to privatize the state's commodity
commissions.
</P>
<P>
	   At stake is who decides how to spend the $8 million earmarked for research,
market development, promotion and education for the four major crops grown in
Kansas.
</P>
<P>
	   The governor now appoints the members of the four commissions that regulate
checkoff dollars farmers pay on wheat, grain sorghum, corn and soybeans. Farmers
want to elect their own commissioners to administer the funds.
</P>
<P>
	   Also at issue is who gets to keep the $400,000 in interest earnings from the
checkoff program, said Greg Krissek, assistant secretary at the Department of
Agriculture.
</P>
<P>
	   That interest now goes into the state's general fund. Farmers contend that
all the money, including the interest earnings, should go back to the commodity
commissions.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are some people saying, and arguing, that it is not really the
state's money. It is the farmers' money and the commodity commission should be
able to utilize it," said Dennis Morrice, executive director of the Kansas
Soybean Association.
</P>
<P>
	   The farmers' proposal -- which has the support of the Kansas Department of
Agriculture and Gov. Bill Graves -- will be put before the Legislature this
session, Krissek said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
