<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    Friday, Jan. 7, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Republicans Debate Gays in Military
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   DURHAM, N.H. (AP) -- At a campaign debate in New Hampshire on Thursday, GOP
presidential contenders had an incendiary exchange over gays in the military.
Gary Bauer said that Democratic stance that homosexuals should serve openly
would further the "radical homosexual agenda," and an animated Alan Keyes said,
"I will return to the ban on homosexuals in the military." Said frontrunner
George W. Bush, "I'm a don't ask, don't tell man." The Clinton administration's
policy, which the president has said has not worked well, is to allow gay
service members if they do not make their sexual orientation known. John McCain
said that policy could be fine-tuned, but he added, "I cannot change a policy
that's working."
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Police Use Tear Gas on Protesters
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- More than 50 officers in riot gear used tear gas to disperse
hundreds of people protesting the U.S. government's decision to return
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez to his father in Cuba. Protesters blocked
intersections and cut off access to the Port of Miami. Police arrested at least
135 people, including two prominent Cuban exile leaders, for refusing to
disperse. The situation was expected to continue Friday. Brothers to the Rescue,
a Miami-based exile group that searches the waters off Florida for Cubans trying
to make it to the United States, called for supporters to drive 15 mph Friday
throughout Miami-Dade County.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Wal-Mart, Web Firm Create New Co.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and a Silicon Valley firm are forming
a new Internet company that will work to enhance the giant retailer's Web site
and bring shoppers online for the first time. Wal-Mart.com Inc. will be an
independent company based in Palo Alto, Calif., with its own board of directors
and management team. The deal between Wal-Mart and Accel was announced late
Thursday. It indicates that Wal-Mart is looking for help as it expands its role
in the competitive e-retailing world. Wal-Mart has operated a Web site since
1996, but its online business has lagged behind Web-only rivals such as
Amazon.com and eToys.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Troops Fan Across Eastern Indonesia
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   AMBON, Indonesia (AP) -- Thousands of soldiers fanned out Thursday across a
group of islands in eastern Indonesia to try to quell violence between Muslims
and Christians that has claimed hundreds of lives in the past 10 days. On Friday
in Jakarta, an estimated 80,000 Muslim demonstrators demanded that the
government end the bloodshed, threatening to declare a holy war in defense of
Islam. The rally, held after morning prayers at National Monument Square across
the street from the presidential palace, followed a series of smaller protests
by Muslims in the capital in recent days.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Clinton Rejoins Mideast Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- President Clinton plunged back into slow-moving
Mideast peace talks Thursday, meeting with Israel's prime minister and the
Syrian foreign minister after face-to-face negotiations between the two sides
ground to a halt. The U.S. aim is a treaty that would exchange the Golan
Heights, a strategic border territory Israel has held for more than three
decades, for diplomatic and economic relations with Syria. Clinton met
separately for an hour each with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Syrian
Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Black Colleges Get Racist Threats
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Predominantly black colleges in Alabama and
Tennessee have received letters threatening the "total destruction of your race"
and bearing the image of the Confederate flag. Letters postmarked Fayetteville,
N.C., were sent to Oakwood College in Huntsville, Alabama A&AMP;M University in
Huntsville, Alabama State University in Montgomery, and Stillman College in
Tuscaloosa. They were also received by Fisk University and Meharry Medical
College in Nashville, Tenn. The anonymous messages said, "Eventually, we'll get
rid of you. The year 2000, the war escalates. ... We promise." Police have
alerted the FBI.
</P>
