<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FSU's Amato Takes N.C. State Job  </HEADLINE>
    By DAVID DROSCHAK AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina State didn't just hire an assistant
coach to be the head football coach for the Wolfpack. They believe Chuck Amato
has been THE assistant.
</P>
<P>
	   Amato left national champion Florida State and the side of Bobby Bowden on
Thursday to accept the head coaching job at his alma mater. He brings years of
experience of running the day-to-day operations of the Seminoles -- who won two
national titles in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're getting a guy who has been running the No. 1 program in America this
decade, the No. 1 program as we sit here right now," Wolfpack athletic director
Les Robinson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bowden, who is 70, agreed with Robinson, saying Amato was given plenty of
duties as his top assistant.
</P>
<P>
	   "He loves responsibility," Bowden said of Amato, who was his assistant head
coach for 14 of Amato's 18 years with the Seminoles. "I threw more on him than
any other coach I've had. He was the assistant head coach and that's exactly
what he was."
</P>
<P>
	   Amato, who inherits a 6-6 team, was given a five-year contract with a base
salary of $185,000 a season.
</P>
<P>
	   Amato, 53, admitted that he had slept a total of only six hours in the past
two days. But he had an overflow crowd of 300 Wolfpack alumni and supporters on
the edge of their seats during his emotional return to his alma mater.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm ready, and I don't care about the scrutiny," said Amato, who has never
been a college head coach. "I'm a tough guy and I don't care."
</P>
<P>
	   Amato said he met with Robinson in Charlotte on Wednesday, and the two
finalized the deal at 2 a.m. Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wanted to make sure that they wanted to make the investment," Amato said.
"Poor Les, he didn't realize I had that many questions for him because I had
never been a head coach before. But I have been at this for some time, and every
year I would write a question down. So, I had about 62 of them.
</P>
<P>
	   "I like to look people in the eye to see how they answer questions, to see
their reaction. But I don't think there's any question North Carolina State
University wants to be like Virginia Tech, wants to be like Florida State, wants
to be like Nebraska."
</P>
<P>
	   Amato coached at N.C. State from 1972-1980, then spent two years at Arizona
as defensive coordinator before joining Florida State in 1982.
</P>
<P>
	   It took the Wolfpack six weeks to hire a head coach after Robinson fired
Mike O'Cain on Nov. 24 following a 41-40 record in seven seasons.
</P>
<P>
	   But Robinson defended the length of the 43-day search, saying Bowden himself
called early in the process to ask if Amato could be allowed to coach against
Virginia Tech in Tuesday's national title game.
</P>
<P>
	   Robinson granted that wish.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are part of a corporate group bigger than N.C. State called the Atlantic
Coast Conference," Robinson said. "We really pull for each other, and we had a
team playing for the national championship. It helps put money in our pockets.
</P>
<P>
	   "It was that important to them that he coach in that game. Then I got to
thinking, 'How bad would it be for our head coach to have been the assistant
head coach, on national TV, winning the national championship?"'
</P>
<P>
	   Robinson said he talked to about 12 coaches during the long search, but met
with Amato first and offered him the position.
</P>
<P>
	   "There were so many things I liked about him. I wanted somebody to beat
him," Robinson said. "He was put there as a standard. Nobody beat him."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0216 </TRAILER>
