<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parnevik Leads Mercedes by a Stroke  </HEADLINE>
    By DOUG FERGUSON AP Golf Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   KAPALUA, Hawaii (AP) -- Jesper Parnevik always seems to play well in the
British Open, which may be why he felt so comfortable in the vicious trade winds
off the coast of Maui for the Mercedes Championship.
</P>
<P>
	   Tiger Woods seems to play well anywhere, which explains why he's in
contention once again.
</P>
<P>
	   While the average score for the first round was 75.03, Parnevik scratched
out nine birdies -- along with a bogey and back-to-back double bogeys -- for a
4-under 69 in the first round of the first tournament of the year.
</P>
<P>
	   "Similar winds to Carnoustie," Parnevik said. "It was a three-, four-,
five-club wind. Those conditions, you can't think about the swing or anything
like that. You just try to get the ball around the golf course and hope for the
best."
</P>
<P>
	   Players did well Thursday to throw out the yardage book, too. Duffy Waldorf
found that out when his 5-iron from 175 yards wound up 50 yards short, and his
full sand wedge on the next shot didn't make it to the green, either.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought I was never going to get to the hole," said Waldorf, one shot
back after a 70.
</P>
<P>
	   Woods, meanwhile, didn't skip a beat after ending the 1999 season on a
spectacular note, winning the last four PGA Tour events and finishing no worse
than seventh in 13 of his last 14 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
	   Despite a bogey on the 17th and missing a birdie opportunity on the
downwind, par-5 18th, Woods still managed a 71 and was two shots out of the
lead, along with Ernie Els. Defending champion David Duval birdied the last two
holes and was among those at 72.
</P>
<P>
	   "You hit some clubs some distances that you're not quite used to," Woods
said. "These conditions, you just have to keep plugging away."
</P>
<P>
	   With gusts up to 40 mph -- and more expected today for the second round --
only eight players managed to break par. That's a stark contrast from a year
ago, when only three players failed to break par on the Plantation Course at
Kapalua.
</P>
<P>
	   That's not the only change.
</P>
<P>
	   A year ago, Duval used the Mercedes as a springboard to topple Woods as No.
1 in the world, winning by nine strokes with a score of 26-under. This kind of
wind won't allow for anyone to come close to that score.
</P>
<P>
	   And this year, Duval and the rest of the PGA Tour are trying to catch up to
Woods.
</P>
<P>
	   "You're never surprised to see his name on the board now," Waldorf said.
"He's playing at a level that not many have reached out here. All of us have
played at that level, but not for very long."
</P>
<P>
	   A victory at Kapalua would be his fifth in a row, the longest streak since
Ben Hogan won five straight tournaments in 1953.
</P>
<P>
	   "He has to screw up pretty bad not to be up on the leader board," Parnevik
said. "He doesn't have to do everything right to win. And when he does
everything right, he runs away with it."
</P>
<P>
	   Everything went right -- and then everything went wrong -- for Parnevik. He
birdied six of the first 11 holes to open a 4-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
	   "And then the fun began," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   He missed the 12th green and three-putted for double bogey, then missed the
green and dumped a chip shot into the bunker for another double bogey on the
13th. Parnevik birdied the next two holes, then chunked a wedge on No. 17 that
led to a bogey.
</P>
<P>
	   An official on the 18th green announced Parnevik as wearing "the wild red
pants," not uncommon for the most eccentric dresser in golf. But that only
prompted a shout from the gallery.
</P>
<P>
	   "If you knock it in the hole, we don't care what color pants you wear,"
someone yelled.
</P>
<P>
	   Parnevik's putt veered some 20 feet to the left once it reached the green
and grazed the cup, giving him his ninth birdie of the day and a 1-shot lead.
</P>
<P>
	   By that account, Woods was downright boring.
</P>
<P>
	   Wearing his cap backwards at times to keep it from blowing off, Woods rarely
found trouble on the wide-open fairways, and only the tricky grain on the greens
kept him from gaining more ground. He missed eight birdie putts from 15 feet or
in.
</P>
<P>
	   But any round under par was a good day.
</P>
<P>
	   Rich Beem had a 46 on the back for an 84, while Match Play champion Jeff
Maggert and Ted Tryba also had to sign for a score of 80 or worse.
</P>
<P>
	   If Parnevik didn't already wear a hat with the bill flipped up, the trade
winds would have taken care of that. As whitecaps swept across the Pacific Ocean
below and tree limbs appeared to be on the verge of snapping, it was all the
elite field could do to hang on.
</P>
<P>
	   And these conditions are typical of Kapalua.
</P>
<P>
	   "If this is a normal wind and I had this to play, I'd quit," Hal Sutton said
after a 4-over 77. "I couldn't stand up. I don't know what the skinny people
were doing."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0216 </TRAILER>
