<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wolters Chosen for US Women's Team  </HEADLINE>
    By CHUCK SCHOFFNER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Now that she's finally a member of the U.S. women's basketball team, Kara
Wolters still has plenty of incentive.
</P>
<P>
	   All she has to do is look at coach Nell Fortner.
</P>
<P>
	   Fortner, who'll take over as coach of the WNBA's new Indiana Fever following
the Olympics this fall, took Wolters in the league's expansion draft last month.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolters, added to the national team by USA Basketball on Thursday, doesn't
want to let her down.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it says a lot knowing that she leaves me with the U.S. team and
also drafted me to Indiana," said Wolters, who was an All-American at
Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's definitely a confidence thing. To know that a coach, who's a great
coach, is that positive and confident in me, that really means a lot to me and
it makes me want to work even harder for her and for the team."
</P>
<P>
	   Wolters, a 6-foot-7 center, has been practicing with the team since
September. She became its 11th member, leaving one more spot to be filled. The
team, which resumes training in Miami tonight, is expected to become the Olympic
team next summer.
</P>
<P>
	   The selection committee was impressed with Wolters' most striking feature --
her size.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it's a very good day for our team," Fortner said. "Kara has so much
USA Basketball experience. She brings a different element to the floor with her
size that we need on this team."
</P>
<P>
	   Wolters, who played for Fortner on the 1998 world championship team, has
averaged three points and 2.3 rebounds in 15 games with the national team, which
will leave for a European tour later this month. She played with the WNBA's
Houston Comets last season.
</P>
<P>
	   Her selection means that two of the game's premier players, Cynthia Cooper
and Sheryl Swoopes, are still not on the U.S. team. Cooper, who has led the
Houston Comets to all three WNBA championships, withdrew from the national team
in October.
</P>
<P>
	   Swoopes played on the 1996 Olympic team. Cooper played in the 1988 and 1992
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
	   Karen Stromme, who chairs the selection committee, said the group will
discuss candidates for the 12th spot on the team in a conference call next week.
But she said the committee might not make a decision then.
</P>
<P>
	   "Training time is vital," Stromme said. "We would like to as soon as the
committee feels it could reach a unanimous decision. The sooner the better.
However, not at the expense of making a decision just to get somebody to train."
</P>
<P>
	   Stromme said the committee has a "short list" of players it is considering,
but would not reveal any names.
</P>
<P>
	   "There's a lot of very talented players," she said. "But our committee's
challenge is not necessarily to put an All-Star team together, but rather the
best team that's going to win in Sydney."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
