<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Andre Reed Criticizes Bills on Web  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ORCHARD PARK, N.Y. (AP) -- Buffalo Bills wide receiver Andre Reed is an
angry man. He's angry at management over his diminished role on the team, and
he's even angry at benched quarterback Doug Flutie.
</P>
<P>
	   Reed, who said in early December that the best thing for him would be to
keep his mouth shut about his lack of playing time, apparently no longer feels
that way.
</P>
<P>
	   The 15-year veteran of four Super Bowls let his feelings boil over again on
his Internet site. His journal on Tuesday revealed more disappointment, and it
came only two days after he moved into second place on the NFL list of career
receptions with 945, behind only Jerry Rice of the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
	   "It wasn't just a happy moment for me, but also frustration," Reed wrote.
"The five balls that I did catch weren't even routes, and that just makes me
look bad, like they have to give me charity throws. They've just been throwing
me bones to keep me happy, but I'm not happy at all.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think the franchise realizes that, and they know that I don't want to be
here anymore," Reed continued. "You look at the game Monday night with Jerry in
San Francisco. The 49ers still respect Jerry, and whether it was his last game
in that uniform or not, I think he went out the way he wanted to.
</P>
<P>
	   "Here, they haven't given me that freedom and respect. I'm sure San
Francisco wouldn't do that to Jerry Rice. It'll be a chip on my shoulder for a
long, long time. I think I can start fresh somewhere else and offer a team
something next year and hopefully go out the way I want to."
</P>
<P>
	   Reed also passed former Seattle Seahawks star Steve Largent and took over
fourth place on the NFL's yards receiving list with 13,095. Coach Wade Phillips
said that getting Reed the records was one of the goals, but that did little to
placate the veteran star.
</P>
<P>
	   "People around here think that I'm retiring, and that Sunday was my last
game, but it wasn't!" Reed wrote. "At this point I just want to go where I'm
appreciated and respected, and I haven't had that here."
</P>
<P>
	   Reed also said he hopes the Bills give him his unconditional release after
the playoffs, and thinks they will.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's obvious I'm not in their future plans, and I can't subject my family
or myself to that anymore. It's time for me to move on. Believe me, I'll be
happier. I was not a happy football player this year; it was very miserable
going to work every day."
</P>
<P>
	   Reed finished the season with 52 catches for 536 yards and only one
touchdown, and his longest reception was 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
	   With the emergence of Eric Moulds, who led the team with 65 catches for 994
yards and seven touchdowns, and the promise of rookie Peerless Price (31 catches
for 393 yards and three TDs), Reed's frustration at playing a minor role now is
understandable.
</P>
<P>
	   But with at least one more game to play this season -- on Saturday at
Tennessee -- Reed still planned on playing a prominent role, even if it isn't
running routes and catching important passes.
</P>
<P>
	   "Hopefully, we're on a winning note next week!" he wrote. "It's a 12-team
tournament now. I think a lot of the young guys will be looking to Thurman
Thomas, Bruce Smith and myself (for leadership), and I'm glad I can be looked to
in that regard."
</P>
<P>
	   Reed also vented on offensive coordinator Joe Pendry and Flutie, who has
been replaced by Rob Johnson for Saturday's game after starting the first 15
games of the season.
</P>
<P>
	   "You may have heard that I am not on speaking terms with Doug Flutie," Reed
wrote. "Doug Flutie has changed as a person over one year, and Joe Pendry has
had a plan for me from Day 1. You don't do that to people because it comes back
to bite you."
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Flutie's Internet journal dealt with his benching, and there was
no grousing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I definitely want to be in the game and help us get to the Super Bowl,"
Flutie wrote. "But I unconditionally accept the decision Coach Phillips has
made."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0222 </TRAILER>
