<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Titans Look To Finally Beat Buffalo  </HEADLINE>
    By TERESA M. WALKER AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee Titans safety Marcus Robertson, with 150
stitches in his face following a motorcycle crash, still wants to play in the
AFC playoffs Saturday against the Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
	   "I want to be out there because this team is the best team I've been a part
of, and I think our chances to win the Super Bowl are good," Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
	   "It doesn't happen very often, and it's been five years since we've been to
the playoffs. I know it's my opportunity right now to try to seize the moment."
</P>
<P>
	   The Titans won a franchise-record 13 games this season, and their 13-3
record is the best ever not to win a division. The Titans will play host to
Buffalo (11-5) Saturday in a game that already has a place in NFL history for
having two teams with the most combined wins in a wild-card game.
</P>
<P>
	   Bills defensive end Bruce Smith said it was disappointing that Buffalo and
Tennessee didn't have easier opponents to open the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm sure both teams are going to give the fans their money's worth," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Saturday's game will be the first time these teams have met in the playoffs
since that infamous 38-35 overtime game on Jan. 3, 1993, when the Houston Oilers
(who later moved to Tennessee) blew a 32-point lead to the Bills. Fans recently
voted it the league's fifth-most memorable game.
</P>
<P>
	   Only six former Oilers remain on the roster for Tennessee, and they have
been answering questions about that game all week. They all agree that the game
is ancient history.
</P>
<P>
	   "I liken it to when I was in the seventh grade, the first year I ever played
tackle football," left guard Bruce Matthews said. "I broke my leg, and it hurt
bad. God gives you the ability to lock out ugly, negative things in your life. I
guess that's what happened with that."
</P>
<P>
	   If the Titans get that kind of lead again, they won't blow it this time.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think we could make the outcome a little different this go-around,"
Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
	   Smith admitted that the game, which sent the Bills onto their third straight
Super Bowl appearance, isn't something he thinks of much. He thinks Buffalo's
defense, the best in the NFL, will be too busy dealing with a Titans offense
that has topped 40 points in each of its last two games.
</P>
<P>
	   McNair finally has found his rhythm, throwing six TD passes in his last five
quarters, and the Titans went 7-2 against the NFL's best defenses.
</P>
<P>
	   If the Titans take a lead, Smith expects them to use Eddie George, who ran
for 1,304 yards this season, to play keepaway.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're going to make sure we play the most disciplined game we've ever had
to play with these two guys in the backfield," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Bills will take the field with Rob Johnson at quarterback instead of the
benched Doug Flutie. Johnson, who will be making his first playoff start, was
impressive Sunday in throwing for 287 yards against the Indianapolis Colts.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson said he was glad Tennessee had only one game film to study him.
Titans safety Blaine Bishop said their lack of familiarity with Johnson easily
counters Flutie's ability to create magic.
</P>
<P>
	   "From one game, it's kind of hard to say what Rob Johnson likes to do, what
he leans on when it gets tough. So it will be very interesting," Bishop said.
</P>
<P>
	   It won't be easy with Adelphia Coliseum sold out and fans in a frenzy over
the first playoff game in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
	   Titans rookie end Jevon Kearse, who led the AFC with 14 1/2 sacks, said the
game offers Tennessee a chance to prove the franchise can play against Buffalo
in the playoffs. Houston was 0-2 in its previous two playoff games with the
Bills.
</P>
<P>
	   "We owe it to the organization," Kearse said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
