<DOCNO> APW20000107.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Seahawks' Kennedy Ready for Playoffs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    KIRKLAND, Wash. (AP) -- In his 10 pro seasons, Cortez Kennedy of the Seattle
Seahawks has been the NFL Defensive Player of the Year, an eight-time Pro Bowl
defensive tackle and has earned more money than he can possibly spend.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, this Sunday will be special. After 151 regular-season games, Kennedy
will play in his first playoff game when the Seahawks meet the Miami Dolphins in
the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
	   "I never in my life have had so many ticket requests," Kennedy said. "That's
one of the reasons why I'm not answering my phone this week."
</P>
<P>
	   Kennedy was the third player chosen in the 1990 draft, after quarterback
Jeff George by Indianapolis and running back Blair Thomas by the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1992, when Kennedy was the NFL Defensive Player of the Year, the Seahawks
won a franchise-low two games. He played so well and so hard that he stood out
on a 2-14 team.
</P>
<P>
	   Mike Holmgren, Seattle's first-year coach, is Kennedy's fourth with the
Seahawks. He played two seasons under Chuck Knox, three under Tom Flores and
four under Dennis Erickson before Holmgren arrived from Green Bay in January.
</P>
<P>
	   "It feels great," said a smiling Kennedy. "Usually, I'm talking about going
deer hunting right now. Well, I can put that on hold. I can't wait until Sunday.
This is 50 times better than going to the Pro Bowl. I can't imagine how I'm
going to feel when I step on the field Sunday. This is something I've been
waiting on a long time."
</P>
<P>
	   It almost didn't happen. After 10 games, the Seahawks were 8-2 with a
five-game winning streak and a three-game lead in the AFC West.
</P>
<P>
	   Then they lost five of their final six games in a tailspin that almost cost
them the second division title in team history. They reached the playoffs last
Sunday when Kansas City lost in overtime to Oakland after the Seahawks were
beaten 19-9 by the New York Jets.
</P>
<P>
	   "I can't wait to get that bad taste out of my mouth," Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kennedy is popular with his teammates and well-liked by players on opposing
teams.
</P>
<P>
	   Russell Maryland, one of his best friends and a former college teammate at
Miami, is a defensive tackle with Oakland who helped beat the Chiefs and get
Kennedy and the Seahawks into the playoffs. He plans to be in the Kingdome on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   Kennedy has been making some phone calls himself this week. He placed a call
to Chiefs defensive tackle Chester McGlockton, an old friend who used to play
with the Raiders, to needle him unmercifully about Kansas City missing the
playoffs. All in good humor, of course.
</P>
<P>
	   "I won't mess with Russell about not going to the playoffs," Kennedy added.
</P>
<P>
	   Kennedy, a Pro Bowler again this season, and Pro Bowl linebacker Chad Brown
were elected captains of Seattle's defense for the playoffs. It's an honor the
low-key Kennedy didn't seek, but it's a responsibility he knows he needs to
fulfill.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't like to be thought of as a leader. But, hey, this is OK. This is
the time I need to step up. But I don't believe at yelling at anybody. I'll tell
the guys, 'You know what you have to do.' I don't have to be ranting and
screaming," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Kennedy is turning over his $16,000 paycheck for Sunday's game to two
charities close: the Jerome Brown and Payne Stewart foundations. Brown, also a
defensive tackle, played with Kennedy at Miami and died in a car accident in
1992, while Stewart, a top golfer, died in a plane crash last year. Stewart's
agent, Robert Fraley, who also was Kennedy's agent, also died in the crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0225 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
