<DOCNO> APW20000107.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys Hope Healthy Deion Will Help  </HEADLINE>
    By JAIME ARON AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   IRVING, Texas (AP) -- Without a healthy Deion Sanders to cover Randy Moss or
Cris Carter, the Minnesota Vikings have had no problem torching the Dallas
Cowboys' secondary.
</P>
<P>
	   Sanders hopes things will be different Sunday now that he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm better this time," Sanders said. "I think it will allow us to do more
things and not just sit back and wait on what they're going to do. We'll be able
to force them into situations.
</P>
<P>
	   "But even if you had Lester Hayes and Mike Haynes, I don't know if you'd
have enough talent to match up with those guys."
</P>
<P>
	   Moss caught three touchdown passes totaling 163 yards and Carter had seven
catches for 135 yards as Minnesota beat Dallas 46-36 on Thanksgiving 1998.
Sanders missed that game with a toe injury that required offseason surgery.
</P>
<P>
	   In November, the NFL's most productive tandem combined for 15 catches, three
touchdowns and 207 yards as the Vikings scored the final 27 points after falling
behind 17-0. Sanders, considered the NFL's best cover cornerback, limped through
the game with hamstring and groin problems.
</P>
<P>
	   The stakes are higher for Round 3.
</P>
<P>
	   This time, it's a first-round playoff game.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm going to do my best," Sanders said, smiling. "We're going to have a
good time."
</P>
<P>
	   While fans would love to see Sanders and Moss go head-to-head on every snap,
Dallas coaches won't allow it. They prefer mixing up their coverages to avoid
being predictable.
</P>
<P>
	   Still, Sanders mostly will line up on the right side of the defense, often
before Minnesota is out of its huddle. Once quarterbacks stand over the center,
they make sure to find Sanders.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeff George sure did two months ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the 15 times Sanders lined up against Moss, George went that way only
twice. The matchup was a draw as Sanders knocked down a long pass and Moss had
an 8-yard catch.
</P>
<P>
	   "Deion's unbelievable," George said. "When he's not healthy, he's
unbelievable. Just his presence on the field is unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
	   "But that doesn't mean you shy away from the guy. We have every bit of
confidence in our receivers and our running game."
</P>
<P>
	   The respect teams show Sanders shifts pressure to the other side of the
field. And that's where Dallas has been vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
	   Injuries to would-be starter Kevin Smith and top backup Kevin Mathis have
increased the playing time of converted safety Charlie Williams and undrafted
rookie Duane Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
	   Although whoever is out there gets help from a safety, it's not always
enough.
</P>
<P>
	   The back of Williams' jersey is all over the videotape from the last game
against the Vikings, especially on Moss' big plays. Teams also have started
picking on Hawthorne, who is listed generously at 5-foot-10.
</P>
<P>
	   The good news for the Cowboys is that Smith and Mathis both might be back
for the first time since the previous Vikings game. Each has been in and out of
the lineup since then.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought the guys who were on the field the two previous times were not
healthy," Dallas coach Chan Gailey said. "So even if Kevin Smith and Kevin
Mathis don't make it back, at least the guys who are on the field will be 100
percent. We'll gain an advantage there. Then if we get either of those guys
back, it'll help our chances of being able to match up."
</P>
<P>
	   Sanders is glad to have help and he's happy to be healthy himself.
</P>
<P>
	   But there's one more thing he'd like to see.
</P>
<P>
	   "I wish our offense would let that clock tick down to the last second before
we snap every ball," he said, "because the more you keep those guys off the
field, the less opportunities they have."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0069 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Johnson May Coach Final Game  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    SEATTLE (AP) -- If Jimmy Johnson and Dan Marino are closing out their Miami
careers, they'd rather it not happen on Sunday when the Dolphins and Seattle
Seahawks -- each with five losses in their last six games -- meet in the NFL
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   "Somebody is going to have a real good news conference come next Monday,"
said Johnson, who is in his fourth season as coach of the Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
	   Said Marino: "We're disappointed. Now, we feel we've got a reprieve."
</P>
<P>
	   The Seahawks (9-7) and the Dolphins (9-7) both reached the playoffs on the
final day of the season, when they both lost for the fifth time in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seahawks' 19-9 loss to the New York Jets last Sunday put the Dolphins in
the playoffs and apparently dropped Seattle out of them. Then, 50 minutes later,
Kansas City lost in overtime to Oakland, and the Seahawks were in.
</P>
<P>
	   When the AFC West champion Seahawks and the wild-card Dolphins meet, it will
be the final game in the Kingdome, which is being torn down for a new football
stadium.
</P>
<P>
	   The Seahawks are in the playoffs for the first time since 1988, ending the
longest playoff drought in the league. The Dolphins haven't won a playoff game
on the road since 1974.
</P>
<P>
	   The Dolphins, who won seven of eight in the first half of this season, lost
to the Jets 38-31 at home and 21-10 at Washington in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
	   "Obviously, I'd like to have 11 or 12 wins. We don't. We've got nine wins.
But we're in the playoffs," said Johnson, who won two Super Bowls in five
seasons as coach of the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
	   "We feel we're a better team than our record," said Marino, who is still
looking to win his first Super Bowl in his 17 seasons with the Dolphins. "We let
it slip for awhile."
</P>
<P>
	   Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren, who previously coached at Green Bay, has never
lost a playoff game at home. If he extends that record to 6-0, Sunday's game
might be the last for Johnson and Marino.
</P>
<P>
	   Marino might choose to retire and Johnson might step away from coaching. He
also is the team's general manager.
</P>
<P>
	   Marino faced the Seahawks in the playoffs as a rookie in 1983 and again in
1984. He likes his team's chances against a Seattle team that went in reverse
after going 8-2.
</P>
<P>
	   "If we win three games, we're in the Super Bowl," said Marino, who played
and lost in the 1985 Super Bowl against San Francisco. "When we play well, we
can beat anybody."
</P>
<P>
	   And Johnson said: "I like our chances."
</P>
<P>
	   A lot of teams liked their chances in the final six weeks against the
Seahawks. Jon Kitna, in his first season as a full-time starting quarterback,
threw 10 interceptions during those six games and couldn't produce a touchdown
in two of them.
</P>
<P>
	   Against the Jets, the Seahawks had to settle for three field goals by Todd
Peterson.
</P>
<P>
	   Ricky Watters, Seattle's running back, started against the Jets despite a
sprained right knee and had 30 yards on nine carries. Holmgren, probably fearing
that Ahman Green would fumble the ball in a crucial situation, gave Watters'
backup one carry.
</P>
<P>
	   Watters' knee is still bothering him and Holmgren said he won't be 100
percent for the Dolphins' game.
</P>
<P>
	   "I've got to be more cautious with the football in these playoff games and
understand that's what wins them," said Kitna, thinking past Miami.
</P>
<P>
	   Kitna hopes to get a lot more help from Watters, but conceded that might not
happen. So he's prepared to pass the ball more often this week.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not going to say, 'Wow, we need the running game to win,' " Kitna said.
"I don't think that's the case. Certainly that helps you win. But when you throw
the ball 45 times, you have to be more efficient and I wasn't efficient in the
later parts of the third quarter or the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
	   "You have to be more efficient and use the passing game as the running game.
But it sure makes things easier if you have the running game going."
</P>
<P>
	   Sunday's game will be a homecoming for Dolphins backup quarterback Damon
Huard, who played at the University of Washington. Damon's younger brother,
Brock, another former Huskies quarterback, is a rookie with the Seahawks, but
won't be active for the game because he's the third-string quarterback behind
Kitna and Glenn Foley.
</P>
<P>
	   The Huard brothers will have 25 family members, including their parents and
friends, in the Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
	   Damon Huard got five starts when Marino was sidelined with a neck injury
this season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0227 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0070 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Housing Raise Proposed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) -- Lance Cpl. Matt Alandt ran into a stark
reality when he transferred to Camp Pendleton and sought off-base housing with
his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
	   Rent for a two-bedroom apartment in Oceanside, north of San Diego, was $725.
His monthly housing stipend from the Marine Corps was $623.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's pretty tough,'' said Alandt, 21, of Boise, Idaho, who moved back on
base this year. ``You live paycheck to paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
	   Relief may be on the way for the more than half of the 1.4 million members
of the military who receive monthly stipends for off-base housing. Defense
Secretary William Cohen said Thursday that the Clinton administration will look
to spend $3 billion over five years to end a requirement that military members
pay 15 percent of their off-base housing costs.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can never pay you what you're worth to this country,'' Cohen told the
Marines at Camp Pendleton. But ``we can pay you more than we have been paying.''
</P>
<P>
	   The proposal, part of the president's 2001 military budget request, is part
of a campaign to make military life more attractive by increasing pay and
benefits. In recent years, the Pentagon has had trouble recruiting new members
and retaining those already in uniform.
</P>
<P>
	   Cohen reminded the Marines that their base pay rose 4.8 percent on Jan. 1,
and that many will get additional increases of as much as 5.5 percent on July 1.
He said he also would seek ways to improve military health care, but gave no
specifics.
</P>
<P>
	   The stipend varies depending on location, rank, marital status and number of
children.
</P>
<P>
	   On-base housing is free, but is in short supply nationwide. And 200,000 of
the 300,000 units are considered substandard and in need of replacement or
repair.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition, many choose to live off-base so spouses can be closer to their
jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   In parts of the country where the cost of living is relatively high, the
housing allowance doesn't go far. At Camp Pendleton, the stipend -- including an
increase for this year -- ranges from $690 per month for a junior enlisted
person with dependents to $1,130 for a top officer.
</P>
<P>
	   Under the plan, Clinton will ask Congress to consider using $160 million to
reduce service members' out-of-pocket costs for off-base housing to an average
15 percent of rent or mortgage. The current average is nearly 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   By 2005, all costs for off-base housing would be paid by the government,
with the Pentagon budget setting aside $3 billion to cover the costs.
</P>
<P>
	   That would translate into an additional $111 per month for corporals at
Pendleton and about $175 a month more for staff sergeants.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We can't have the best military in the world unless we keep the quality of
people that you represent,'' Cohen said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0228 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0072 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relief Sought on Off-Base Housing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMP PENDLETON, Calif. (AP) -- Lance Cpl. Matt Alandt ran into a stark
reality when he transferred to Camp Pendleton and sought off-base housing with
his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
	   Rent for a two-bedroom apartment in Oceanside, north of San Diego, was $725.
His monthly housing stipend from the Marine Corps was $623.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's pretty tough,'' said Alandt, 21, of Boise, Idaho, who moved back on
