<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China: 15,000 Killed in Quake  </HEADLINE>
   By ELAINE KURTENBACH Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- Thirty years ago, a powerful earthquake struck in the dead
of a winter's night, killing 15,621 people in southern China. But the
devastation remained hidden until survivors gathered this week to mourn the
dead.
</P>
<P>
	   Breaking three decades of silence, several state-run newspapers reported
today that the Jan. 5, 1970, earthquake that struck a relatively isolated part
of Yunnan province with a magnitude of 7.7 had been covered up by authorities
amid the chaos of the ultraleftist Cultural Revolution.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time of the quake, the official Xinhua News Agency ran a brief report
noting that it had occurred but it reported a lower magnitude and omitted
information on casualties and damage, the Beijing Morning Post newspaper
reported.
</P>
<P>
	   Today, keeping such information secret would be difficult due to loosening
controls and greater ease of communication throughout the country. The communist
leadership still keeps tight control, however, over information it considers
sensitive.
</P>
<P>
	   The death toll of 15,621 from the quake in Tonghai county in Yunnan would
make it China's third most deadly this century. The worst was the July 28, 1976,
7.8 to 8.2 magnitude earthquake in the eastern city of Tangshan, which killed
240,000. A magnitude 8.6 quake on Dec. 16, 1920 killed 100,000 people in the
northwestern province of Gansu.
</P>
<P>
	   The Beijing Morning Post report noted that at the time of the 1970 quake,
China was isolated from the West and had a policy of refusing outside
assistance. Most of the aid provided from inside the country to victims of the
quake was ``spiritual'' in nature, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the fanatical political atmosphere of the time, news was devoted mainly
to the propaganda purposes of the leftist extremists in charge and to the
glorification of then-Chairman Mao Tse-tung.
</P>
<P>
	   ``After the quake, the disaster area received hundreds of thousands of
copies of the `Quotations of Mao Tse-tung' and Mao statues and 14,350 letters of
condolence, but the amount of material and financial relief was pathetically
small,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The 1970 earthquake devastated seven counties over an area of 5,456 square
miles in central Yunnan, a major tobacco-growing region. Estimated at today's
prices, it caused more than $326.9 million in damage, the report said.
</P>
<P>
	   The first shock was followed by 12 aftershocks of magnitudes ranging from 5
to 5.9, it added.
</P>
<P>
	   News of the quake came to light after the newspaper Yangcheng Evening News
reported that relatives of the victims had gathered on Wednesday in Yuxi city in
Yunnan for a memorial service.
</P>
<P>
	   It was unclear why reports of the deaths and destruction resulting from the
quake did not surface earlier. Although China's media remains entirely state
controlled, in recent years the government has more openly reported about
earthquakes and other disasters, despite continuing to severely restrict access
by foreign journalists to rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
	   In a similar instance, only in recent years have state media reported on the
August 1975 collapse of dams at the Banqiao and Shimantan reservoirs in central
Henan province that drowned 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
	   The communist government has yet to fully account for the greatest calamity
of the Mao era, the Great Famine of the late 1950s and early 1960s that killed
as many as 30 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   That disaster resulted from a premature attempt to establish communism by
collectivizing agriculture and an ill-conceived ``backyard furnace'' program
that led farmers to neglect fields and melt down their tools to make steel.
</P>
<P>
	   The government remains secretive about many issues it considers sensitive or
important for national security. Vaguely worded, arbitrarily enforced laws on
protecting state secrets have been used to jail scores of dissidents,
journalists and others who run afoul of the authorities.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet growing numbers of foreigners live and travel here and many Chinese are
traveling overseas. Wider access to telephones and use of the Internet have also
increased the flow of information.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0252 </TRAILER>
