<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Sees Revived Gays Debate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talk on the Democratic presidential campaign trail about
liberalizing the policy on allowing homosexuals to serve in the military is seen
from inside the Pentagon as little more than that: talk.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Candidates for political office are certainly free to do that and must do
that in order to explain their views to the American people. But I would not
speculate as to what that may or may not mean a year from now,'' Rear Adm. Craig
Quigley, a spokesman for Defense Secretary William Cohen, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Former Sen. Bill Bradley and Vice President Al Gore both had said Wednesday
night they would make sure that homosexuals could serve openly. Gore added a new
twist, however, when he said he would not nominate anyone to the Joint Chiefs of
Staff who did not agree with his position on gays serving.
</P>
<P>
	   Gore has criticized the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, set in law
by Congress in 1993, that permits gays and lesbians to serve as long as they
don't openly state their sexual preferences.
</P>
<P>
	   Presidents don't normally set litmus tests for members of the Joint Chiefs,
whose collective opinions are conveyed to the president by the Joint Chiefs
chairman, by law the president's chief military adviser. A president usually
takes for granted that the four service chiefs will carry out his orders.
</P>
<P>
	   If the next president decided he wanted to change the law on gays in the
military, he almost certainly would face the same firestorm of dissent in
Congress that greeted President Clinton in the early weeks of his first term.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton entered office saying he wanted gays to be allowed to serve openly,
but opposition in Congress and among military leaders left him with no choice
but to accept a compromise.
</P>
<P>
	   In remarks to reporters Thursday, Clinton said he still believes that gays
and lesbians ought to be allowed to serve so long as they obey the Uniform Code
of Military Justice, which prohibits homosexual contact.
</P>
<P>
	   ``So I would like to find some way for people to be honest, to obey the law
and to serve with distinction in the military,'' Clinton said. ``So I think that
is where our focus ought to be, and the next president will have to figure out
how to do that. But I think there will have to be a change in the law now.''
</P>
<P>
	   The Democratic candidates' willingness to loosen strictures on gays in the
military drew animated responses Thursday night as the GOP candidates debated.
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Bauer said the Democratic stance would further the ``radical homosexual
agenda,'' and an Alan Keyes said, ``I will return to the ban on homosexuals in
the military.''
</P>
<P>
	   Texas Gov. George W. Bush said, ``I'm a don't ask, don't tell man.''
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain said the policy could be fine-tuned, but he added, ``I
cannot change a policy that's working.''
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Dugan, who was a member of the Joint Chiefs as head of the Air Force
until September 1990, said in an interview Thursday that he saw no problem with
a president using a litmus test like that suggested by Gore.
</P>
<P>
	   On the other hand, Dugan said, military leaders would expect a president to
put a high priority on maintaining good order and discipline in the military --
a condition that would be undermined, in Dugan's view, if gays were given
special treatment or permitted to flaunt their sexuality in ways that
heterosexuals may not.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the policy is to allow gays in the military to do whatever they want,
(Gore) is going to go through a lot of senior officers before finding someone''
willing to serve on the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Dugan said.
</P>
<P>
	   As it happens, the next president will have little immediate opportunity to
apply any such litmus test anyway, unless he takes the unusual step of firing
the service chiefs when he takes office in January 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Joint Chiefs Chairman Gen. Henry H. Shelton was confirmed by the Senate just
last fall to serve until September 2001, and the vice chairman's post would not
become vacant until spring 2002 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
	   Of the four service chiefs, Air Force Gen. Michael Ryan is due to leave
first, in fall 2001. The Navy's chief, Adm. Jay Johnson, is scheduled to be
replaced this summer and his successor would have just begun a four-year term
when the next commander-in-chief takes office. The Army chief, Gen. Eric
Shinseki, and Marine Corps Commandant Gen. James Jones just started their
four-year terms last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0258 </TRAILER>
