<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 02:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Women Off Welfare Lacking Insurance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Getting off welfare and getting a job can mean losing
health insurance coverage, according to a study of women and children leaving
welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
	   About one-third of women formerly on welfare who went to work had no
insurance. Women who left welfare and didn't work fared worse -- nearly half
lacked insurance, even though many of them should be eligible for Medicaid, the
government health program for the poor, according to the study to be published
Monday in the journal Health Affairs.
</P>
<P>
	   Millions of families have left welfare in the last several years, prodded by
tough new rules and the strong economy. But advocates for the poor worry that
when they lose their monthly welfare checks they also lose government-subsidized
health insurance.
</P>
<P>
	   Most former welfare recipients still qualify for Medicaid, but -- for a
variety of reasons -- many leave the program. There are few statistics available
that show exactly how many have been dropped from Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
	   The Urban Institute study, which examined 1,004 women and 1,662 children who
left welfare between 1995 and 1997, focused on how some people leaving welfare
add to the ranks of the uninsured, which number 44 million people.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Despite the fact that there are several ways to maintain Medicaid
eligibility after leaving welfare, a large percentage of women and children are
losing that coverage and falling through the cracks,'' said co-author John
Holahan, director of the Health Policy Center at the Urban Institute, one of the
sponsors of the study.
</P>
<P>
	   The study found that children previously receiving welfare fared better than
women when it comes to keeping insurance. Forty-seven percent were covered by
Medicaid and 29 percent were covered by private insurance, but 29 percent were
uninsured. The numbers add up to more than 100 percent because some children had
multiple sources of health insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   The study did not examine the reasons why women who get jobs after leaving
welfare don't have health insurance through their employers. The study's authors
said other research shows that former welfare recipients have low-wage jobs that
don't offer insurance or, if insurance is offered, don't pay enough for them to
afford the premiums.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Finding work does not guarantee that a former welfare recipient will also
obtain health care coverage,'' said Bowen Garrett, co-author and research
associate at the Urban Institute.
</P>
<P>
	   The research was part of a project funded by several organizations,
including the Henry J. Kaiser Family.
</P>
<P>
	   The study is the latest evidence that low-income families leaving welfare
are losing insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
	   Auditors at the Health Care Financing Administration, which runs Medicaid,
found that some states are illegally denying benefits to poor families dropped
from the welfare rolls.
</P>
<P>
	   People were losing Medicaid coverage because they were not told they were
eligible, were automatically dropped from computerized Medicaid files when they
got off welfare, or were improperly harassed by caseworkers when they applied
for coverage, auditors said.
</P>
<P>
	   A study last year by Families USA, a liberal consumer group, estimated that
675,000 people lost Medicaid coverage and had no other health insurance in 1997
due to strict new welfare rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0258 </TRAILER>
