<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mideast Talks Peace Talks Lagging  </HEADLINE>
   By DONNA ABU-NASR Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Even with President Clinton intervening, Israel
and Syria remained apart after four days of lagging peace talks, their
face-to-face negotiations at a standstill.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton, who has made Mideast peace a top priority for the final year of his
term, returned here for the third time since the negotiations began Monday in
hopes of quickening the pace of the talks. He planned another trip today.
</P>
<P>
	   The president met separately on Thursday with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, but did not try to bring the
two leaders together for a second three-way meeting, according to White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton left after spending six hours at the semi-secluded conference center
where the delegates are sequestered. Lockhart called the meetings constructive
and ``obviously substantive,'' but did not say whether the president made any
headway.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Both the prime minister and the foreign minister are quite engaged,''
Lockhart said. ``There are a lot of issues on the table. There are a lot of
things that have to be worked through, and it's going to take more than one
afternoon to work on these issues.''
</P>
<P>
	   A source close to the Syrian delegation said Clinton, al-Sharaa and Barak
would hold a three-way meeting today, but there was no confirmation of that from
Israeli or U.S. officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Tensions surfaced early Thursday when the four committees charged with
handling contentious issues failed to convene. Syria is insisting on a meeting
of the working group handling its key demand for a timetable for Israel to
relinquish the Golan Heights, which Syria lost in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
	   The Israelis appeared pleased that the negotiations were focused on peace
terms and security measures, such as installing an early warning system at the
border and clearing it of troops.
</P>
<P>
	   The Syrians have said they were not ready to return home and tell their
people they had disregarded their most important concern -- the land issue --
and addressed only security issues.
</P>
<P>
	   State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said that even though there was no
committee activity Thursday, some of the issues that the committees would
address were taken up substantively in bilateral meetings between the United
States and the two parties.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The feeling is that those meetings have been sufficiently good and
constructive that they have ... superseded committee meetings,'' said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton has assured Israel and Syria he was willing to play a helpful and
consistent role in trying to iron out their differences.
</P>
<P>
	   Although two trips are on his schedule for next week -- to Arizona and Texas
on Monday and Tuesday and to New York on Thursday -- Lockhart said the peace
talks would take precedence.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. aim is a treaty that would exchange the strategic Golan Heights for
diplomatic and economic relations with Syria.
</P>
<P>
	   Marking the end of Ramadan, Islam's holiest month, the White House issued a
presidential message with a prayer for peace.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We pray that the new moon will bring a new era of peace between nations --
in the Middle East and all across the world -- so people can emerge from the
shadows of violence and make better lives for their children,'' Clinton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0301 </TRAILER>
