<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.-North Korean Talks To Resume  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talks designed to pave the way for a high-level North
Korean visit to the United States will resume later this month in Berlin, U.S.
officials say.
</P>
<P>
	   The new round, to begin Jan. 22, was announced by the State Department on
Thursday, a day after a North Korean official raised questions over whether
North Korea was still interested in such a visit. A previous round of talks was
held in Berlin in November.
</P>
<P>
	   A State Department statement said a U.S. delegation led by U.S. envoy
Charles Kartman would meet with a North Korean delegation headed by Vice Foreign
Minister Kim Gye Gwan.
</P>
<P>
	   The discussions have focused on improving ties and North Korea's missile
program.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration has said Pyongyang's agreement in September not to test a
long-range ballistic missile was expected to lead to a visit by a senior North
Korean official.
</P>
<P>
	   However, Chu Chang Jun, North Korea's ambassador to China, told reporters in
Beijing on Wednesday that North Korea had been prepared to send senior officials
to the United States until Washington committed ``acts of betrayal against our
country.''
</P>
<P>
	   He did not elaborate and U.S. officials proceeded with plans for the Berlin
talks and the U.S. visit.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We look forward to hosting a high-level visit at the earliest
opportunity,'' State Department spokesman James Foley said, adding that it was
up to North Korea to designate which official or officials.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We will continue to work on preparations for such a visit when our
bilateral talks resume (in Berlin),'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
	   Separately, Sandy Berger, who is President Clinton's national security
adviser, said the administration puts a high priority on the talks because it
remains concerned about North Korea's missile program.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We want to pursue that very actively,'' he said in an address to the
National Press Club. ``North Korea has a choice. It can either pursue more
normal relations ... or it can continue with its threatening nuclear and missile
programs and continue to be isolated and continue to be contained by the rest of
the world.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're prepared to go down either path,'' Berger said.
</P>
<P>
	   Berger sidestepped a question on a story in Thursday's editions of The
Washington Times that China was continuing to supply materials for North Korea's
long-range missile program despite promises that it would tighten exports of
such technology.
</P>
<P>
	   The latest shipment was made just two weeks ago, through a Hong Kong
company, the newspaper said, quoting a classified Pentagon intelligence report.
</P>
<P>
	   While neither confirming nor denying the report, Berger said, ``We obviously
would not want to see China aiding North Korea's missile program. We've made
that clear to China. I don't think it's in China's interest to have a North
Korea that possesses nuclear weapons and the missile capability to deliver them
at long ranges, since China's fairly close to North Korea.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
