<HEADLINE> NBA Roundup  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Don Nelson might be lucky he only lost Karl Malone's respect.
</P>
<P>
	   Nelson was so upset with Malone and the officials that the 59-year-old
Dallas coach physically confronted the muscular Utah star during the Jazz's
105-92 road victory Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
	   Nelson, who was not available for comment, bumped Malone after the coach was
ejected for arguing about a foul call on Dallas center Shawn Bradley after a
play involving Malone.
</P>
<P>
	   "That's the first time a coach has bumped me in 15 years," Malone said. "I
was taught when I was little to respect my elders, but you're totally out of
line when you get in a player's face. He crossed the line and I have no respect
for that."
</P>
<P>
	   Malone, 6-foot-9 and conservatively listed as 260 pounds, said a fight with
the 6-foot-6 coach would be like a collision between a "Volkswagen and an
18-wheeler."
</P>
<P>
	   In other NBA games, it was Detroit 101, Milwaukee 95; Toronto 101,
Sacramento 89; Minnesota 98, Portland 96; Indiana 102, Denver 97; Cleveland 90,
Golden State 75; and Miami 111, Houston 95.
</P>
<P>
	   Nelson, who said Wednesday that he would step down as coach after the season
to concentrate on his duties as general manager, was ejected with 6:04 left in
the third quarter when he was given a double technical for arguing with referee
Scott Wall.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley was called for a foul against Malone, whose knee struck Bradley's
midsection as the 7-foot-6 center tried to draw a charge.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley was down for several minutes before he was helped to the locker
room. He returned to start the fourth quarter, but was ejected after picking up
his second technical.
</P>
<P>
	   Nelson's son and top assistant, Donnie, took over the team and was hit with
a technical with 4:53 left in the third quarter for going on the court to
protest a no-call.
</P>
<P>
	   "I thought I was going to have to jump on his back and slow him down,"
Donnie Nelson said of his father's confrontation with Malone. "That's what he
is. He's a competitor and he's feisty."
</P>
<P>
	   Utah coach Jerry Sloan also got into the act, drawing two technicals and an
ejection with 3:37 to play in the game.
</P>
<P>
	   Malone led Utah with 24 points and 11 rebounds, Bryon Russell added 20
points, and John Stockton had 12 points and 10 assists. Utah has won five
straight and 11 in a row against Dallas.
</P>
<P>
	   Michael Finley had 30 points for the Mavericks, who've lost nine of 10 and
six in a row at home. Dirk Nowitzki added 24 points, and Cedric Ceballos had 21
points and 14 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Grant Hill scored 19 of his 31 points in the fourth quarter as Detroit
extended its winning streak to six games with a home victory over Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
	   Hill, coming off consecutive 42-point performances in Orlando and Atlanta,
was 13-of-21 from field and had seven assists and five rebounds in 38 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   Christian Laettner added 20 points, and Jerry Stackhouse had 18. Glenn
Robinson led the Bucks with 31.
</P>
<P>
	   Charles Oakley had a season-high 20 points and 16 rebounds as Toronto beat
Sacramento, snapping the visiting Kings' winning streak at four games.
</P>
<P>
	   Doug Christie hit four 3-pointers and had 16 points, and Tracy McGrady added
15 points to help Toronto overcome Vince Carter's second straight subpar
performance since being left off the U.S. Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter, coming off a 13-point effort Tuesday night against Portland, was
7-of-23 from the field and scored 14 points.
</P>
<P>
	   Chris Webber led Sacramento with 27 points and 19 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin Garnett banked in a 10-foot shot with 3.3 seconds left to cap a
27-point performance as Minnesota snapped visiting Portland's winning streak at
six games.
</P>
<P>
	   Malik Sealy tied his season-high with 27 points, and Terrell Brandon had 17
points, 14 assists and eight rebounds. Minnesota is 8-1 in its last nine games
after an eight-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
	   Rasheed Wallace led Portland with 24 points.
</P>
<P>
	   At Cleveland, Lamond Murray scored 20 points as the Cavaliers beat Golden
State, extending the Warriors' losing streak to eight games.
</P>
<P>
	   Rookie Andre Miller had 13 points and seven assists for Cleveland, which
dropped 10 of its previous 11.
</P>
<P>
	   Antawn Jamison led Golden State with 22 points. The Warriors shot a
season-low 31 percent and matched a season-low for points.
</P>
<P>
	   Reggie Miller scored 20 points as Indiana won in Denver, extending the
Pacers' winning streak to a season-high seven games.
</P>
<P>
	   Rik Smits had 17 points, and Travis Best scored 13 of his 15 points in the
fourth quarter to help Indiana beat the Nuggets for the eighth straight time.
</P>
<P>
	   Antonio McDyess led Denver with 21 points and nine rebounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Alonzo Mourning had 28 points and nine blocks in Miami's eighth straight
victory over Houston.
</P>
<P>
	   Jamal Mashburn added 19 points for Miami. Rookie point guard Steve Francis
had 22 points for the Rockets, who have lost six straight on the road and 10 of
13 overall.
</P>
</TEXT>
