<HEADLINE> Notes From Campaign 2000  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. (AP) -- On consecutive days, Republican George W. Bush trekked to
investment houses to deliver his stump speech and ask the audience for its vote.
</P>
<P>
	   Did he make the audience swoon? Reporters may never know.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Fidelity Investments and Scudder Kemper Retirement Services forbid
their employees from speaking to reporters on any subject -- even political
speeches the companies arrange.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You can't speak to him,'' a Fidelity spokeswoman told two women talking
with a reporter after the Texas governor's appearance at its Bedford office
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   David Weinstein, Fidelity's head of government relations, said the policy
prevents the public from assuming that an employee's reaction is the same as
Fidelity's.
</P>
<P>
	   A Scudder spokeswoman offered the same rationale after that company also
barred reporters from seeking audience reaction after a Bush speech Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   BY THE NUMBERS:
</P>
<P>
	   52 -- Percentage of Americans who think the Republicans and Democrats will
continue to be the only two major political parties in the next 50 years. Pew
Center, November.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   VOTER'S VOICE:
</P>
<P>
	   ``Tonight, I was looking to hear a new voice, a new vision. What I heard was
a lot of cut and burn. I didn't hear anything tonight that made me hopeful about
the future.'' -- Mary Westfall of Durham, N.H., after Thursday night's GOP
presidential debate.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THIS DATE FOUR YEARS AGO:
</P>
<P>
	   In Dubuque, Iowa, Gore predicted a difficult re-election contest and pleaded
with Democratic supporters to help keep the Republican ``right wing fringe''
from winning the White House. ``We simply cannot afford to take anything for
granted, not now, and not for the rest of the year,'' Gore said during a
30-minute campaign speech for the Clinton-Gore ticket. ``We have to build the
Democratic Party in this state because the general election is going to be a
close, tough, hard-fought battle.''
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   THURSDAY'S ROUNDUP:
</P>
<P>
	   In Durham, N.H., Republican presidential candidates hold first of
back-to-back debates and split on the question of whether gays should be allowed
to serve openly in the military. Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Sen. John McCain
express support for existing policy that allows them to serve while keeping
their sexual orientation a secret. Rivals Steve Forbes, Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes
and Orrin Hatch say it should not be allowed.
</P>
<P>
	   A nonpartisan commission chooses Boston, Winston-Salem, N.C., and St. Louis
as sites for three presidential debates in the fall and announces rules that
could make it tough for third party candidates to participate. Reform Party
candidate Pat Buchanan calls the decision a ``transparent farce'' designed to
benefit the establishment parties. Donald Trump, his potential rival, agrees and
threatens legal action.
</P>
<P>
	   Among Democrats, Bill Bradley endorses international treaty to ban
anti-personnel land mines and rival Vice President Al Gore sides with U.S.
relatives of a 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez, who the Immigration and Naturalization
Service says must be returned to his father in Cuba. Relatives in Miami want to
keep him in America.
</P>
