<HEADLINE> Bradley Endorses Landmine Treaty  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Arguing that the United States can ``lead the world
by the power of our example,'' Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley
has formally endorsed an international treating banning anti-personnel land
mines.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley issued his endorsement at a campaign rally Thursday, saying military
experts had assured him the treaty poses no threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue is getting attention in Iowa, which launches the presidential
nominating process with its caucuses Jan. 24. Today, a group called Iowans to
Ban Landmines planned an event in downtown Des Moines with Nobel Peace Prize
laureates Jody Williams and Tun Channareth of the International Campaign to Ban
Landmines.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley said the timing of his announcement was deliberate. He had been
asked about the issue during earlier campaign swings, but had not taken a
position.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our military advantage is high-tech and will increasingly be high-tech,''
the former New Jersey senator said. ``There's no lower tech weapon in the world
than a land mine.''
</P>
<P>
	   His rival, Vice President Al Gore, also has endorsed the pact.
</P>
<P>
	   The treaty negotiated in Ottawa would ban anti-personnel land mines and
commit countries agreeing to it to dispose of land mines already in place. It
has been signed by more than 130 countries, but not the United States, and
ratified by more than 70.
</P>
<P>
	   The United States argues that weapons are needed on the Korean peninsula to
deter the North from invading the South. President Clinton has said the United
States will approve the treaty by 2006, but only if the armed forces come up
with an alternative by then.
</P>
<P>
	   Backers of the treaty say hundreds of thousands of land mines remain in
place for years after conflict, killing innocent people. Critics argue that
landmines are an essential part of a military strategy.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley will be in Iowa for several days of campaigning, including a
Saturday debate with Gore. Today, he was returning to health care issues -- a
subject that has become a sharp bone of contention between the two contenders.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, Bradley told supporters packed into a hangar at the Des Moines
airport that the treaty makes sense, ``not only so we can enhance our national
security, but we can lead the world by the power of our example.''
</P>
<P>
	   He said a major factor in his decision was that land mines are
indiscriminate killers. ``Our military advantage is that we are mobile, and land
mines are stationary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Afterward, Bradley headed to a chilly picket line where members of the
Teamsters Union are on strike and he got praise for a health care plan that Gore
has criticized as one that would squander the nation's projected budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
	   Picketer Ed Hamel, of Des Moines, told Bradley of his 10-month-old child who
suffers from cerebral palsy, but isn't covered by the family health policy.
</P>
<P>
	   Gripping his arm, Bradley declared: ``This fight is for you. Can I tell your
story out there?''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think you made up my mind,'' said Hamel.
</P>
<P>
	   Later, Bradley said that response is typical of what he gets from voters who
have heard about his health plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0315 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
