<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census Seeks Head Count Workers  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Wanted: A half-million hard workers to visit neighbors and
get them to talk about themselves. The hours are flexible, the pay is good.
</P>
<P>
	   With the national head count closing in, the Census Bureau launched an
effort Thursday to hire an army of part-time workers to take the tally.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Our goal is to have a pool of local people who are familiar with their
communities and committed to a successful count in their own neighborhoods,''
Census Director Kenneth Prewitt said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said the Bureau has 520 offices open across the country with each
needing to hire 800 to 1,000 people for four weeks to six weeks around census
day, April 1. He said the agency will spend $9.5 million on help-wanted
advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   Just 65 percent of American households mailed back their Census forms in
1990. While the Bureau hopes to boost that rate with advertising this time, most
of the workers being hired are needed to visit the homes of people who fail to
respond by mail.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall, the count is on schedule, Prewitt said, with 150,000 people hired
so far and a pool of about 1 million applicants. He said the agency wants an
overall pool of about 3 million from which to choose.
</P>
<P>
	   Those hired include about 6,000 welfare-to-work applicants, Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
	   Legal residents age 18 and older are eligible to work for the Census Bureau.
They do not need to be citizens, he said.
</P>
<P>
	   In many areas the agency is seeking bilingual workers. Pay varies from $8.25
to $18.50 per hour.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt urged anyone interested in a Census job to call the agency's
toll-free number, 1-888-325-7733.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said other aspects of the effort are also on schedule, including:
</P>
<P>
	   --The first local counts will begin in two weeks in rural parts of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
	   --Printing is ahead of schedule with all 123 million long forms finished and
the work about 75 percent complete on the short forms.
</P>
<P>
	   --The agency has verified 20 million rural addresses, adding 10,000 new
ones, and is now sending the 100 million city addresses to local governments for
verification.
</P>
<P>
	   --The agency has obtained 4.5 million square feet of office space, 17,000
telephones, 100,000 pieces of furniture and thousands of pieces of office
equipment.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said about two-thirds of the workers hired so far are women, many
seeking a second part-time job. He noted that most people who worked for the
agency in dress rehearsals are coming back for the final count.
</P>
<P>
	   Overall there are about 860,000 jobs to be filled, but not all at the same
time, so Prewitt said the agency expects many people will do more than one of
them.
</P>
<P>
	   The effort to count the estimated 274 million people in the United States is
a decade-long program, Prewitt stressed, noting that planning for the 2010 count
already has started.
</P>
<P>
	   He warned that ``the conditions that make it difficult to count this country
completely have magnified since 1990,'' including the presence of more
immigrants, a larger non-English speaking population, a more mobile population,
more total households and more irregular living arrangements.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe we can do a basic enumeration better than we did in 1990,'' he
said, but that does not necessarily mean a more accurate census.
</P>
<P>
	   Prewitt said he expects there will still be an undercount, in particular
among minorities, and the agency will need to do a post-census quality check to
measure that undercount and correct it in the overall totals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0520 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 06:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Country Music Album Sales Decline  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- It's a true country heartbreaker: Sales of country
music declined 4.5 percent last year even as sales for the record industry
overall jumped 6.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Country music sold 69.3 million albums last year, according to SoundScan, a
Hartsdale, N.Y., company that tracks music sales and released 1999 figures on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
	   The most successful was Shania Twain, whose "Come on Over" album sold 5.6
million.
</P>
<P>
	   Industry officials said country is no longer the fad of the moment, as it
was in the 1980s when Garth Brooks became a superstar.
</P>
<P>
	   Also, they said consolidation of the radio industry has led to tighter
playlists as conglomerates put pressure on stations to be more profitable. That
makes it harder to develop new stars and cultivate record buyers.
</P>
<P>
	   Another reason given for the drop is that many traditional country music
fans have become alienated by the influence of pop on country.
</P>
<P>
	   "What we're doing is we're giving away the music to other formats and we're
frustrating the fans of our own format," said Evelyn Shriver, president of the
country division of Asylum Records.
</P>
<P>
	   The record industry overall sold 754.8 million albums in 1999. But among
country performers, only Ms. Twain and the Dixie Chicks (with 3.5 million sales
of "Wide Open Spaces") made the year's list of top 10 sellers.
</P>
<P>
	   The country industry is reliant on a select group of superstars. Brooks, the
Dixie Chicks and Faith Hill each have two of the 10 best-selling country albums
of the year. And four of the top 10 were released in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   "Trying to add some artists to that mix and create diversity is a priority
for us this year," said Ed Benson of the Country Music Association, a trade
organization that promotes country music.
</P>
<P>
	   Brooks, 37, the biggest-selling artist in country music history, has
indicated he may retire at the end of 2000 to spend more time with his three
young daughters. That could be a big blow to Nashville.
</P>
<P>
	   Nashville has survived such trends before. The industry rebounded from a
decline in the mid-1980s to reach unprecedented heights. Even now, far more
country albums are being sold than a decade ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 0608 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 06:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Satisfaction' Said Rock's Best  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- More than 30 years later, the competition between the
Beatles and the Rolling Stones rages on.
</P>
<P>
	   The Beatles placed nine entries on a list of rock 'n' roll's 100 greatest
songs, as compiled by VH1 in a poll of 700 people in the music industry. The
Stones have five.
</P>
<P>
	   But it's the Stones' celebrated ode to sexual frustration, "(I Can't Get No)
Satisfaction," that topped the list. The Beatles could do no better than ninth,
with "Hey Jude."
</P>
<P>
	   The Stones' 1965 hit has one of the most recognizable guitar riffs in music,
which Keith Richards said came to him one night when he was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
	   "It kind of sticks up as an anthem for the time it was released and for
every generation that came since," said Todd Schwartz, VH1 programming director.
"It strikes a chord with every teen-ager."
</P>
<P>
	   After "Hey Jude," three other Beatles songs made the top 25: "Yesterday," "A
Day in the Life" and "I Want to Hold Your Hand."
</P>
<P>
	   "The Beatles had so many songs that the vote got divided," Schwartz said.
</P>
<P>
	   Elvis Presley, who had four songs on the list as did Led Zeppelin, couldn't
crack the top 10. The best he could do was No. 18 with "Jailhouse Rock."
</P>
<P>
	   A lot of big names were shut out of the top 100 entirely, among them
Madonna, Fleetwood Mac, Neil Young, U2 and R.E.M. Aretha Franklin's "Respect"
came in second and Led Zeppelin's "Stairway to Heaven," a staple of FM radio in
the 1970s, was third.
</P>
<P>
	   Rounding out the top 10 are "Like a Rolling Stone" by Bob Dylan; "Born to
Run" by Bruce Springsteen; "Hotel California" by the Eagles; "Light My Fire" by
the Doors; "Good Vibrations" by the Beach Boys; "Hey Jude"; and "Imagine" by
John Lennon.
</P>
<P>
	   The list's oldest song was "Rock Around the Clock" by Bill Haley &AMP; His
Comets, released in 1954. The newest was Nirvana's "Smells Like Teen Spirit,"
from 1991.
</P>
<P>
	   Nirvana's hit was the only one from the 1990s to make it. Schwartz said it
may be because VH1's voters were even older than the network's usual audience.
VH1 aims at age 30 and up.
</P>
<P>
	   VH1 will count down the list in a special that runs over five nights,
starting Jan. 17.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
