<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 10:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thais Target 'Anna and King' Videos  </HEADLINE>
    By THAKSINA KHAIKAEW Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thai police have swung into action against the
banned Hollywood movie "Anna and The King," arresting two people allegedly
peddling pirated video disks and threatening them with long prison terms for
insulting Thailand's revered monarchy.
</P>
<P>
	   The filmmaker, 20th Century Fox, meanwhile confirmed Friday that it would
not appeal against a censors' ruling last month banning the film, starring
Oscar-winner Jodie Foster and action star Chow Yun-fat, for allegedly
denigrating a 19th century king.
</P>
<P>
	   "Partly because we respect Thai law, partly because it would be no use,"
said Atsara Pithaksorayuth, a Fox public relations official. "It is impossible
to improve the film to meet the demand of the censorship board."
</P>
<P>
	   Though the movie was easily banned from cinemas, many had expected
Thailand's flourishing market in pirated video cassettes and video discs to
easily circumvent the ban.
</P>
<P>
	   Copies of "Anna and The King" are reported to be going for $3.50.
</P>
<P>
	   Police arrested Jinjutha Boondharmmakul, 24, a university student, and
vendor Ravipatra Sawadwattanawong after they were caught on Thursday in
possession of 400 CD versions in a market parking lot.
</P>
<P>
	   Beside facing charges of violating copyright laws, which carry penalties of
up to two years in prison and a $1,080 fine, they could be charged under
seldom-applied laws against insulting the king, said Police Col. Suchart
Teerasawad.
</P>
<P>
	   The men could be sentenced to up to 15 years in prison for diminishing the
standing of the monarchy, an institution revered by nearly all of Thailand's 61
million people. But King Bhumibol Adulyadej, the world's longest-reigning
monarch, has made it known that he does not want anyone prosecuted under the
laws this year.
</P>
<P>
	   Police Maj. Gen. Prakard Satamarn, who headed the censorship board, said the
crackdown on video versions would continue.
</P>
<P>
	   "Anna and The King" was banned from being filmed and screened in Thailand
because of its depiction of Mongkut, a 19th century king of Siam, as Thailand
was then known.
</P>
<P>
	   Historians said the story was inaccurate, giving Anna Leonowens, an
Englishwoman hired to teach Mongkut's children, a prominence in court life and
hinted romantic involvement with the king that did not exist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
