havoc, and both those powers rest in the same hands,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Consumer Electronics Show Opens
</P>
<P>
	   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- A refrigerator that can sense when milk goes
sour; a microwave that will tell you what to cook from the
leftovers in your house; a car with a chip that stops you from
speeding. Electronics manufacturers at the giant Consumer
Electronics Show that opened yesterday are showcasing hundreds of
new ``smart'' devices like these, claiming they can make life
easier through seamless connections to the Internet. But a big
question is: Will consumers bite on such ideas? Computing and
software giants such as Microsoft, Sun Microsystems, Cisco and
Intel are betting they will, as are consumer electronics
manufacturers including Sony, Panasonic, Whirlpool, General
Electric and Casio.
</P>
<P>
	   Northwest Web Customers at Risk
</P>
<P>
	   EAGAN, Minn. (AP) -- Northwest Airlines is alerting customers who
recently made purchases on its Frequent Flier Web site that their
credit card numbers and personal information were unprotected
because of a programming glitch. Northwest spokesman Jon Austin
said the risk of hackers getting the information is small, but one
the airline is taking seriously. ``We want to be able to take care
of this ourselves because it is a problem we created and one we
want to help resolve,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Pricewaterhouse Violations Found
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Nearly half the partners at accounting giant
PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP reported having violated rules
prohibiting them from owning stock in companies they audit, and
many more such lapses went unreported, a review led by an
independent consultant has found. The Securities and Exchange
Commission, which made the consultant's review public yesterday,
said its investigation of New York-based PricewaterhouseCoopers is
continuing. A year ago, the firm agreed in a settlement to conduct
the review and create a $2.5 million education fund after the SEC
alleged that some of its accountants compromised their independence
by owning stock in corporations they audited.
</P>
<P>
	   Most Asian Markets Close Higher
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher today
following two days of massive declines, although technology shares
remained weak. Hong Kong's blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 252.40
points, or 1.7 percent, closing at 15,405.63. The index had plunged
more than 11 percent in the past two days. In Tokyo, the 225-issue
Nikkei Stock Average gained 25.14 points, or 0.14 percent, to close
at 18,193.41.
</P>
<P>
	   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment: unchanged at 4.1 percent
</P>
