<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 11:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Demand for Luxury Cruises Grows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) -- Luxury cruises are in the money.
</P>
<P>
	   Among the guests aboard the 1,316-passenger Rotterdam when it sailed from
Port Everglades on Thursday were four couples who each booked a penthouse
verandah suite costing more than $275,000 for a 96-day global cruise, according
to officials from Holland America Line, the ship's Seattle-based owner.
</P>
<P>
	   Beverages, tips, shopping and shore excursions easily can add an additional
40 percent to a cruise vacation's tab, said cruise line officials.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 925 guests were booked for the entire three-month itinerary at fares
ranging from $27,000 to $138,000 per passenger. Holland America said that was an
increase of more than 50 percent from the number taking the world cruise last
year.
</P>
<P>
	   Most remaining cabins were filed by travelers taking just parts of the
route.
</P>
<P>
	   The cruise includes stops at 40 different ports on five continents,
including Antarctica and Midway Island in the Pacific.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
