<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 11:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Dumps Young &AMP; Rubicam Ad Agency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army said today it is dumping its advertising agency,
Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. of New York, which held the account for 12 years and coined
the ad slogan, ``Be All That You Can Be.''
</P>
<P>
	   In what it billed as a ``dramatic series of changes'' in how it markets
itself to America's youth, the Army said it will set up an in-house group
staffed by civilians with corporate marketing experience to pick a new ad
agency. It also hired a Chicago consulting firm, Jones-Lundin Associates Inc.,
to help in the selection.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army said Young &AMP; Rubicam is welcome to compete for the new contract, in
which the firm's compensation will depend on how many enlistments result from
its advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
	   To a greater extent than the other military services, the Army has had
difficulty meeting its recruiting goals. In 1999 it had a shortfall of 6,290
recruits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
