<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 11:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Command Sgt. Maj. Loses Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEIDELBERG, Germany (AP) -- The U.S. Army's former top enlisted man in Europe
has lost his appeal of the punishment and fine he received for fraternizing with
a subordinate, the command said today.
</P>
<P>
	   Command Sgt. Maj. Riley C. Miller was found guilty of fraternization with a
junior noncommissioned officer under his direct supervision at a hearing Dec.
21. The military earlier had dropped more serious charges that Miller sexually
assaulted his female driver.
</P>
<P>
	   Lt. Gen. James C. Riley, the commander of 5th U.S. Army Corps in Heidelberg,
who had the option of recommending that Miller face a court martial trial or
lesser action, had ordered he be given a letter of reprimand and forfeit $3,700
in pay over a two month period.
</P>
<P>
	   A military statement today said that Gen. Montgomery C. Meigs reviewed and
denied Miller's appeal of that punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   Meigs removed Miller, a 30-year veteran, from his job as the top
representative of Army enlisted personnel in Europe in September and assigned
him to other unspecified duties.
</P>
<P>
	   The U.S. Army Europe has since announced that Sgt. Maj. David L. Lady,
previously sergeant major of the U.S. Army Armor Center at Fort Knox, Ky., will
be its new command sergeant major.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1156 </TRAILER>
