<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army May Dump Ad Agency  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army said today it may dump its advertising gency,
Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. of New York, which has held the account for 12 years.
</P>
<P>
	   In what it billed as a ``dramatic series of changes'' in how it markets
itself to America's youth, the Army said it hired a Chicago consulting firm,
Jones-Lundin Associates Inc., to help it select an ad agency for a new contract
that, unlike the existing arrangement, would pay the agency based on how many
recruits it attracts.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army said Young &AMP; Rubicam is welcome to compete for the new contract.
The agency's current five-year contract is due to expire in July. Officials said
it was unclear whether that contract would be terminated early.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the past several years the Army has spent about $110 million a year on
advertising.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army also said it will set up an in-house group staffed by civilians
with corporate marketing experience to monitor the performance of the new ad
agency.
</P>
<P>
	   To a greater extent than the other military services, the Army has had
difficulty meeting its recruiting goals. In 1999 it had a shortfall of 6,290
recruits.
</P>
</TEXT>
