<DOCNO> APW20000107.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Spending Sought for Farm Plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration will seek $1.3 billion in new
spending for farm conservation programs in its 2001 budget, including $600
million in payments to farmers who voluntarily take steps to stop runoff from
their land.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration also is proposing to expand the popular Conservation
Reserve Program, which pays farmers to take environmentally sensitive land out
of production for at least 10 years.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore, who announced the proposals today during a campaign
trip to Iowa, said they would ``provide needed financial support to our family
farmers as well as tremendous environmental benefits for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
	   The measures would nearly double what the Agriculture Department is spending
this year on conservation programs. The administration's 2001 budget also is
expected to include subsidies to compensate farmers for depressed commodity
prices.
</P>
<P>
	   USDA predicts that net farm income will drop $7.6 billion this year to $40.4
billion, making it likely that Congress will approve another large infusion of
federal aid this fall. The administration hopes to steer at least some of that
money into conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
	   The centerpiece of the administration's conservation plan is the new $600
million subsidy program, which was introduced in Congress last year by Sen. Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa. Payment levels under the ``Conservation Security Program'' would
be based on the size scope of the conservation measures taken by the farmers.
They could include planting grass along streams and cutting back on livestock
grazing.
</P>
<P>
	   An existing program that provides assistance for manure control and a
variety of other conservation measures would be increased from $174 million this
year to $325 million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Other proposals include:
</P>
<P>
	   --Increasing the acreage cap in the Conservation Reserve Program from 3.6
million to 40 million acres. That would allow more than twice as much land to be
enrolled in the program during the 2001 fiscal year as would be permitted under
current law.
</P>
<P>
	   --Expanding a program that pays farmers to restore wetlands by 210,000 acres
in 2001 and an additional 250,000 acres a year after that. The Wetlands Reserve
Program is currently limited to 975,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
	   The conservation proposals would represent a fundamental shift in the way
the government has traditionally supported farmers, said Agriculture Secretary
Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have been paying farmers for decades to grow commodities and, in some
cases, not to grow commodities. Now we must start thinking of the land itself as
our most valuable commodity,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
