<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Freaks and Geeks': Fresh New Course  </HEADLINE>
    By FRAZIER MOORE AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- "Freaks and Geeks" reminds us that it's not enough just to
say "outsider." Alienation comes in many shapes and sizes, and this drama, as
its title might suggest, celebrates the rich variety.
</P>
<P>
	   Set in a midwestern high school, circa 1980, "Freaks and Geeks" is a
knowing, affectionate and often very funny outpost on the rim of suburban life.
What we find there resists stereotypes and Hollywood styling. The look of the
show is remarkably unremarkable. The characters, like the world they occupy,
seem captured as they really are.
</P>
<P>
	   Of course, "Freaks and Geeks" is hardly TV's first showcase for teen-age
outcasts. But what makes it so special is its fresh take on outsider status --
and its bounty of outsiders.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, happily, this wonderful show has been rescued from the Saturday fringes
of the NBC schedule, where, since its September premiere, no one knew about it
but adoring critics. NBC has moved the series to a more accessible slot: Monday
at 8 p.m. EST. Its survival there apparently depends on an instant upsurge in
the ratings.
</P>
<P>
	   Here's hoping.
</P>
<P>
	   "Freaks and Geeks" centers on Lindsay Weir. A bright but disaffected
sophomore, she has sought refuge from one fringe group (the school's brain
trust) by penetrating another (the fun-loving, rules-defying freaks).
</P>
<P>
	   "Oh, you're that chick who got an A," says gratuitous burnout Daniel, trying
to place her.
</P>
<P>
	   "Yeah, well," says Lindsay, feeling nailed. "Whadaya gonna do?"
</P>
<P>
	   Played by the adorable Linda Cardellini, Lindsay is a complicated mix of
goodwill, gumption and free-floating peevishness. The recent death of Lindsay's
grandmother has shaken her, triggering fundamental doubts about the meaning of
life and, more to the point, who she wants to be.
</P>
<P>
	   Now, as she tries to redefine herself, everyone is on her case -- especially
her father (Joe Flaherty), who, dispensing guidance, always cites the worst-case
scenario.
</P>
<P>
	   "You know who used to cut class?" he lectures Lindsay. "Jimi Hendrix. You
know what happened to him? He DIED!"
</P>
<P>
	   "I just cut one class!" Lindsay fires back. "And guess what? Everybody's
still alive!"
</P>
<P>
	   She's alive, yes, but steeped in confusion.
</P>
<P>
	   She dreads a first date with her would-be boyfriend Nick, whom she assumes
will expect her to go all the way. But when, instead, he serenades her off-key
to a Styx record ("Laaaady! When you're with me I'm smiling!"), she's
disappointed that he won't make out a little.
</P>
<P>
	   In a chronic funk, Lindsay views her world through wary eyes. She reacts to
its absurdities with a stricken smile. And in the face of all the brazen winners
who surround her, she seems hellbent on taking up for the underdog (which may
help explain the choice of her new friends).
</P>
<P>
	   Another underdog: her freshman brother. Played by John Daley, Sam is a sweet
kid who, small and immature for his age, is dwarfed even by the petite Lindsay,
who on at least one occasion defends him against a bully.
</P>
<P>
	   But unlike Lindsay, Sam is fundamentally happy hanging out with his geek
pals. Together they endure the indignities of PhysEd and contemplate such issues
as, "Will girls ever like us?"
</P>
<P>
	   Maybe so. On this week's episode, a lovely transfer student befriends Sam
and his chums. She launches model rockets with them. She pigs out with them at
an all-you-can-eat ribs restaurant. She's a dream come true for the boys.
</P>
<P>
	   But then comes the question: Other than keeping her from the clutches of the
"in" crowd, what should be their next move?
</P>
<P>
	   Sam: "OK, we're all in love with her. And obviously she likes all of us. So
now all we have to do is decide who gets her."
</P>
<P>
	   Gangly, bespectacled Bill: "How do we do that?"
</P>
<P>
	   Sci-fi nut Neal: "The same way we decided who had to stand in line for 'The
Empire Strikes Back' tickets."
</P>
<P>
	   Sam: "I'll get the hat."
</P>
<P>
	   As its heroes struggle to maintain their footing against the undertow of
adolescence, "Freaks and Geeks" is funny without being phony, tender without
being sentimental, honest without being harsh.
</P>
<P>
	   Even in its new time slot, this show may still be a Nielsen pariah. But make
no mistake, if it were watched by everyone whose high school experience it
echoes, "Freaks and Geeks" would be a Top 10 hit.
</P>
<P>
	   Remember: We're all on the outside of something. Misfits of the viewing
world, unite!
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
	   'CRIER TODAY': Court TV newcomer Catherine Crier launches a live, daily
one-hour program that will examine news stories, and draw on newsmakers and
opinion leaders, to shed light on current legal issues such as the death penalty
and the First Amendment. For Monday's premiere, Crier talks to wrongfully
convicted boxer Rubin "Hurricane" Carter -- subject of the new film "The
Hurricane." Court TV will air "Crier Today" weekdays at 1 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore "at" ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
