<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that are moving substantially or trading heavily
today on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock Market, and American Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   At least four major investment firms downgraded Lucent following late
Thursday's warning by the communications equipment maker that its profits from
the final three months of 1999 won't meet Wall Street forecasts. But Lucent's
troubles were apparently seen as a gain for its main rivals in supplying speedy
fiber-optic gear for the communications networks that make up the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   The German software group reported that its pretax profit doubled last year
as the company reached its goal of 15 percent to 20 percent sales growth. SAP is
scheduled to report more precise figures on Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
	   The Atlanta-based beverage company named a new head for its European
division, which struggled through a contamination scare and a huge recall last
year. Charles S. Frenette will become an executive vice president and take over
the Greater Europe Group, which includes 49 countries, following the retirement
of William P. Casey. Frenette, 47, is currently the chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
	   The company warned that it only expects to break-even in per-share profits
for the fourth quarter. A First Call/Thomson Financial survey of four analysts
predicted the company would earn 25 cents a share for the period. Hanger, based
in Bethesda, Md., blamed transition problems associated with last year's
acquisition of NovaCare O&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
	   The company is launching a co-branded gaming site with Red Hat, a leading
developer of Linux-based computer systems. IEntertainment, based in Research
Triangle Park, N.C., said it also will begin developing games using Red Hat
Linux.
</P>
<P>
	   Redknife, a provider of electronic commerce services, will use Infodata's
applications information management technology in developing a new e-commerce
system. Infodata is based in Fairfax, Va.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray downgraded the provider of online legal
information to buy from strong buy, Dow Jones Newswires reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The network technology company warned late Thursday it will post a larger
than expected fourth-quarter loss of $1 million to $1.5 million, or 6 cents to 9
cents a share. FVC, based in Santa Clara, Calif., said it didn't complete a
major contract in December as expected.
</P>
</TEXT>
