<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mostly Up; Gold Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- The U.S. dollar was higher against most major currencies in
European trading today. Gold prices rose.
</P>
<P>
	   The euro was quoted at $1.0288, down from $1.0337 Thursday, while the
British pound fell to $1.6368 from $1.6470.
</P>
<P>
	   Later in New York, the euro was trading at $1.0294 and the pound was
changing hands at $1.6378.
</P>
<P>
	   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Thursday included
105.40 Japanese yen, up from 105.14; 1.5622 Swiss francs, up from 1.5522, and
1.4570 Canadian dollars, up from 1.4537.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro rates, the dollar is
worth 1.9007 German marks, up from 1.8920; 6.3766 French francs, up from 6.3457;
2.1424 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1318, and 1,882.07 Italian lire, up from
1,873.14.
</P>
<P>
	   At midday in New York, the dollar was quoted at 105.05 yen and 1.5616 Swiss
francs.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold closed in London at $281.90 per troy ounce, up from $279.20 on
Thursday. In Zurich, the bid was $281.40, up from $279.10.
</P>
<P>
	   Gold rose $1.90 in Hong Kong to $282.75.
</P>
<P>
	   Silver opened in London at $5.14 per troy ounce, up from $5.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
