<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 former utility workers harmed by asbestos settle for $2 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) - A group of asbestos companies agreed to pay $2
million to 14 retired utility workers and the heirs of three others stricken
with asbestos-linked diseases at power stations a generation ago.
<P>
	   The men, ranging in age from 56 to 75, had suffered exposure to asbestos
insulation products while working at Rochester Gas &AMP; Electric Corp. as far back
as the late 1950s, their attorney, Dennis Herron, said Friday. Most of them
retired in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
	   Three of the men who sued for damages in 1997 have since died of lung, colon
and throat cancers. Their share of the award goes to their families. The
wrongful death and injury lawsuit had gotten to the first day of jury selection
Thursday before being settled.
</P>
<P>
	   As part of the settlement, the identities of the 21 defendants - asbestos
manufacturers, suppliers and distributors - were kept confidential. The utility
was not sued because New York employers are protected from claims under a
workers' compensation law.
</P>
<P>
	   The men were employed at a variety of power stations in the Rochester
region, including the Ginna nuclear plant on Lake Ontario's southern shore.
Power plants use great amounts of insulation for high-pressure steam pipes.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal government banned the use of asbestos at industrial work places
in 1972. Exposure to asbestos can result in illness anywhere from 10 to 40 years
later, Herron said.
</P>
<P>
	   "The interesting thing with a lot of these 17 guys is they didn't work
directly with these products," he said. "They were doing their job next to a guy
who was replacing asbestos pipe covering ... and were exposed as a bystander."
</P>
<P>
	   All of the men were eventually stricken with illnesses that scientists have
linked to asbestos exposure, from various cancers to pleural thickening and
scarring of the lungs.
</P>
<P>
	   It was at least the fourth asbestos lawsuit in Rochester since 1996 that
ended in a payout.
</P>
<P>
	   In January 1996, the family of a retired Kodak worker who had recently died
of mesothelioma - the only form of lung cancer directly linked to asbestos
exposure - was awarded $375,000 in a settlement with five asbestos manufacturers
and a distributor.
</P>
<P>
	   In August 1997, nine asbestos manufacturers and distributors paid more than
$500,000 to the widow of a former Eastman Kodak Co. worker who had died five
months earlier of mesothelioma.
</P>
<P>
	   Last June, 18 makers and suppliers of asbestos paid $1.25 million to a Kodak
worker and the families of four fellow employees who had died of
asbestos-related illnesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 1410 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Peace Corps Director Sworn In  </HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BRISCOE Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The new Peace Corps director, sworn in Friday, says he
wants more volunteers in developing countries to work with computers as a means
of offering high-tech assistance to the world's poor.
</P>
<P>
	   Mark L. Schneider said he also wants volunteers to use e-mail to increase
global contacts for communities and classrooms at home.
</P>
<P>
	   He took the oath of office at the Peace Corps' downtown Washington
headquarters before a cheering crowd of Peace Corps workers, former volunteers
and administration officials.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am convinced that today's Peace Corps volunteers are comparative experts
in harnessing information technology to the task of poverty reduction,'' said
Schneider, who was appointed by President Clinton while Congress was out,
eliminating the need for Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider and his wife, Susan, served as Peace Corps volunteers in El
Salvador in the late 1960s. He is a former U.S. Agency for International
Development assistant administrator for Latin America. He has also worked for
the Pan American Health Organization and was senior deputy assistant secretary
of state for human rights.
</P>
<P>
	   The idea of having volunteers equipped with laptop computers and other
high-tech devices is not new, but Peace Corps administrators have shied away
from equipping them with too much technology because they want volunteers to
live at the same level as the people they serve.
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider said computer-equipped volunteers could help develop small
businesses, explore new products that could boost local economies and help
reduce production costs. They also might be used to monitor immunizations, help
the poor acquire title to land and give urban teachers access to the Internet
for their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider said he also wants to work to increase the number of Peace Corps
volunteers from the current 7,000 to 10,000 -- a goal set by President Clinton
but not yet funded by Congress.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Volunteers convey a sense of optimism to those around them that what is
attempted can be achieved,'' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton included Schneider among his ``recess appointments'' to avoid a long
nomination process. As it is, Schneider has no guarantee of being able to serve
after Clinton's term ends at the start of 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider, 58, is the 15th director of the corps set up by President Kennedy
in 1961. Peace Corps volunteers now serve in 78 countries, receiving a living
allowance roughly comparable to local salaries. They include educators,
environmentalists, health experts, business advisers and agriculturists.
</P>
<P>
	   Schneider succeeds longtime Clinton aide Mark Gearan, who resigned as Peace
Corps director in August to become president of Hobart and William Smith
Colleges in Geneva, N.Y.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1418 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toner to take chief job at Electric Boat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   GROTON, Conn. (AP) - A Mystic man has worked his way up through the
ranks at Electric Boat to become president of the company - a first for the
submarine maker.
<P>
	   Senior Vice President Michael W. Toner takes over Jan. 17, replacing
President John K. Welch, who has been named to head the Marine Systems Group of
General Dynamics, the parent company of Electric Boat.
</P>
<P>
	   When Toner reported for work at Electric Boat in 1965, he was taking a class
while waiting for security clearance. The teacher said they should appreciate
the opportunities that were available to them.
</P>
<P>
	   Why, someone in the room might even be president of the company someday,
Toner recalled the teacher saying.
</P>
<P>
	   "At the time I was trying to figure out what I was going to have for lunch
or when I was going to get out of that class," Toner said with a laugh. "But
I've thought about it over the years, and chuckled to myself, and thought,
'Wouldn't it be something if that happened?'
</P>
<P>
	   "I've reflected on it a lot the last few days, and now it has," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   One of Toner's chief concerns will be increasing the volume of business in
the shipyard, possibly through new partnerships with the nearby Naval Submarine
Base and the Portsmouth Naval Shipyard in Kittery, Maine.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'd like to see us start to try to get some new work into the shipyard, and
reinvigorate the work force," Toner said. "That would give us the ability to
transfer the knowledge to the next generation of shipbuilders."
</P>
<P>
	   While design work on the Virginia class of submarine is winding down, he
held out hope that the shipyard could handle other projects, such as the next
generation of aircraft carriers and the conversion of four older ballistic
missile submarines to fire conventional missiles.
</P>
<P>
	   Labor union leaders at the shipyard approved of Toner's appointment.
</P>
<P>
	   "I think it could be very good news, because he understands the shipyard;
he's not an outsider," said Kenneth G. DelaCruz, president of the Metal Trades
Council.
</P>
<P>
	   Melvin E. Olsson, president of the Marine Draftsmen's Association, said
Toner's and Welch's appointments should be good for the company.
</P>
<P>
	   "Mike's going to be a good president for Electric Boat. He knows the
shipyard top to bottom, and what I like is he cares about the people as much as
he does the bottom line," Olsson said.
</P>
<P>
	   Toner, 56, has been second in command since May 1998, when he was named
senior vice president and directed 4,200 employees in the engineering and design
departments.
</P>
<P>
	   He came to the company after graduating with a degree in nuclear science
from New York Maritime College.
</P>
<P>
	   He took a job at Electric Boat when the Marine Engineers Benevolent
Association was on strike, and planned to stay until the end of the summer or
until the strike was over.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead, he rose through the ranks as a manager and earned more academic
degrees: a master's degree in engineering from the University of Connecticut in
1970 and an executive master's of business administration from the University of
New Haven in 1982.
</P>
<P>
	   Toner and his wife, Carol, have three grown children.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
