<HEADLINE> Dow Up 146.44; Nasdaq Up 73.93  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose sharply today, with blue-chip shares surging
despite more signs of inflationary pressure and the technology group mounting a
modest rebound even after a profit warning by Lucent.
</P>
<P>
	   In afternoon trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up
146.44 at 11,399.70, extending the 250-point rebound of the past two days and
wiping out the remainder of Tuesday's 359-point tumble. Earlier in the day, the
Dow was up nearly 202 points.
</P>
<P>
	   The tech-laden Nasdaq composite index was up 73.93 at 3,801.06 after
plunging 400 points, or nearly 10 percent, over the previous three sessions.
</P>
<P>
	   Other broad-market indicators were also posting sizable gains, with the
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rising 17.47 to 1,420.92.
</P>
<P>
	   The strength in technology came despite Lucent Technologies' disclosure late
Thursday that the company won't meet most profit forecasts for the final quarter
of 1999. Lucent fell in late trading on other markets and was trading today at
52 15/16, down 16 1/16 from Thursday's close on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Lucent's troubles were apparently seen as a gain for its main rivals in
supplying speedy fiber-optic equipment for the communications networks that make
up the Internet.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is not an industry issue," said Alex M. Cena, an analyst at Salomon
Smith Barney. Cena lowered his earnings estimates for Lucent, but said its woes
were due to specific problems at the company.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, its rivals soared. Nortel Networks was up 14 9/16 at 91 9/16 on
the NYSE, while in heavy Nasdaq trading, Cisco Systems was up 3 3/16 at 103
3/16, Ciena was up 14 1/16 at 59 15/16 and JDS Uniphase was up 17 1/4 at 167.
</P>
<P>
	   Before today's open, the government reported that the nation's unemployment
rate held steady at a three-decade low of 4.1 percent in December as 315,000
workers found jobs, above most forecasts and the biggest gain since July.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the latest sign of a strong labor market that could force employers
to pay higher wages and benefits and then boost their prices to compensate. The
Labor Department reported that average hourly earnings rose by 0.4 percent to
$13.46 in December, the largest gain since September, but in line with what most
were forecasting.
</P>
<P>
	   While wage and job growth are good developments for workers, the Federal
Reserve has already bumped up interest rates three times in less than a year to
slow the red-hot economy and keep inflation under control. Some economists
believe the Fed could boost rates again as early as its Feb. 1-2 meeting,
possibly hurting company profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Notably, many of today's strongest issues were companies who make products
that consumers need regardless of the economic backdrop: Procter &AMP; Gamble surged
7 1/2 to 115 3/8 and Coca-Cola jumped to 3 3/16 to 60 3/16 to help lead the Dow,
which also drew a boost from drugmakers Merck, up 5 1/16 at 73 3/16 and Johnson
&AMP; Johnson, up 3 3/4 to 96 5/16.
</P>
<P>
	   In other trading, advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin
on the NYSE, while Nasdaq gainers led by nearly a 3-to-2 ratio. The Russell 2000
index of smaller companies was up 7.85 at 483.19.
</P>
<P>
	   NYSE volume came to 852.45 million shares at midafternoon, up sharply from
720.29 million at the same point on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.14 percent. European indexes
bounced back sharply from declines this week, with Germany's Xetra DAX rising
4.7 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 up 0.9 percent, and France's CAC-40 up 1.6
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
