<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Army Pays for Ads Based on Recruits  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Hoping to boost its sagging fortunes on the recruiting
front, the Army said Friday it will demand that its advertising agency be paid
based on performance -- how many recruits it attracts -- instead of a flat fee.
</P>
<P>
	   Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. of New York has held the advertising account for 12
years, and its current contract is due to expire in July. Army officials said it
was unclear whether that contract would be terminated early.
</P>
<P>
	   In what it billed as a ``dramatic series of changes'' in how it markets
itself to America's youth, the Army said it hired a Chicago consulting firm,
Jones-Lundin Associates Inc., to help it select an ad agency for the new
contract linking payment to performance.
</P>
<P>
	   Jones-Lundin also will advise the Army on whether it should drop its
advertising slogan, ``Be all that you can be,'' which has been a trademark
recruiting pitch since 1981. Last year, Advertising Age magazine ranked ``Be all
that you can be'' the No. 2 jingle of the century, behind McDonald's, ``You
deserve a break today.'' Some in the Army believe the long-running slogan is
less effective with today's youth.
</P>
<P>
	   Over the past several years the Army has spent about $110 million a year on
advertising, but it has had trouble attracting enough recruits. Last year the
Army reported missing its recruiting target by 6,290.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army said Young &AMP; Rubicam is welcome to compete for the new contract.
</P>
<P>
	   The Army also said it will set up an in-house group staffed by civilians
with corporate marketing experience to monitor the performance of the new ad
agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
