<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The man with the million-megawatt smile is state's $100 million  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Johnnie Ely flashed a $100 million smile as he was
introduced Friday as the winner of the New Year's Eve Millennium Millions
lottery, the largest jackpot in state history.
<P>
	   "I am a happy, happy man," said the 66-year-old short order cook - make
that, ex-short order cook. That much was obvious as he joked with reporters at a
news conference held at Tavern on the Green in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
	   Opting for a lump sum cash payment, Ely won $44 million. After taxes, he
will receive a check for about $27 million.
</P>
<P>
	   Ely, who lives in the South Bronx with his wife of 35 years, Rosemary, a
nurse, didn't learn he was the sole first place winner of last Friday night's
drawing until Monday night. He was visiting friends in New Jersey and didn't
check his tickets until he heard that the winning ticket was still unclaimed.
</P>
<P>
	   "I checked the first ticket and nothing. Then the second ticket and - bingo,
bull's-eye - that was it," Ely said. But he didn't trust his aging eyes and
asked his son, Johnnie Jr., to check, too. Once he confirmed it, Ely said, "Like
a fool, I called the wife out."
</P>
<P>
	   "She put on her glasses, looked the numbers over and said, 'Sweetie, can I
retire now?"'
</P>
<P>
	   "You can retire," he told her. "Can I get a used car?" his son chimed in.
"Yes, you can," Ely calmly answered. He also has two grown daughters.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's cool, real cool to be able to do all the things you've always dreamed
about doing," he said. "But it's the kind of thing that now that you've got it,
you freeze."
</P>
<P>
	   Ely, who has worked for 35 years as a short order cook, spent $100 on
tickets over a month, including the two random quick pick tickets he picked up
the night before the drawing at a Manhattan check cashing store.
</P>
<P>
	   He also belonged to a pool with co-workers from The Java Shop, a
mid-Manhattan restaurant and bar.
</P>
<P>
	   After confirming his good fortune with state lottery officials on Tuesday,
Ely went to work as usual at 4 a.m. Wednesday. Coffee shop manager Winston
Willer said Ely came in and told him, "I've got good news and bad news."
</P>
<P>
	   The good news, he told him, was that the winning lottery ticket was sold at
the check cashing place where he bought their tickets. "I got so excited. I
said, let me go get them and check," Willer said. But Ely told him not to
bother. The bad news was that Ely had the winning ticket.
</P>
<P>
	   "I didn't believe him, even after he told me he had confirmed it," Willer
said, "but I told him, "What are you doing here? Go home."'
</P>
<P>
	   He did, and thanks to the jackpot he doesn't have to make another vegetable
omelet, his specialty, ever again.
</P>
<P>
	   "It couldn't happen to a nicer guy," said waitress Hilda Purdy. She said Ely
used to call her "Cookie," and was always there with fatherly advice. "If I
could tell him one thing, I'd say, 'I'm glad for him. I wish that money gives
him all the happiness he's looking for."'
</P>
<P>
	   He is a regular lottery player, spending $5 a day on tickets. He's also had
many smaller wins. "I've won $1,300 three or four times, $500 to $600 a half a
dozen times and practically every week I win $25 or $30," he said. Despite his
windfall, he planned to keep on playing.
</P>
<P>
	   Ely said his unexpected early retirement has left him not really knowing
what to do. "I still wake up at 2:30 every day, only now I just look out the
window." He said he planned to take care of his extended family, including
helping several nieces and nephews through college, but beyond that he had no
plans.
</P>
<P>
	   He called himself a simple, practical man who likes to fish in his spare
time, drink diet soda and eat lots of vegetables - not too crunchy. Asked what
he wanted for himself, Ely replied:
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't need nothing. As long as I keep the good health I've had through
the years, what else does a man really need?" Then, flashing that
million-megawatt smile again, he joked, "I mean, I'm a millionaire, right?
That's what this is all about, brother. I am a millionaire!"
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
