<DOCNO> APW20000107.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Board OKs Calhoun's Coke endorsements as UConn coach  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Basketball coach Jim Calhoun can use his
association with the University of Connecticut men's basketball team to
advertise for Coca-Cola, the state Ethics Commission decided Friday.
<P>
	   At issue is a rule prohibiting Connecticut employees from using their public
positions for personal gain. Another rule says state workers can't use their
jobs to endorse private companies.
</P>
<P>
	   But Calhoun's agent, Peter Roisman, argued successfully that an exception
should be made because UConn and Calhoun each have separate agreements with
Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
	   "Jim Calhoun is a famous basketball coach who works for the state of
Connecticut," Roisman said. "He's not using the state of Connecticut to make
money."
</P>
<P>
	   Alan Plofsky, the commission's executive director, said his board will keep
a close eye on Calhoun's Coke endorsements.
</P>
<P>
	   "The board's decision allows (Calhoun) to appear in advertisements that also
use the UConn logo or the UConn Husky or any other tie-in to the school because
Coca-Cola has a separate licensing agreement with UConn," Plofsky said.
</P>
<P>
	   "But it allows it based on a most extremely important provision - that he
not be paid one penny extra for that appearance," Plofsky said.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ethics Commission had been asked by Southern New England
Telecommunications Corp. to approve a similar provision for ads they wanted to
run featuring Calhoun. When the commission insisted that SNET disclose the terms
of the contract before considering it for approval, the company pulled its
request.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're not going to disclose details because they say they don't want to
give away trade secrets," said Commissioner Richard Vitarelli.
</P>
<P>
	   Plofsky said Coca-Cola gave the Ethics Commission the details of their
contract with Calhoun, but the board agreed to the company's request that
Calhoun's compensation be kept secret.
</P>
<P>
	   "The amount of money really doesn't indicate whether there's a conflict of
interest or not," Plofsky said. He said the dollar amount is not a public
document because the price was given to the commission verbally.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ethics Commission voted to postpone its discussion of another contract
Calhoun has pending with Nike.
</P>
<P>
	   When the Nike contract was first given to the commission for approval, the
board had multiple problems with it, Plofsky said. He would not discuss specific
problems, but said it has been rewritten to comply with ethics rules.
</P>
<P>
	   Roisman said he will give the board the revised contract, but argued against
having its details discussed in a public meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   "We feel a public discussion of them is a violation of (Calhoun's) privacy,"
Roisman said.
</P>
<P>
	   The board will review the contract before deciding whether to discuss it
publicly.
</P>
<P>
	   Plofsky argued the Nike deal should be discussed at an open meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   "We are here to decide if it is in compliance or if there is a conflict with
the ethics code," he said. "That needs to be discussed and disclosed on the
record."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 1505 </TRAILER>
