<DOCNO> APW20000107.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Most support capital punishment, think appeals take too much time  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - When it comes to murder, most Connecticut people
surveyed believe in an eye-for-an-eye brand of justice.
<P>
	   A Hartford Courant/Connecticut Poll published Friday found 66 percent of
residents surveyed believe capital punishment is appropriate punishment for
murder.
</P>
<P>
	   The support from two-thirds of those surveyed came even though 55 percent of
those polled said they don't believe the death penalty is a deterrent to murder.
</P>
<P>
	   Nearly 40 percent of those asked said they believe a black or Hispanic
defendant is more likely to be sentenced to death than a white defendant who
commits a similar crime, while 51 percent said they believe race would have no
real effect on the punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   Although there is support for the death penalty, the poll found that
two-thirds of those questioned believe it is somewhat unlikely or very unlikely
that an execution will actually take place in the state anytime soon. Sixty-four
percent believe the appeals process is too drawn out.
</P>
<P>
	   Convicted serial killer Michael Ross was sentenced to death in 1987 and
while physically living on Connecticut's death row, has had his death sentence
thrown out. He is awaiting a new trial to determine his punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, New London Superior Court Judge Thomas Miano excused a fifth
juror from serving on the panel that will determine whether Ross is executed or
gets life in prison.
</P>
<P>
	   Jury selection was scheduled to begin Monday to choose five new jurors to
replace ones that Miano excused since the original panel was picked months ago.
A failed, last-minute appeal delayed the penalty hearing for so long that some
jurors could no longer serve on the panel.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to Ross, there are six other men on death row.
</P>
<P>
	   Should the time come when the state actually begins executing those
sentenced to death, some of the respondents believe there is bound to be a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
	   Thirty percent said they believe it is likely that Connecticut will execute
someone who later is proved to be innocent.
</P>
<P>
	   The telephone poll of 500 randomly selected state residents was conducted
Dec. 7 to 13 by the Center for Survey Research and Analysis at the University of
Connecticut. It has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
