<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Once a member, Bradley now resists voter group on candidate survey  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WASHINGTON (AP) - For three years after leaving the Senate, Bill Bradley
lent his name to a voter education group that implores candidates in state and
federal campaigns to fill out a lengthy multiple-choice survey on issues.
<P>
	   Now, as a presidential candidate, Bradley has the chance to fill out Project
Vote Smart's "National Political Awareness Test" himself. But to the dismay of
the nonpartisan group, Bradley is resisting. His campaign says the test's
multiple-choice format is too confining and leaves little room for substance.
</P>
<P>
	   Bradley's Democratic opponent, Vice President Al Gore, has declined to fill
out the questionnaire on similar grounds. Republican George W. Bush and Reform
Party candidate Pat Buchanan have also turned down the group's entreaties.
</P>
<P>
	   But given his past affiliation with the group, it is Bradley's stance that
has most frustrated officials at Project Vote Smart's Philipsburg, Mont.,
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
	   "The quandary we have with Senator Bradley," said Richard Kimball, president
of the Project Vote Smart board, "is that he reviewed (the test) and approved it
for other candidates, but did not take it himself."
</P>
<P>
	   Spokesman Tony Wyche said the Bradley campaign has made numerous attempts to
satisfy Project Vote Smart with written summaries of the candidate's positions.
</P>
<P>
	   "We've tried a couple different ways to make it happen," Wyche said. "We've
sent them fact sheets. We're hoping to find a way to make this work."
</P>
<P>
	   Project Vote Smart argues that compliance with the multiple-choice format is
important to give voters a side-by-side comparison of candidate positions.
Candidates must answer at least 70 percent of the questions to get a passing
grade from Project Vote Smart.
</P>
<P>
	   Next Wednesday, Project Vote Smart will release grades for more than 100
major and minor party presidential candidates and 12,000 candidates for
Congress, governor and state legislatures across the country. Candidate answers
will be released as well.
</P>
<P>
	   For now, the group's Web site notes simply whether a candidate has submitted
answers.
</P>
<P>
	   Republicans Gary Bauer, Steve Forbes, Orrin Hatch and John McCain have done
so. Bradley, Gore, Bush, Buchanan, Republican Alan Keyes and potential Reform
Party candidate Donald Trump have not.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is probably the worst performing group of front-runners, by a long
shot, since 1990" when the group began, Kimball said.
</P>
<P>
	   Founded by 40 leaders including former presidents Gerald Ford and Jimmy
Carter, Project Vote Smart has always encountered some resistance to its issues
test.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1998, only about 60 percent of congressional candidates got passing
grades. President Clinton and Republicans Buchanan and Forbes were among the
big-name presidential candidates who declined to fill out questionnaires in
1996.
</P>
<P>
	   But Bradley is a unique case. Though he submitted his resignation last
month, his name and picture still appear on Project Vote Smart's Web site under
"founders."
</P>
<P>
	   The group invited Bradley to join its board in 1996 as he prepared to leave
the Senate after three terms representing New Jersey. Bradley wrote back that he
would be "honored to support your efforts to strengthen representative
democracy."
</P>
<P>
	   As a board member, Bradley received periodic reports on Project Vote Smart
programs and annual budgets, as well as drafts of National Political Awareness
Tests. His silence was always taken as approval of the group's work, Kimball
said.
</P>
<P>
	   This year, Project Vote Smart supporters reached out to Bradley as a
candidate, encouraging him to fill out the questionnaire. During those
discussions, Bradley's staff learned that Bradley was still considered a member
of the Vote Smart board.
</P>
<P>
	   On Dec. 7, Bradley wrote to the group that when he became a candidate for
president, "I made an effort to resign from all the boards on which I sat. If
you do not believe that that has happened with Project Vote Smart's current
board, then please now consider this to be my resignation."
</P>
<P>
	   Kimball said he is holding out an eleventh-hour hope that many candidates,
including Bradley, will submit answers to the issues survey by next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
