<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Broadcaster Race Heats Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LONDON (AP) -- Hotel and TV network owner Granada Group confirmed Friday
that it might bid for one of its independent commercial television peers,
Carlton Communications or United News &AMP; Media.
</P>
<P>
	   The announcement had been expected ever since Carlton and United unveiled
plans for a $12.7 billion merger in late November, and heats up the race to
create what would be Britain's largest commercial broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
	   A ruling on whether the Carlton-United merger will be referred to Britain's
Competitions Commission is due soon. Granada said it would make its final
decision regarding any bid after the regulatory process has run its course.
</P>
<P>
	   Granada's chairman, Gerry Robinson, would not disclose whether his company
would prefer to bid for Carlton or United, noting that taking over either would
benefit Britain's Independent Television, or ITV.
</P>
<P>
	   ITV, Britain's oldest commercial network, was set up as a rival to the
British Broadcasting Corp., or BBC, in the form of 15 regional franchises.
</P>
<P>
	   Granada, which owns four of the franchises, has long been pushing to create
a single ITV company that it feels would be a more formidable competitor.
</P>
<P>
	   Making a deal with either company would help prevent a north-south divide
within ITV, Robinson said, adding that a Carlton-United merger would create a
powerhouse in Britain's southern half.
</P>
<P>
	   The combined Carlton-United group would create Britain's largest commercial
broadcasting group, with six major ITV franchises covering about 65 percent of
Britain's households.
</P>
<P>
	   The group would own a number of interests in digital television
broadcasting, national newspapers and a string of local British TV franchises.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Carlton and United were believed to have been motivated by fears about
the possible arrival of a much larger rival from the United States. By merging,
they would become a more formidable takeover candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   Both Carlton and United said Friday that they remained committed to merging,
despite Granada's interest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1533 </TRAILER>
