<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Memorial' to slain boy is a mess, newspaper says  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - A park where a slain 8-year-old boy liked to
play that was later dedicated to his memory is more of an eyesore than a place
for children, the Connecticut Post reported Friday.
<P>
	   Litter, cigarette butts and broken glass are strewn across Leroy "B.J."
Brown Jr. Memorial Park, the newspaper said. The basketball court is marred by
3-inch cracks that sprout grass and moss, and only fragments of nets hang from
the rims.
</P>
<P>
	   Posts intended to keep vehicles out of the park have fallen or been removed,
benches are worn or missing seats and the shards of broken bottles - clear,
green and brown - glisten everywhere, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
	   Leroy and his mother, Karen Clarke, were killed Jan. 7, 1999, allegedly
because Leroy was planning to testify against Russell Peeler, a convicted drug
dealer accused of killing Ms. Clarke's boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors said Peeler's brother, Adrian Peeler, killed the boy and his
mother to keep Leroy silent. Jury selection in the brothers' trials began this
week; if convicted, both could face the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   Christopher Duby, a spokesman for Mayor Joseph P. Ganim, said improvements
are planned for the park, but said the volume of work in 1999 meant crews could
not get to it earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   He said work on parks would begin as soon as the winter ends, and said the
memorial would be high on the priority list.
</P>
<P>
	   "Even if it were just a typical park, it would be a high priority," Duby
said. "But the fact of whose memory it's being done in makes it more
(important). Nobody is blind to that."
</P>
<P>
	   State Rep. Robert T. Keeley Jr., D-Bridgeport, called the condition of the
park a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm very frustrated," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   At the nearby Boys and Girls Club, Executive Director Ken Bruno said he
hopes the park will be improved, for memory of the slain boy and for the
children who were affected by his death.
</P>
<P>
	   "The kids felt very strongly that we do something to memorialize him," he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
