<HEADLINE> Pat Buchanan to fight new debate rules  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - Presidential hopeful Pat Buchanan threatened Friday to
go to the Federal Election Commission to protest new rules that could keep him
out of televised debates this fall.
<P>
	   "This is a conspiracy designed to perpetuate monopoly control of the
presidency and the White House by the two dominant national parties," he said of
rules announced Thursday by a special debate commission. "We're going to fight
this in court and we're going to fight it in the court of public opinion, and I
can tell you right now we're going to win it."
</P>
<P>
	   The Commission on Presidential Debates, a nonpartisan group set up in 1987
as an impartial sponsor of the nationally televised debates, said they would be
limited to candidates showing at least 15 percent support in national polls.
</P>
<P>
	   That could leave Buchanan off the screen.
</P>
<P>
	   "This is about giving the American people a third choice other than these
two Xerox copies we get every four years, these Doublemint twins from
Washington, D.C.," he said after meeting with leaders of New York's Conservative
Party at a restaurant on Manhattan's East Side.
</P>
<P>
	   He introduced Putnam County real estate developer Edward Heelan as his New
York campaign chairman. Heelan said the campaign had submitted papers to appear
on primary ballots in 29 of New York's 31 congressional districts. The filing
deadline for the March 7 primary was midnight Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   Buchanan, who bolted the GOP to mount a campaign for the Reform Party
nomination, said he hoped to be on New York's Conservative, Right to Life and
Independence lines in the general election. The Independence Party is New York's
affiliate of the national Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
	   "If I can win those nominations, I think the Republican candidate, who I
expect to be Mr. Bush, will fold his tent and write off New York," Buchanan
declared. "It will be a Buchanan-Gore race for the state of New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Leaders of the tiny but politically influential Conservative Party have also
met with Republican hopefuls Steve Forbes and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
Buchanan said his meeting was cordial, but that the party leaders plan to wait
until September to decide whom to support.
</P>
<P>
	   Buchanan spoke as real estate developer Donald Trump, who is considering a
bid for the Reform Party presidential nomination, prepared to meet with
Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura, the party's highest elected official.
</P>
<P>
	   Buchanan said Ventura appeared to be leaning toward supporting Trump.
</P>
<P>
	   "But the truth is if you're going to beat Pat Buchanan, you've got to get in
the race," Buchanan said. "You've got to get down on the field, you can't just
make comments from the box office. And thus far no one has gotten into this race
to challenge us for the Reform Party nomination."
</P>
<P>
	   Buchanan also offered some thoughts on New York's Senate race, expected to
pit first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
	   "There could be a third party candidate running, Right to Life and Reform
and Conservative as well," he said. "Do not rule out the possibility of a
three-way race for the U.S. Senate from New York."
</P>
<P>
	   Buchanan declined to say whom the third-party candidate might be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 1536 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
