<HEADLINE> Mideast Delegates Hold Services  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- Delegates to the Mideast talks will take most of
the day off Saturday, which this year marks the end of the holy Muslim month of
Ramadan and is also the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
	   Syria's Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa plans to invite members of his
delegation to lunch to mark the Eid al-Fitr, according to a source close to the
Syrian delegation. The source said the Syrian delegates will remain in
Shepherdstown and plan to take most of the day off.
</P>
<P>
	   Traditional Jews in the Israeli delegation planned to hold Sabbath services
Friday evening and Saturday morning with a borrowed Torah.
</P>
<P>
	   Among those planning to attend the services at the Clarion Hotel, where the
Israeli and Syrian delegations are secluded during peace talks, are Foreign
Minister David Levy and Attorney General Elakhim Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
	   There is no synagogue within walking distance. The Torah scroll being used
Friday and Saturday was borrowed from a synagogue in Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
	   Observant Jews do not travel or work on the Sabbath.
</P>
