<HEADLINE> Incoming Coke CEO Continues Shakeup  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    ATLANTA (AP) -- Coca-Cola's incoming chief continued to shake things up
Friday, naming a new head of the company's critical European division, which
struggled through a costly contamination scare last year, and appointing a new
chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
	   It was the second and third such moves this week by Doug Daft. Many analysts
viewed the management shuffle as Daft's way of quickly putting together a new
team in time for his official takeover of the Atlanta-based soft drink giant in
April at the annual shareholders meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   "He's been in Atlanta since 1991 and is familiar with the system and the
players, so there isn't the normal waiting time you would normally get with a
new CEO," said Merrill Lynch analyst Douglas Lane. "And stay tuned, I think
there is more to come."
</P>
<P>
	   On Wall Street, Coca-Cola stock shot up more than 5 percent, rising $3 to
$60 a share Friday afternoon in a day of broad stock gains on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Daft was named as the successor to Coke's chairman and chief executive, M.
Douglas Ivester, last month immediately following Ivester's surprise retirement
announcement.
</P>
<P>
	   Daft picked Charles S. Frenette to take over the Greater Europe Group, which
includes 49 countries, following the retirement of William P. Casey. Frenette
also will become an executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
	   Frenette, 47, is currently the chief marketing officer. Taking his place
will be 44-year-old Stephen C. Jones, president of Coke subsidiary Minute Maid
since November and former deputy division president in Japan.
</P>
<P>
	   Both appointments must be approved by the board.
</P>
<P>
	   Casey was in charge of the European division when the company underwent a
massive product recall in Belgium and France last year due to a health scare.
But Coke spokesman Rob Baskin said Casey had long been contemplating retirement
was not being forced out or punished for the European problems.
</P>
<P>
	   "Absolutely not," Baskin said. "This seemed like a good time to do it, what
with Doug Daft organizing for the future and putting his own team in place."
</P>
<P>
	   Frenette oversaw the creation of the company's new marketing strategy, which
is to be slowly unveiled over the next few months. Coke has already introduced
new glass bottles, and a presentation is expected to be made to the company's
bottlers next week in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
	   But many experts were not concerned that Frenette was taking a different job
at such a critical point.
</P>
<P>
	   "He was also on the ground a lot in Belgium during the recall and was more
hands-on in terms of fixing the problem than any other one guy," Lane said. "And
the (marketing) plans are already in place ... they just need to be
implemented."
</P>
<P>
	   On Tuesday, Daft announced that the company's highest-ranking black
executive had reversed his decision to retire at the end of this year. Carl Ware
instead will become an executive vice president in charge of a new division
overseeing global public and governmental relations.
</P>
<P>
	   Analyst David Goldman of Banc of America Securities said the moves should
also "build the ranks."
</P>
<P>
	   "Coke may have had a problem when it came to depth in management, and Doug
is moving quickly to correct that problem," Goldman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
