<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jobless Rate Steady at 4.1 Percent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    WASHINGTON (AP) -- A burst of hiring at department stores and construction
companies helped keep the nation's unemployment rate at a 30-year low of 4.1
percent in December, marking a strong finish for a year in which Americans
enjoyed the best labor market since the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
	   Employers added 315,000 jobs to their payrolls last month, the largest gain
since July. Big increases came at department stores, enjoying their best holiday
sales season in seven years, and construction companies, basking in a building
boom brought on by warmer-than-usual weather.
</P>
<P>
	   "The century ended on a high note for workers," said First Union chief
economist David Orr. He noted that the gain in payroll jobs was far above the
240,000 increase many economists had expected.
</P>
<P>
	   December's jobless rate of 4.1 percent matched the year's low reached in
November. That level is better than any since unemployment stood at 3.9 percent
in January 1970, the Labor Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   For all of 1999, the unemployment rate averaged 4.2 percent, the best since
a 3.5 percent jobless average in 1969. In 1998, the unemployment rate averaged
4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   "The opportunities for employment and for upgrading jobs in 1999 were the
best workers have seen in 30 years," said Ken Mayland, chief economist for
KeyCorp.
</P>
<P>
	   Strong economic growth is keeping unemployment down to levels most workers
haven't seen since they took their first jobs, economists said. And that's
helping workers who historically have had a harder time finding jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   President Clinton hailed 1999's performance for producing "the lowest annual
unemployment rates for African-Americans and Hispanics ever recorded." The
annual average unemployment rate for blacks in 1999 was 8 percent and for
Hispanics 6.4 percent, Labor Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
	   In December, employers boosted jobs and wages by bigger-than-expected
amounts, which caused economists to worry that strong job and wage growth could
trigger inflation down the road.
</P>
<P>
	   "We're creating jobs faster than workers, and the Fed is right that this
can't go on forever," said Bill Cheney, chief economist for John Hancock.
</P>
<P>
	   Friday's jobless report adds to the likelihood that Federal Reserve
policy-makers will raise interest rates, by at least a quarter of a point, at
their next meeting in February, many economists said. The central bank bumped up
interest rates three times last year to slow the economy and keep inflation at
bay.
</P>
<P>
	   Merrill Lynch's chief economist Bruce Steinberg said the
stronger-than-expected 315,000 jobs created in December "all but guarantees the
Fed will tighten monetary policy on Feb. 2."
</P>
<P>
	   Stock investors seemed to take the report in stride. The Dow Jones
industrial average gained more than 200 points late in the session, and the
Nasdaq index, regaining ground lost in major selloffs earlier this week, was up
by close to 110.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond prices fell as the yields on the bellwether 30-year Treasury bonds
climbed to 6.57 percent from 6.55 percent late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   December's 315,000 additional payroll jobs followed a gain of 222,000 in
November. Department stores hired 34,000 people last month, their first increase
since April. Construction companies added 16,000 jobs, while engineering and
management firms hired a larger-than-normal 23,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
	   Payrolls grew briskly in other industries as well. Bars and restaurants
hired 27,000 workers; health-care providers added 16,000, an above-average gain;
and financial services, including insurance and real-estate, added 12,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
	   But manufacturers lost 1,000 jobs in December, bringing their total job loss
for 1999 to 248,000. The manufacturing job loss has slowed in recent months as
U.S. exporters began to see a revival in foreign demand from countries
recovering from the global currency crisis of 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
	   For all of 1999, employers added 2.7 million jobs, compared with 2.9 million
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, average hourly earnings, a key gauge of inflation pressures, grew
by 0.4 percent to $13.46 in December, the biggest jump in three months. That
followed a tiny 0.1 percent rise in November.
</P>
<P>
	   While strong wage and job growth are good developments for workers,
economists and members of the Federal Reserve worry that the combination could
eventually trigger inflation. Their shared fear: that employers trying to
attract scarce workers to fill job openings will lure them with higher wages and
benefits -- increased costs that could drive up consumer prices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
