<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Resolve Pension Dispute  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court said Friday it will decide whether
employee benefit plans can sue brokers and others who provide services for their
roles in deals that make the plan lose money.
</P>
<P>
	   At issue is whether Ameritech Corp. and its pension plan trustee, Harris
Trust and Savings Bank, can recover some $20 million lost in a deal with Salomon
Brothers Inc., a stock brokerage that is now part of Citigroup Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   In the late 1980s, Salomon sold $21 million worth of interests in a
financial deal involving two motel chains to Ameritech's pension plan. The plan
lost nearly all of its investment in the deal after the motel chains failed.
</P>
<P>
	   Ameritech and the bank that administers its pension plan sued. Among other
things, the lawsuit invoked a federal pension-protecting law, alleging that the
sale had been unfair and a ``prohibited transaction'' under the federal Employee
Retirement Income and Security Act (ERISA).
</P>
<P>
	   Salomon contended it could not be sued under ERISA because it, unlike Harris
Trust and Savings Bank, owed no fiduciary duty to the pension plan.
</P>
<P>
	   A federal trial judge allowed the lawsuit but the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals reversed that ruling and threw out the case.
</P>
<P>
	   The Ameritech pension plan's only option would be to sue its trustee for
engaging in the deal since Salomon owed no legal duty to the plan, the appeals
court said.
</P>
<P>
	   But six other federal appeals courts have allowed such lawsuits even in the
absence of a so-called fiduciary duty.
</P>
<P>
	   The Supreme Court's decision, expected by late June, should resolve the
conflict among the federal appeals courts.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Harris Trust and Savings Bank vs. Salomon Brothers, 99-579.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1548 </TRAILER>
