<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Rise Sharply  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures rose Friday on the Chicago Board
of Trade in a rally driven by weather forecasts and a variety of technical
reasons.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn led the gains, bursting to eight-week highs as steadily rising prices
gave evidence of a possible end to the long downward trend.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat prices pushed higher in sympathy with corn. They also got support from
a forecast for record warm temperatures next week in the Great Plains, home to a
significant winter wheat crop.
</P>
<P>
	   Soybeans also advanced, although gains were limited by forecasts for rain in
crop areas of South America this weekend and again at midweek.
</P>
<P>
	   Wheat for March delivery rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.51 3/4 a bushel; March corn
rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.07 a bushel; March oats rose  1/2 cent to $1.09 1/2 a
bushel; March soybeans rose 3 1/4 cents to $4.78 3/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Beef futures advanced on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, while pork futures
were mixed.
</P>
<P>
	   February live cattle rose .80 cent to 70.87 cents a pound; March feeder
cattle rose .50 cent to 86.87 cents a pound; February lean hogs rose .45 cent to
55.62 cents a pound; February frozen pork bellies fell .08 cent to 82.22 cents a
pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
