<HEADLINE> Kohl Party Tries To Win Back Voters  </HEADLINE>
   By TONY CZUCZKA Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NORDERSTEDT, Germany (AP) -- Germany's conservatives are trying to win back
voters disaffected by Helmut Kohl's slush fund scandal with an anti-tax campaign
in a northern state that holds elections next month.
</P>
<P>
	   The Schleswig-Holstein vote will be the first test of how the Christian
Democrats are weathering the scandal -- and they've already told Kohl not to
campaign in the state.
</P>
<P>
	   By opposing an unpopular new gasoline tax that took effect Jan. 1, party
leaders hoped to tap into public discontent and revive their chances of
unseating Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's Social Democrats in the local election.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolfgang Schaeuble, party chief since Kohl's 1998 election defeat, sought to
rally the Christian Democrats at a two-day strategy session of their national
leadership that began Friday in this town outside Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
	   Kohl skipped the session, unusual for a man who rarely missed a meeting
during the 25 years he ran the party largely as a one-man show. No reason was
given.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're not giving up on the political contest,'' Schaeuble said.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier Friday, gubernatorial candidate Volker Ruehe handed out leaflets
against the energy tax, calling it an ``unbearable burden on the people'' and
``economic rubbish.''
</P>
<P>
	   Yet Kohl's troubles remain a heavy burden. The former chancellor has angered
many in his party by admitting he solicited up to $1 million in political
donations from 1993-98 and illegally kept them off the books.
</P>
<P>
	   He has refused to name the donors, despite repeated appeals by his party to
help clear up the scandal. Prosecutors opened a criminal probe against Kohl this
week for possible breach of trust.
</P>
<P>
	   Before the scandal erupted, the Christian Democrats had high hopes of
extending a string of election victories and winning in Schleswig-Holstein.
</P>
<P>
	   Ruehe acknowledged the danger that the Feb. 27 state ballot would become ``a
referendum about mistakes made by the Christian Democrats at the federal
level.''
</P>
<P>
	   Both Schaeuble and Ruehe -- top aides to Kohl during his 16 years as
chancellor -- are edging away from their former boss after some initial
reluctance.
</P>
<P>
	   With growing exasperation, Schaeuble said the party may have to accept that
Kohl will ignore its repeated appeals to name the anonymous donors -- and must
try to move on.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Of course, we were not happy when he said he would stick by his opposing
point of view,'' Schaeuble said. ``We can't do anything about it. We can't force
him.''
</P>
<P>
	   Ruehe said he kept Kohl out of the campaign because he wanted to put ``the
accent on the new party leadership.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Helmut Kohl told me already in early December that I had a free hand in
the matter,'' said Ruehe, who was defense minister under Kohl.
</P>
<P>
	   Schroeder opens his party's campaign in the state capital Kiel on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
