<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rise in crime really a product of cooked books  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - In the New York Police Department, where crime
statistics can make or break a supervisor's career, the numbers from one
Brooklyn precinct were alarming: a 19 percent jump in crime last year.
<P>
	   But it wasn't the current head of the 88th Precinct who suffered for the
increase. His predecessor, police acknowledged Friday, had underreported crime
figures from the year before, creating the apparent crime wave in the Fort
Greene section.
</P>
<P>
	   Capt. Charles F. Dowd, who was promoted because of his work in the 88th
Precinct, was transferred out of his new job and denied an expected promotion
when the skewed numbers became public knowledge. The New York Times first
reported the discrepency on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   According to The Times, at least five police commanders have been questioned
about the veracity of their statistics since 1996. The use of crime statistics
in planning police activity is one factor in the dramatic dropoff in the city
crime rate, which is now at a 30-year low.
</P>
<P>
	   Dowd apparently misclassified felony cases as less-important misdemeanor
cases. The result: robberies were down from 606 in 1997 to 399 in 1998; assaults
were down from 263 to 188; grand theft was down from 292 to 207.
</P>
<P>
	   When the numbers went up in 1999, new Capt. James Guida appeared in trouble.
Robberies appeared to jump from 399 to 470, assaults went from 188 to 195, and
grand theft increased from 207 to 326. An internal police audit turned up the
reason for the shocking increase.
</P>
<P>
	   Dowd, who kept his captain's rank, was never charged with any wrongdoing. He
is now in a non-command job at a Queens precinct.
</P>
<P>
	   Police Commissioner Howard Safir, who initially told The Times that Dowd
"was dumped because he was playing with the statistics," later said that Dowd
had not willfully misled the department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 1610 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
