</P>
<P>
	   Tech Stocks Strong Despite Lucent
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks rose today despite Lucent
Technologies' disclosure late yesterday that the company won't meet
most profit forecasts for the final quarter of 1999. Lucent fell in
late trading on other markets and was trading today at 52 15/16,
down 16 1/16 from Thursday's close on the New York Stock Exchange.
Lucent's troubles were apparently seen as a gain for its main
rivals in supplying speedy fiber-optic equipment for the
communications networks that make up the Internet. Nortel Networks
was up 14 9/16 at 91 9/16 on the NYSE, while in heavy Nasdaq
trading, Cisco Systems was up 3 3/16 at 103 3/16, Ciena was up 14
1/16 at 59 15/16 and JDS Uniphase was up 17 1/4 at 167.
</P>
<P>
	   European Stocks Close Higher
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Technology and telecommunications stocks staged a
comeback today, reversing a week of declines in most European
markets. The Dow Jones Industrial Average posted strong gains
throughout the session, providing an extra boost for bourses. The
Dow Jones Stoxx Index of 606 European companies closed up 2.1
percent at 359.75, while the Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended up
3.2 percent at 395.36. The telecom sector of the Dow Jones Stoxx
Index rose 3.4 percent, while the technology sector gained 3.7
percent. The Paris CAC 40 index ended up 1.6 percent at 5,539.61.
Spain's IBEX-35 share index rose 2.2 percent to 11,102.40 as
utilities GasNatural and Union Fenosa posted strong gains. Union
Fenosa rose 5.3 percent. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX index reversed four
consecutive days of losses to end 4.7 percent higher at 6,780.96.
SAP boosted the index up 18.5 percent after the company released
positive fourth-quarter figures.
</P>
<P>
	   Y2K Glitch Hits Some Credit Cards
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Buyers beware: Your credit card might get
charged more than once because some merchants failed to update
their computer software for the Year 2000. Visa and Mastercard said
today they have checks in place to catch duplicate charges, but
they suggest that customers review their credit card statements
anyhow. A vast majority of transactions are going through without
problems, they added. The problem is being caused by outdated IC
Verify software from CyberCash, which makes electronic transaction
processing software. The company offered free fixes last year, but
some merchants didn't get them.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton Asks Anti-Cyber-Terror Funds
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pledging to defend against ``those who would
use cyberspace to do us harm,'' President Clinton said today he
will ask Congress for $91 million to develop new technologies to
combat cyber-terrorists. Speaking to reporters before departing to
West Virginia for Middle East peace talks, Clinton said the New
Year's Y2K threat underscored ``how really interconnected we all
are'' -- and revealed how one person can use a computer for good or
sinister purposes. ``There has never been a time like this, in
which we have the power to create knowledge and the power to create
havoc, and both those powers rest in the same hands,'' Clinton
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Taiwan Chipmaker Buying Second Co.
</P>
<P>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Taiwan's largest computer chipmaker,
Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Co., said Friday it will buy the
island's third largest producer in a stock swap that analysts
valued at more than $3 billion. With an earlier deal, the purchase
will make TSMC the world's largest chip foundry. TSMC's agreement
to buy Worldwide Semiconductor Manufacturing Corp. follows recent
speculation that Taiwan's No. 2 company, United Microelectronics
Corp., had been courting Worldwide. The deal will put pressure on
United Microelectronics to find its own merger partner, said Nathan
Emerson, director of ABN Amro Asia Investment Consultancy in
Taipei.
</P>
<P>
	   Accounting Firm Violations Found
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Five partners of PricewaterhouseCoopers LLP
and a slightly larger number of other employees are said to have
been dismissed as a result of a review led by an independent
consultant. The review found that nearly half the partners at the
accounting giant reported having violated rules prohibiting them
from owning stock in companies they audit. The review made public
by the Securities and Exchange Commission also said many more such
lapses were said not to have been reported. A
PricewaterhouseCoopers managing partner, Kenton J. Sicchitano, told
The New York Times that in addition to the dismissals, other
employees were disciplined but not fired. He declined to give
names.
</P>
<P>
	   Army May Dump Ad Agency
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Army said today it may dump its
advertising agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam Inc. of New York, which has
held the account for 12 years. In what it billed as a ``dramatic
series of changes'' in how it markets itself to America's youth,
the Army said it hired a Chicago consulting firm, Jones-Lundin
Associates Inc., to help it select an ad agency for a new contract
that, unlike the existing arrangement, would pay the agency based
on how many recruits it attracts. The Army said Young &AMP; Rubicam is
welcome to compete for the new contract. The agency's current
five-year contract is due to expire in July. Officials said it was
unclear whether that contract would be terminated early.
</P>
<P>
	   Hong Kong May End Rice Import Limit
</P>
<P>
	   HONG KONG (AP) -- War fears are out, free trade is in. Rice is
out, hamburgers are in. And Hong Kong's rice import controls --
imposed 45 years ago to secure a steady wartime food supply -- could
soon be history. As Hong Kong moves into the 21st century with an
eye on high-technology as a future anchor of the economy, the
government is considering dismantling the rigid set of rules on
rice export and stockpiling.
</P>
<P>
	   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
	   Unemployment: unchanged at 4.1 percent
</P>
<P>
