<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Christmas for Beleaguered Copts  </HEADLINE>
   By DONNA BRYSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   EL-KUSHEH, Egypt (AP) -- Coptic Christmas passed without celebration in this
mostly Christian corner of southern Egypt.
</P>
<P>
	   No one came to Father Markos Abdel-Masih's midnight Mass. His parishioners
have been too afraid to leave their homes after dark -- even to pray for peace
-- since an outbreak of Muslim-Christian fighting.
</P>
<P>
	   Instead of Mass, Father Gabriel Abdel-Masih officiated at a Christmas Eve
funeral for the 21st victim, a 25-year-old civil servant who died of gunshot
wounds.
</P>
<P>
	   Early Friday, when el-Kusheh would normally have been crowded with thousands
of Christmas worshippers, the only sign of life drifted down from windows far
above the darkened streets. It was the faint, televised voice of Coptic Pope
Shenouda preaching from his cathedral in Cairo, 275 miles to the north.
</P>
<P>
	   ``All those people who died -- how can we forget?'' said Gabriel
Abdel-Masih, who shares with the priest a name common among Egyptian Christians.
``It is only the Lord who can resolve the tensions between people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Copts, whose independent church broke away from the Byzantine Orthodox
church in the sixth century, are the largest religious minority in predominantly
Muslim Egypt. Nationwide, they make up about 10 percent of the population of 60
million. But in el-Kusheh they are by far in the majority, and a relative
prosperous one.
</P>
<P>
	   El-Dabba Michael Habib, a shop owner, said there was no warning before his
Muslim neighbors shot his 17-year-old son Waiel on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   From his father's house down the street, Habib and his wife watched as the
top floor of their four-story apartment building erupted in flames. Waiel and
his aunt were in an apartment on the second floor.
</P>
<P>
	   Habib watched as Waiel jumped from the second floor and ran toward him.
Habib opened the door to find a mob chasing his son and shooting at him, hitting
him 12 times.
</P>
<P>
	   ``He was bleeding a lake of blood,'' Habib sobbed. Police stood by
helplessly while the attackers kept him from taking his son to a doctor, Habib
said. The aunt was able to flee to safety.
</P>
<P>
	   To help tell his story Friday, Habib pulled out the blood-stiffened gowns he
and his wife were wearing when Waiel died in their arms.
</P>
<P>
	   Like many Muslims in el-Kusheh, police officer Abdul Sohour said the attacks
were not set off by widespread religious hatred, but by ``fights between
families.''
</P>
<P>
	   The government, often reluctant to discuss religious intolerance, has blamed
the violence on ``conflicting reactions between Muslims and Christians on
business matters.''
</P>
<P>
	   Police said Friday that 15 Muslim suspects had been arrested. No violence
has been reported since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I am so sad about the people who were killed, the Christians, because they
are like my brothers,'' said Abdul Nasser Abdul Rady, a Muslim shopkeeper.
</P>
<P>
	   Coptic families described being attacked for about two hours beginning at
10:30 a.m. Sunday, when Mass let out. All could identify many of their attackers
-- neighbors they had known amicably for years.
</P>
<P>
	   ``They stole everything in the house, and what they couldn't steal, they
burned,'' Habib said. ``I wish they had taken everything I had, but left me my
son.''
</P>
<P>
	   Father Abdel-Masih said animosity has lurked beneath cordial
Christian-Muslim relations since he was a child. From time to time, he said,
violence erupts when groups of Copts and Muslims take sides in conflicts between
individuals.
</P>
<P>
	   The priest said last week's trouble, which began two days after a dispute
between a Coptic merchant and a Muslim shopper, appeared orchestrated.
</P>
<P>
	   Since Sunday, black-uniformed officers from the elite national State
Security force have been patrolling in armored vehicles and on foot.
</P>
<P>
	   Copt victims said they did not believe their trust would ever be revived. In
an ironic coincidence of faiths, their Christmas this year fell on the day that
ended Ramadan, the Muslim holy month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1618 </TRAILER>
