<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 16:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trucks Dominate Detroit Auto Show  </HEADLINE>
    By JUSTIN HYDE AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   DETROIT (AP) -- If there's one message that will be heard loud and clear
over the glad crowing of automakers at this year's Detroit auto show, it's this:
The car of the future is a truck.
</P>
<P>
	   From hulking four-door pickups to micro-sport utility vehicles and station
wagons on steroids, trucks will dominate the turntables of the 2000 North
American International Auto Show, just as they dominated the sales charts in
1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Yet industry watchers point to some warning lights such as rising
competition and fuel prices that may make the vehicles a tougher sell.
</P>
<P>
	   All the large American manufacturers, along with several Asian and European
automakers, will show off new production models and concept vehicles at the
show, which begins media previews Sunday. The emphasis on trucks is so strong
that the hometown gang -- General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co. and the Chrysler
division of DaimlerChrysler AG -- have no major passenger car introductions
scheduled.
</P>
<P>
	   The companies can say they're just giving consumers what they're asking for.
SUVs were the fastest growing segment in 1999, up 15 percent over the previous
year, according to Morgan &AMP; Co. in West Olive, Mich. Trucks accounted for 58
percent of the 11.6 million vehicles sold by GM, Ford and Chrysler in 1999 --
and probably a much larger percent of their vehicle profits.
</P>
<P>
	   Jim O'Connor, Ford division president, noted that more than 40 new SUV
models have been introduced since 1991, and that at least 10 more are due out in
the next two to three years.
</P>
<P>
	   "Everyone wants a piece of this action," he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Why the boom in trucks? One reason is the "wealth effect" -- a term covering
all the benefits of a strong economy, such as low unemployment, low interest
rates for car loans, a strong stock market and even good mortgage rates that
allowed some consumers to refinance and use home equity to buy vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   That wealth allows consumers to buy more expensive vehicles and to keep more
vehicles parked outside their homes. Ken Cherven, an analyst with The Polk
Company, found that trucks and SUVs were often the second vehicle in a family,
and that 61.5 percent of U.S. households owned more than one vehicle in 1998.
</P>
<P>
	   Another reason is the increase in households with children. Analyst Michael
Ward with Salomon SmithBarney found that increases in SUV sales in the 1990s ran
parallel to the boom in children under 14.
</P>
<P>
	   "The SUV segment has been pulling customers from the traditional family
sedan market," Ward said in a November report.
</P>
<P>
	   For the Detroit auto show, considered the most important event of its kind
in North America, automakers have prepared several new truck and SUV models.
</P>
<P>
	   GM has already shown its Pontiac Aztek SUV and Chevrolet Avalanche truck-SUV
combo; it will also have further details about its deal with AM General, the
maker of the monster Hummer SUV. Chrysler will unveil new versions of its
minivans. Ford will display a new mini-SUV, its entry against models already on
the market from Honda and Toyota.
</P>
<P>
	   Toyota and Honda will show off new SUVs heading for production, while Audi,
Subaru and even Volkswagen will show off SUV and pickup concept vehicles.
</P>
<P>
	   While experts say total U.S. vehicle sales in 2000 could decline slightly
from a record 16.9 million in 1999, it could also be the year that automakers
sell more trucks than cars. They came close in 1999, with trucks accounted for
48.5 percent of sales.
</P>
<P>
	   But with all the new models entering the market, automakers may have to
reduce the profit margins to stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
	   "If history is any indication, companies won't let vehicles sit on their
lots, and price will be the competing mechanism," Cherven said. "There's
certainly some potential benefit to consumers if some of those segments become
overly competitive."
</P>
<P>
	   Rising gasoline prices also could be a threat to truck and SUV sales. Art
Spinella, an industry sales analyst with CNW Marketing Research in Bandon, Ore.,
said GM, Ford and Chrysler could feel a pinch if customers switch back to more
fuel-efficient cars.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's short-sighted, because effectively what they're doing is giving up the
car market," he said. "They're releasing the car market to the Japanese and
Europeans."
</P>
<P>
	   But many of the newer SUVs are designed to deliver better fuel economy. In
his report, Ward predicted that given a strong economy and stable demographics,
truck and SUV sales would show little signs of weakening in 2000.
</P>
<P>
	   "Fuel prices certainly are a risk to the SUV market, but we believe that
increasing gas prices would only shift the mix toward minivans -- kids don't
disappear in a recession or when fuel costs are higher," Ward said.
</P>
<P>
	   The show opens to the public on Jan. 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1624 </TRAILER>
