<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Soprano Debuts as Butterfly  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    An AP Arts and Entertainment Review
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Sylvie Valayre made her Metropolitan Opera debut in the
title role of "Madama Butterfly," touchingly conveying emotions though her voice
is not supremely sweet.
</P>
<P>
	   The slim French soprano used vibrato to add vocal texture to her role as a
young Japanese woman deeply in love. She sank to her knees often and as
naturally as though she'd done it all her life. Applause for her was lavish.
</P>
<P>
	   Valayre, who is from Paris, has sung the role in San Francisco and Naples.
She made her La Scala debut in 1996 in "La Gioconda."
</P>
<P>
	   Conductor Marcello Viotti also made his debut, shaping the Puccini music
with care. Viotti was born in Switzerland to Italian parents, lives in France
and is a guest conductor at European opera houses and principal conductor of the
Bavarian Radio Orchestra in Germany.
</P>
<P>
	   Vladimir Galouzine sang Pinkerton. His was not the portrayal of a man too
young to realize what he's doing. His Pinkerton acts confident that it is his
right as an American Navy lieutenant to marry a Japanese woman, then leave her
and have a "real" marriage at home. Galouzine's singing, straightforward, loud
and without nuances, complements the portrayal, though musically it's
uninteresting.
</P>
<P>
	   William Shimell sang the American consul. His warning advice to Pinkerton
that Butterfly trusts him and he should be careful with her came across as
unusually tentative and wimpy, as it bounced off Pinkerton's strong confidence.
</P>
<P>
	   Bernard Fitch ably sang Goro, the marriage broker. When he sings something
not terribly important, early in Act 1, his music is beautiful, reaching heights
that some operas do not at their best moments.
</P>
<P>
	   Suddenly one realizes why "Madama Butterfly" is such a popular opera.
Between its big numbers -- such as the love duet which ends Act 1 and
Butterfly's "Un bel di" -- the connecting music is one beautiful melody after
another.
</P>
<P>
	   Jane Bunnell sang Suzuki, Butterfly's devoted maid, with compassion and
devotion in her voice. Their voices blended admirably. James Courtney as
Butterfly's uncle was frightening, arriving just after the wedding and singing
his denunciation of the bride.
</P>
<P>
	   Baritone Richard Hobson sounded stalwart in his Met debut in the small part
of the rich man who wants to marry the deserted Butterfly. Marie Zifchak's part,
Pinkerton's American wife, is so small her voice couldn't be judged. However, a
director put her unnecessarily close to Butterfly when the latter is beginning
to realize what Pinkerton has done.
</P>
<P>
	   This cast will sing the opera four more times. "Butterfly" will be broadcast
live on Feb. 26, with a different cast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1636 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Life Cereal To Revive Mikey Ads  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    CHICAGO (AP) -- "Mikey" is coming back.
</P>
<P>
	   The finicky kid who wouldn't eat his breakfast -- unless it was Life cereal
-- is returning to television, but this time as a grownup.
</P>
<P>
	   The rejiggered reprise of one of TV's most famous advertising campaigns
represents the latest move by the ad industry to bring back its past icons. In
recent months, viewers have become reacquainted with the Green Giant, Charmin's
Mr. Whipple, StarKist's Charlie the Tuna and others.
</P>
<P>
	   The Mikey ad campaign is being relaunched more than a quarter-century after
its debut with an all-adult cast as an appeal to the baby boomers' bent for
nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
	   The lines are the same, the shtick is the same and so is the product. Only
the actors playing Mikey and his breakfast mates are new.
</P>
<P>
	   Quaker Oats Co., which makes Life, hopes the new Mikey can work some old
magic on a product now facing fiercer-than-ever competition from endless rows of
cereals lining supermarket shelves.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Mikey ad has the kind of charm that bridges across time," says Gary
Rosenbaum, creative director of ad agency Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding, which
resurrected Mikey.
</P>
<P>
	   The original Mikey ad was "the best kid commercial ever," said David Lubars,
president of the Fallon, McElligott ad agency in Minneapolis, who has no
connection to either ad. "It was a combination of a good idea and because the
kid was so likable," he said. "There's something magic about it. You can't plan
for that."
</P>
<P>
	   The commercial is to be launched Jan. 17 and run through June.
</P>
<P>
	   In the original ad, which aired from 1972-84, two kids share their suspicion
of a cereal that's "sposed ta be good for ya." They decide to test it out on
Mikey, because "he hates everything."
</P>
<P>
	   But pudgy-faced Mikey, who never utters a word, takes to it, prompting the
famous lines: "He likes it! Hey, Mikey!"
</P>
<P>
	   The ad agency heeded research, which found that 70 percent of adults could
identify the Life cereal ad from just a brief description. The ad placed No. 10
in TV Guide's list of "The 50 Greatest Commercials of All Time."
</P>
<P>
	   So why not bring back a freckled 3-year-old, like the one who filmed the
spot with his two brothers in 1971?
</P>
<P>
	   Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding executives say they wanted to add a twist. They
selected a handsome Mikey in his 20s -- New York-based actor Jimmy Starace --
who eats Life as he sits reading his morning newspaper, alongside a man and
woman. In the spirit of the original, all three act like kids.
</P>
<P>
	   The original Mikey was assured by Quaker that he would remain anonymous in
publicity associated with the campaign's return. But icons, even former ones,
find it hard to escape the media.
</P>
<P>
	   Tracked down at New York radio station WKTU where he works as an advertising
account manager, John Gilchrist, now 31, said he remains under contract to
Quaker and couldn't say much.
</P>
<P>
	   "It never ends, it seems," he said of Americans' fascination with the
character.
</P>
<P>
	   Hey Mikey -- what about a reprise of that role?
</P>
<P>
	   "That would be nice. ... Hopefully you'll see me again."
</P>
<P>
	   It's unlikely the commercial will give Life back the lofty share of the
cereal business it once claimed. Quaker sold some $78 million worth of Life last
year, a respectable showing, and sales have grown in recent years. But cereals
proliferated in the 1990s, leaving Life a much smaller slice of an $8 billion
industry.
</P>
<P>
	   "Sometimes the best ideas are not the newest ideas," John McMillin, a food
industry analyst for Prudential Securities, said of the ad. "But I don't think
they can go to the well too many times with this."
</P>
<P>
	   Could Mikey help bring back the good old days for Life?
</P>
<P>
	   "If they can get Michael Jordan, maybe," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
