<HEADLINE> New Mudslides Feared in Venezuela  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Incessant rains in Venezuela could cause new
flooding and landslides, a top weather official said Friday, raising the
possibility of a repeat of the disaster that killed thousands of people last
month.
</P>
<P>
	   Air Force meteorology director Jose Pereira said the rains are causing a
``high risk'' situation on Avila, the mountain ridge that separates the capital
of Caracas from the Caribbean Sea. Landslides along the Avila on Dec. 15 killed
as many as 30,000 people.
</P>
<P>
	   Pereira said forecasters are predicting continued rains in the region,
``increasing the possibility of new mudslides.''
</P>
<P>
	   Currently, he said, there are light rains in the area. He warned residents
to be ready to move quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   The threat of landslides is especially acute in the state of Vargas, the
coastal zone hardest hit in December. The region has received 10 times the
normal rainfall.
</P>
<P>
	   Pereira said Mount Avila is now so saturated that if there is another heavy
rain, ``the consequences could be terrible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
