<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 16:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Clarify Bankruptcy Law  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court agreed Friday to clarify how difficult
it should be for states to collect money from bankrupt debtors who owe back
taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   An Illinois dispute over sales taxes owed on a $12 million jet centers on
the narrow and arcane issue of who carries the ``burden of proof'' in certain
bankruptcy cases. But the real-world consequences are considerable, and spurred
nine other states to urge the court to resolve the matter.
</P>
<P>
	   William J. Stoecker was president and sole director of Chandler Enterprises
Inc. when in 1988 the corporation bought a Falcon 50 airplane from an
out-of-state seller.
</P>
<P>
	   After Stoecker obtained a legal opinion that the purchase was exempt from
Illinois tax, Chandler Enterprises did not file any tax return on it.
</P>
<P>
	   The corporation also failed to register the plane with the Illinois
Department of Aviation, so it was years later that state officials decided
Chandler owed more than $900,000 in taxes and interest. By that time, Chandler
Enterprises had ceased to exist and Stoecker had filed for federal bankruptcy
protection.
</P>
<P>
	   State officials sought to a collect a penalty from the bankruptcy trustee
for Stoecker's estate, but a federal judge ruled that the trustee could not be
forced to pay.
</P>
<P>
	   The judge said the government had the burden of proving that Stoecker, as a
``responsible officer'' of Chandler Enterprises, had willfully failed to pay the
tax.
</P>
<P>
	   The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed that ruling, saying the
burden of proof was on Stoecker to prove he did not willfully avoid paying the
sales tax.
</P>
<P>
	   Stoecker' bankruptcy trustee then sought the Supreme Court's help.
</P>
<P>
	   In a friend-of-the-court brief, nine other states told the justices that the
7th Circuit court was correct but that the Supreme Court should definitively say
so to resolve conflicting rulings in lower courts.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The current split of authority could wreak havoc on state tax
administration and promote forum shopping in tax cases,'' the court was told by
lawyers for California, Montana, New Mexico, North Dakota, Ohio, Oklahoma,
Oregon, South Dakota and Vermont.
</P>
<P>
	   A decision is expected by late June.
</P>
<P>
	   The case is Raleigh vs. Illinois, 99-387.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
