<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge allows case to proceed; more layoffs planned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   MANCHESTER, Conn. (AP) - A federal judge has refused to dismiss a union
lawsuit trying to block Pratt &AMP; Whitney's restructuring plan, and will hear the
case next week.
<P>
	   The Machinists Union workers contend Pratt's plan to shift work among plants
violates their contract with the company.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. District Judge Janet C. Hall in Bridgeport on Thursday rejected a
request from the company that the case be dismissed. The company had argued that
she did not have jurisdiction to hear the case.
</P>
<P>
	   Machinists official James Parent said Hall has promised the union's lawyers
that she will make a decision relatively quickly after next week's trial.
</P>
<P>
	   That's important, Parent said, because a six-month notification period
required by the union's contract ends Feb. 16, and the company could go ahead
with its plans at that point.
</P>
<P>
	   "Once the work is moved out of Connecticut, it's really hard to change
that," Parent said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Pratt plans to reduce the work force at its North Haven plant from 2,700 to
about 100.
</P>
<P>
	   About 970 of the jobs would be moved to Pratt's East Hartford plant, while
some 200 overhaul and repair jobs would be transferred from North Haven to Pratt
plants in Arkansas, Oklahoma, and Texas. More than 300 other such jobs now done
in Connecticut would also be shifted, and there would be an unspecified number
of layoffs.
</P>
<P>
	   Pratt spokesman Mark Sullivan expressed confidence about the legal
situation.
</P>
<P>
	   "We maintain firmly that we have lived up to all our obligations to the
Machinists, and we believe very strongly that we will prevail at trial," he
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Pratt President Louis Chenevert told the Connecticut Business and
Industry Association's annual economic conference Thursday that the downturn in
the aerospace industry continues to hurt the company.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our airline customers today are struggling to make a profit," Chenevert
said, saying demand for large airplanes is only half of 1998's level of 1,200
orders.
</P>
<P>
	   Additional layoffs may be needed, but it's too early to tell how many,
Chenevert said.
</P>
<P>
	   "We will have to adjust, based on the volume reduction that we're seeing in
2000," he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
