<DOCNO> APW20000107.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Spending Sought for Farm Plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration proposed Friday to almost
double federal spending on farm conservation programs, both to help farmers cope
with depressed commodity prices and to reduce runoff that fouls many of the
nation's rivers.
</P>
<P>
	   The president's 2001 budget would authorize $1.3 billion in new agricultural
conservation spending, including $600 million in payments to farmers who
voluntarily act to prevent erosion on their land. It also would expand the
popular Conservation Reserve Program, which pays producers to take
environmentally sensitive acreage out of production.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We have been paying farmers for decades to grow commodities and, in some
cases, not to grow commodities. Now we must start thinking of the land itself as
our most valuable commodity,'' said Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman.
</P>
<P>
	   The Agriculture Department predicts that net farm income will drop $7.6
billion this year to $40.4 billion unless Congress steps in this fall with
another large infusion of federal aid. Lawmakers have done that the last two
years, and the administration hopes to steer at least some of the money this
year into conservation programs.
</P>
<P>
	   The 2001 budget also is expected to include some form of payments to be tied
to decreases in crop prices or farm income but the details have not been
finalized, officials said. The 2001 fiscal year begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
	   The centerpiece of the administration's conservation plan is the new $600
million subsidy program, introduced in Congress last year by Sen. Tom Harkin,
D-Iowa.
</P>
<P>
	   Payment levels under the ``Conservation Security Program'' would be based on
the scope of farmers' conservation measures. They could include planting grass
along streams and cutting back on livestock grazing.
</P>
<P>
	   An existing program that provides assistance for manure control and a
variety of other conservation measures would be increased from $174 million this
year to $325 million in 2001.
</P>
<P>
	   Other proposals include:
</P>
<P>
	   --Increasing the acreage cap in the Conservation Reserve Program from 3.6
million to 40 million acres. That would allow more than twice as much land to be
enrolled in the program during the 2001 fiscal year as would be permitted under
current law. It is by far USDA's biggest existing conservation program at $1.3
billion -- about $5,000 per farm.
</P>
<P>
	   --Expanding a program that pays farmers to restore wetlands by 210,000 acres
in 2001 and an additional 250,000 acres a year after that. The Wetlands Reserve
Program is currently limited to 975,000 acres.
</P>
<P>
	   Vice President Al Gore announced the conservation moves in a conference call
with reporters in Iowa, which is holding its presidential nominating caucuses
later this month. Gore said the proposals would provide a ``new source of
welcome income for farmers.''
</P>
<P>
	   They also would soften the blow of tougher environmental regulations that
the administration is considering.
</P>
<P>
	   The Environmental Protection Agency proposed last summer to require states
to submit plans to clean up every waterway that fails to meet water quality
standards. The administration is considering other measures to curb farm runoff
believed responsible for an oxygen-deprived ``dead zone'' in the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
	   The administration's plan ``recognizes that we must put more money into the
hands of landowners if we're going to clean up the nation's remaining polluted
rivers,'' said Scott Faber of American Rivers, a conservation group. ``There is
simply no way politically or logistically that we can regulate every landowner
in America.''
</P>
<P>
	   Farm-state lawmakers may not be as receptive to the plan. The proposals
would provide little immediate relief to farmers, and they would have to spend
some of their own money on conservation to qualify for the aid.
</P>
<P>
	   Grain prices collapsed in 1998 and Congress has provided farmers with $15
billion in consecutive bailouts over the past two years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1735 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 17:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge orders Internet porn site to drop Teen magazine's name  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) - At the request of Teen magazine, a federal judge has
ordered the operators of an Internet pornography site to stop using the
publication's name in its Web address.
<P>
	   "Our magazine is geared to teen girls, and when they find pornography
instead, you can well understand why not only our client would be upset, but our
readers would be upset. It's appalling," Teen magazine lawyer David Jacobs said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   The magazine's president, Lynn Lehmkuhl, said staff discovered the
pornography site in the last week of 1999, and soon heard from puzzled girls.
</P>
<P>
	   "I was horrified. It was really hardcore. Not even 'Playboy.' It was really,
really creepy," Lehmkuhl said.
</P>
<P>
	   The operator of the pornography site, Blue Gravity Communications, and its
owner, Thomas Krwawecz III, were temporarily restrained on Thursday from using
the address by U.S. District Judge Joseph E. Irenas.
</P>
<P>
	   The magazine's Web address is www.teenmag.com.
</P>
<P>
	   Irenas scheduled a hearing Jan. 14 on whether to impose an injunction
against Blue Gravity. He ruled, however, that Teen was likely to prevail because
it would be "irreparably injured" by the use of its name by another.
</P>
<P>
	   Blue Gravity representatives did not attend the hearing, Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
	   Krwawecz, of Pittsgrove, said the address was dormant until it was sold Dec.
9 to a Fort Lauderdale, Fla., company, Cyber Entertainment Network.
</P>
<P>
	   He said that Blue Gravity, of Pennsauken, is still registered as owner of
the address because of delays by the organization that registers the names,
Network Solutions.
</P>
<P>
	   At Cyber Entertainment Network, chief executive officer Joe Elkind said
Friday he could not immediately determine if they now owned the address. He said
his company operates 14 adult Web sites, and about 3,000 other sites that lead
to them.
</P>
<P>
	   The pornography Web site could not be reached Friday morning, but was
available later in the day.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit filed Thursday for Teen is among the first in the nation to rely
on federal law enacted in November to ban "cybersquatting," the practice of
pre-empting Internet domain names from people or companies with trademark
associations to them.
</P>
<P>
	   Domain names are the addresses that computer users enter to reach a Web
site. They come between "www" and "com," "net" or "org."
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit seeks to have the site transferred to the publishers of "Teen,"
and unspecified monetary compensation, including any profits the defendants made
from using the name.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit also cites trademark law, which has generally persuaded judges
in Web site disputes to side with the holder.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our client owns the trademark in Teen magazine, and is going to do
everything it can to protect its rights in Teen magazine, especially in this
case where the defendants have taken the name ... and linked it to a pornography
site," Jacobs said.
</P>
<P>
	   Teen, published since 1957, claims 2 million monthly subscribers with an
average age of 15, Lehmkuhl said.
</P>
<P>
	   The current paper edition features articles on "The Ultimate Crush List" and
"87 Hot Hair and Makeup Tips," while visitors to the Web site could click on
"Dumped? How to deal," and "Weather proof your hair."
</P>
<P>
	   In a cybersquatting case in 1998, a federal judge in Newark ruled that a New
Jersey man can criticize the Jews for Jesus group on the Internet, but he cannot
use the group's name as part of his Web site's address.
</P>
<P>
	   That followed a similar ruling in 1997, when a federal judge in New York
barred an antiabortionist from using Planned Parenthood's name on his Internet
site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 1736 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greek Govt Promises Border Security  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   THESSALONIKI, Greece (AP) -- The Greek government promised tougher border
security Friday after a truck carrying illegal immigrants crashed, killing six
people and injuring dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
	   About 80 immigrants entered Greece from Turkey in a stolen truck heading
west, police said. The driver apparently lost control of the vehicle near the
northern town of Komotini, about 140 miles northeast of Thessaloniki.
</P>
<P>
	   Police said the truck involved in Friday's crash had been speeding down a
small road to avoid highway inspections. The driver fled and was sought by
police. Survivors told police the driver had been drinking.
</P>
<P>
	   The predawn crash brought to at least 29 the toll of immigrants killed in
similar accidents over the last three months.
</P>
<P>
	   A senior security official reiterated plans to deploy 1,000 additional
border guards at frontier units early this year and said the coast guard will
receive extra equipment. The first 200 guards joined patrols along the Evros
River, which separates Turkey and Greece, on Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We believe these measures will limit the wave of illegal immigration,''
Dimitris Efstathiadis, general secretary of Greece's public order ministry, told
state-run NET television.
</P>
<P>
	   Tens of thousands of illegal immigrants from Asia and Eastern Europe attempt
to sneak into Greece each year. Many remain in Greece to find work, while others
attempt to make their way to nearby Italy and other European Union countries.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities say an estimated 15,000 immigrants entered Greece illegally over
the Evros River in 1999, up 10 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
	   Efstathiadis said Greece hoped to sign an immigration control deal with
rival Turkey later this year, but warned that tougher policing might prompt
people smugglers to use more reckless methods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1739 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Futures Fall Sharply  </HEADLINE>
    By The Associated Press
<TEXT>
<P>
	   Oil futures dropped sharply Friday on the New York Mercantile Exchange in a
continuing Y2K letdown and amid evidence that world producers are increasing
output.
</P>
<P>
	   Other energy commodities also fell.
</P>
<P>
	   In other markets, corn prices rose sharply and cocoa rose as a result of
concern over tensions in Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
	   Oil prices finished the week down $1.20 a barrel in a pullback blamed partly
on a lack of any Y2K-related supply disruptions as the new year began.
</P>
<P>
	   Accelerating the decline in oil prices were reports that production by the
Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries had risen in December,
suggesting compliance with last March's cutback agreement might be waning.
</P>
<P>
	   Light sweet crude oil for February delivery fell 56 cents Friday to $24.22 a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
	   "All things considered, I think prices have held up pretty well," said Bill
O'Grady, an energy analyst for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis. "I was afraid
we'd be in the $22-$23 range."
</P>
<P>
	   If OPEC's unity on production limits breaks, world supplies could increase
quickly. But key officials of various producing nations have insisted they will
adhere to quotas until the agreement on production curbs expires in March, and
likely beyond. The production limits were established in an effort to thin out a
one-time glut that sent oil prices spiraling as low as $11.26 a barrel last
February.
</P>
<P>
	   "If OPEC holds things together, I expect we'll see a recovery in prices
later on," perhaps as soon as next week, O'Grady said.
</P>
<P>
	   Also on the New York Merc, February heating oil fell 1.53 cents to 64.75
cents a gallon; February unleaded regular gasoline fell 1.79 cents to 66.10
cents a gallon; February natural gas fell 2.3 cents to $2.173 per 1,000 cubic
feet.
</P>
<P>
	   In London, North Sea Brent crude for February delivery fell 53 cents to
$23.09 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn led grains and soybeans sharply higher on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
	   Corn prices rose for a second straight day on Thursday's news that Brazil
had bought U.S. corn and as corn production estimates were down in Brazil and
Argentina -- bullish developments for U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
	   March corn rose 3 1/4 cents to $2.07 a bushel; March wheat rose 3 1/4 cents
to $2.51 3/4 a bushel; March oats rose  1/2 cent to $1.09 1/2 a bushel; March
soybeans rose 3 1/4 cents to $4.78 3/4 a bushel.
</P>
<P>
	   Cocoa prices pushed up an additional $12 to $853 a ton on New York's Coffee,
Sugar &AMP; Cocoa Exchange as investors took precautions against any weekend unrest
in Ivory Coast, the world's leading producer. A major opposition party failed to
join forces with the new government and talk increased of army dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
	   The developments come two weeks after a former army chief seized power in
the West African nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1739 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0227 </DOCNO>
