<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar slipped against the Japanese yen Friday, giving
up early gains as traders cashed in on the dollar's recent rebound to a
seven-week high.
</P>
<P>
	   A surge in U.S. stocks and comments from a Japanese official supported the
dollar early in the day, but the dollar failed to hold on to the gains against
the yen. Still, the dollar rose against the euro, British pound and Swiss franc.
</P>
<P>
	   In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 105.21 yen, down from
105.40 yen Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar's downturn against the yen late in the day came despite comments
early Friday in Tokyo by Japan's vice finance minister for international
affairs, Haruhiko Kuroda, who said "the yen is still too strong."
</P>
<P>
	   The Japanese government fears a strong yen will hamper a recovery from a
steep recession by making it more difficult for Japanese manufacturers to
compete in world markets. When the yen rises, Japanese goods become more
expensive and less attractive in foreign markets, unless manufacturers cut
prices and thereby reduce their profits to keep market share. A strong yen also
reduces the value of sales proceeds in foreign currencies.
</P>
<P>
	   A rally on Wall Street also helped lift the dollar against the Japanese
currency, continuing its recent trend. But with several days of gains already
this week, traders said the dollar was due for a little consolidation.
</P>
<P>
	   Trading was fairly quiet against the euro, which fell to $1.0276 in late New
York trading from $1.0315 late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The dollar also was quoted at 1.5652 Swiss francs, up from 1.5555, and
1.4560 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4589. The British pound fell to $1.6375
from $1.6480.
</P>
<P>
	   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no longer
traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. Based on Friday's
euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.9033 German marks, up from 1.8958; 6.3834
French francs, up from 6.3586; and 1,884.26 Italian lire, up from 1,877.07.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
