<HEADLINE> Windham County sheriff facing more charges  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   WINDHAM, Conn. (AP) - Windham County's high sheriff - charged four
months ago with embezzlement and racketeering - was arrested Friday on a new
round of charges, including corrupt election practices.
<P>
	   Thomas White surrendered to police Friday morning and was released after
posting a $5,000 bond, state police said.
</P>
<P>
	   White was charged with three counts of larceny including embezzlement,
racketeering and corrupt election practices, state police said. They would not
give any details of the allegations.
</P>
<P>
	   White pleaded innocent in September to two counts each of embezzlement,
tampering with a witness and unlawful restraint, and single counts of bribery of
a witness, hindering prosecution, conspiracy, coercion and racketeering.
</P>
<P>
	   Both arrests stem from an investigation which began in May 1998, state
police said.
</P>
<P>
	   "I have no idea what the specific allegations are, but I can tell you that
we deny them," said Art Meisler, White's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
	   White could not be reached for comment by The Associated Press. Messages was
left for him at his courthouse office in Danielson, at his home, and with a
paging service. He is due in court on Jan. 18.
</P>
<P>
	   White was elected high sheriff last November following a bitter Democratic
primary fight against former Sheriff Jay Kenney. White has been under
investigation in connection with a check he says he inadvertently deposited to a
personal account rather than a business account. The check was for between
$1,000 and $2,000.
</P>
<P>
	   White, 38, has said he repaid that money with interest. He has explained the
deposit as a mistake he made because he was never properly trained as a deputy
sheriff when he was appointed in 1995.
</P>
<P>
	   He has said his legal woes are related to efforts by Gov. John G. Rowland
and the Legislature to abolish the sheriff system.
</P>
<P>
	   Critics of the system say it is rife with corruption, mismanagement and
patronage.
</P>
<P>
	   In the past year, the high sheriffs have been hit with a spate of
embarrassments and scandal.
</P>
<P>
	   In addition to White's arrest in September, New London County High Sheriff
Gerard Egan was charged with keeping an uncertified assault weapon in his
courthouse office. Egan's department is also being investigated by the state's
Attorney General and other agencies for allegedly double-billing the state. Egan
also was ordered to pay a $4,000 fine for violating the state ethics code by
hiring his son and wife.
</P>
<P>
	   A female prisoner says she was raped by male inmates while they were being
transported in a New Haven County Sheriff Department van, and a black couple
says a Windham County special deputy sheriff chased them across the Rhode Island
border while firing his gun at them and yelling racist slurs.
</P>
<P>
	   The new charges against White are just another reason why the system should
be scrapped, some say.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's so blatantly ridiculous," said Joseph Antinerella, a former Hartford
County deputy sheriff who says he was passed over for reappointment because he
is a political enemy of the high sheriff.
</P>
<P>
	   "If this thing is shaking down in a small community like Windham County, you
can only imagine what's happening in a bigger city like Hartford," Antinerella
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 1753 </TRAILER>
