<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mazda Unveils Car-Like SUV  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Mazda Corp. on Friday unveiled the Tribute, a trim sport
utility vehicle that marks the company's first serious effort to crack the
growing SUV market.
</P>
<P>
	   Lexus and Lincoln Mercury also introduced new vehicles at the Greater Los
Angeles Auto Show.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tribute's success is considered important to the continued turnaround of
the Japanese carmaker that's controlled by Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
	   "The addition of the new Tribute to the Mazda lineup marks the company's
resurgence as a full-line manufacturer," said Richard Beattie, president and
chief executive officer of Mazda North American Operations.
</P>
<P>
	   From 1990-93, Mazda sold a version of the Ford Explorer, but dropped it and
has not had a replacement since. SUVs have dominated North American auto sales
in recent years, and grew 15 percent during 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Introduction of the Tribute is "something that's actually going to ensure
their existence. They haven't had an SUV and it's something that's urgently
needed," said George Peterson, an analyst with Auto Pacific Inc.
</P>
<P>
	   Mazda expects to build 20,000 Tributes in 2000 and up to 40,000 in 2001.
Versions intended for the U.S. market will be built at a Ford plant near Kansas
City, Mo., and should appear in showrooms by July, Beattie said. A Ford version
of the Tribute will be introduced next week at the North American International
Auto Show in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
	   Beattie declined to reveal the price tag, but said it will be close to the
cost of smaller SUVs. The target buyer, he said, is a 30-something couple with
two children, a household income of nearly $70,000 and an active lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tribute offers a three-liter, 200-horsepower V6 engine and independent
suspension in more expensive LS and ES models. The DX includes a 130-horsepower,
2-liter 4-cylinder engine.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tribute comes with front wheel drive and an optional "on-demand"
all-wheel-drive system that kicks in automatically if the front wheels begin to
slip.
</P>
<P>
	   At 172 inches long and 72 inches wide, it is 5.5 inches longer overall than
the Jeep Cherokee and 2 inches longer at the wheelbase. With back seats folded
down, it has 71.7 cubic feet of cargo space.
</P>
<P>
	   Mazda sales suffered during the early 1990s as Japan slid into recession. In
1996 Ford increased its investment in the Hiroshima-based company to a
controlling 33.4 percent and began cutting costs.
</P>
<P>
	   That, and improved sales, helped boost earnings to $126 million for the
fiscal year ending in September, up from $66 million a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
	   Lexus introduced its IS 300 compact sports sedan for North American sales in
a bid to lure younger buyers to the Toyota's luxury brand. The car, already
available in Japan, Europe and Australia, is designed to compete with the Audi
A4 and BMW 3-series sedans.
</P>
<P>
	   The IS 300 features a three-liter, 215-horsepower inline six cylinder
engine. The five-speed automatic transmission has race-car style controls on the
steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
	   The target customer is a 35-year-old married male who earns about $100,000
per year.
</P>
<P>
	   "The IS 300 buyer probably has never considered buying a Lexus in the past,"
said Bryan Bergsteinsson, Lexus Group vice president and general manager. "...
We're ready to expand the Lexus family and we think this is just the vehicle to
do it."
</P>
<P>
	   In another Friday debut, Lincoln Mercury unveiled its new factory-stretched
version of the luxury Town Car sedan, the Cartier L. The body is extended six
inches at the factory, providing an additional 7.5 cubic feet of space in the
back seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
