<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teamsters hearings end without resolution of ouster of Philadelphia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   COLLINGSWOOD, N.J. (AP) - The third day of hearings on the ouster of
embattled Philadelphia Teamsters Local 115 leader John Morris ended Friday with
no decision on whether he should keep control of the local.
<P>
	   Morris, surrounded by an entourage of supporters, emerged from the
closed-door proceedings at the Local 676 union hall here. Morris said he had not
been given a fair opportunity to present his side at the hearings.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm fighting this thing to the end," Morris told reporters. "I'm going to
go on to what I have to do."
</P>
<P>
	   Teamsters president James P. Hoffa signed an emergency order in November
removing Morris as secretary-treasurer of Local 115 for charges including
alleged weapons purchases with union money and intimidation of members he
considered disloyal.
</P>
<P>
	   A panel of Teamsters officials heard testimony from only two witnesses since
the hearing began Wednesday, said union trustee Edward F. Keyser Jr., who is
presenting the case for Morris' removal. Morris is entitled to cross-examine
witnesses.
</P>
<P>
	   Keyser blamed Morris for delaying the hearing. He plans to call at least
nine more witnesses and a team of auditors when the hearing resumes. A date has
not been set.
</P>
<P>
	   "He just gets in their babbling. We don't know what he's talking about,"
said Keyser. "He's done nothing but stall these three days."
</P>
<P>
	   Morris, 73, has said the attempt to remove him as head of the 2,700-member
local is a political payback because he backed Hoffa's rival, Ron Carey, for the
union presidency. He won a federal court ruling last week that no emergency
existed to justify removing him without a hearing.
</P>
<P>
	   Amid tight security with dozens of police officers in riot gear and
sharpshooters on the rooftop, the union meeting broke up quietly without
incident Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're trying to make us look bad," said Donald Casey, a Morris supporter.
"We're not bad. We're just trying to stick up for our rights."
</P>
<P>
	   The meetings have been held in Collingswood because the union wanted a
neutral site that was large enough to accommodate the hundreds expected.
</P>
<P>
	   Collingswood Police Chief Thomas Garrity said his department called in a
full contingency of nearly 100 officers as a precaution. The proceedings
Thursday became tense and Morris was twice reprimanded for shouting.
</P>
<P>
	   "It's emotional testimony. It's causing tempers to flare," Garrity said.
</P>
<P>
	   Teamsters international union officials have said that the accusations
against Morris included using Teamster funds to buy and stockpile weapons
including shot guns and stun guns as well as combat fatigues and other clothing.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm not saying he stole them. He has mismanaged funds," Keyser said.
</P>
<P>
	   Morris has said the combat gear was for warmth on cold picket lines, and
stun guns might be needed to defend against antiunion violence. He denied any
other wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   "Why don't you ask me the right question?" Morris told reporters. "Was I
ever arrested? Was I ever put in jail? I'm not that way."
</P>
<P>
	   Morris will have a chance to call rebuttal witnesses after Keyser completes
his case.
</P>
<P>
	   One teamster who declined to give her name said she opposes Morris'
reinstatement and favors a trusteeship for the local. Morris founded the local
in 1955.
</P>
<P>
	   "I don't like him - never did," said the woman, a member of Local 115 for
more than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
	   When the testimony is complete, the panel of Teamsters officials - Charles
Byrnes, secretary treasurer of Local 926 in Pittsburgh; Denis Taylor, president
of Local 355 in Baltimore; and Ron McClain, president of Local 147 in Des
Moines, Iowa - will send a letter to Hoffa within 60 days recommending whether a
trusteeship should be imposed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
