<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuban Boy's Relatives File Petition  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Lawyers for the relatives of 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez filed a
petition Friday to appoint a guardian for the child, a first step toward
preventing the Cuban boy's return to his homeland.
</P>
<P>
	   Neither the attorneys nor the family would comment on the petition until
Judge Rosa Rodriguez made a decision in the case, said family spokesman Armando
Gutierrez.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian was found Thanksgiving Day clinging to an inner tube at sea after his
mother, stepfather and eight other people drowned while trying to reach Florida
by boat.
</P>
<P>
	   The boy was placed with his great-uncle and great-aunt in Miami, but the
Immigration and Naturalization Service ruled Wednesday that he must be returned
to his father in Cuba by next Friday. The decision touched off angry protests in
the Cuban-American community.
</P>
<P>
	   Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas and Miami Mayor Joe Carollo, accompanied by
one of the family's lawyers, flew to Washington on Friday to appeal directly to
Attorney General Janet Reno. Gov. Jeb Bush also asked President Clinton to
reverse the order.
</P>
<P>
	   Reno has said she was consulted on the INS decision and approved of it.
Clinton said Friday the INS did the right thing.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe they followed the law,'' Clinton said. ``This is a volatile and
difficult case. ... We need to keep this out of the political process as much as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
	   In contrast to Thursday, when two Cuban exile leaders and 133 other people
were arrested and police were forced to use tear gas to disperse a crowd,
protesters in Miami were much calmer Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   However, the Cuban exile community called for more civil disobedience. The
planned demonstrations included a vigil Friday night at the federal building in
Orlando and a large protest in Little Havana on Saturday. Protesters are also
planning to drive around Miami International Airport on Monday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``If the child is sent back to Cuba without his day in court, all hell is
going to break loose,'' said Jose Basulto, founder of Brothers to the Rescue, an
anti-Castro group.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush spoke with some demonstration organizers and asked them to ``do the
demonstrations in a way that does not disrupt daily life in South Florida,
because it would hurt the cause of Elian.''
</P>
<P>
	   The petition was filed Friday on behalf of Elian Gonzalez's great-uncle,
Lazaro Gonzalez. It is an attempt by the boy's Miami relatives to get
guardianship and then to file for applications for admission to the United
States and asylum, said David Abraham, an immigration law professor at the
University of Miami.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian played in his relatives' yard Friday with a puppy named Dolphin, a
gift from Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart, R-Fla. The black Labrador chased Elian
around the yard and playfully nipped at his blue soccer shorts.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Elian tells me he does not want to go back to Cuba,'' said Delfin
Gonzalez, the boy's great-uncle. He said Elian wants his family to come here.
</P>
<P>
	   Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, has not been available for comment
since the INS ruling.
</P>
<P>
	   U.S. officials have suggested Elian's father come to Florida to get his son,
while the U.S. National Council of Churches said the boy's relatives in Cuba
want the organization to bring the boy back.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1821 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Claims Mideast Talks Progress  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHEPHERDSTOWN, W.Va. (AP) -- In a move portrayed as evidence of progress,
President Clinton presented Israel and Syria a ``working document'' Friday that
could be a pathway to a land-for-peace treaty between the two old foes.
</P>
<P>
	   In another measured step forward, Clinton met with Prime Minister Ehud Barak
of Israel and Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa, first together, then
separately. It was the first face-to-face meeting between Barak and al-Sharaa
since Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We are moving down the track,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin
said before formal talks drew to a close for the Jewish Sabbath and the Muslim
Eid al-Fitr, the end of the holy month of Ramadan.
</P>
<P>
	   After returning to the White House, Clinton made a series of phone calls to
other world leaders to ``update them on the status of the peace talks in
Shepherdstown and give them a status report, from his perspective, on what
transpired today,'' said national security spokesman David Leavy.
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton spoke with French President Jacques Chirac for about 10 minutes,
Leavy said. He then spoke with German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder for 20
minutes and with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations were to resume Saturday night. He said Barak and al-Sharaa may
go home early next week, leaving experts behind to continue deliberations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is difficult stuff. This is very hard stuff,'' Clinton said on his
fourth day of mediating between Barak and al-Sharaa on details of a settlement
based on the proposition Israel should give up the Golan Heights to gain Syria's
diplomatic recognition.
</P>
<P>
	   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the president gave the U.S.-drafted
document, about seven pages long, to the two sides during the 45-minute
trilateral meeting.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This working document provides a summary of the issues to be decided and
the differences between the parties,'' Lockhart said. ``It is designed as a
procedural tool to focus the substantive discussions and to help bridge the
differences that now exist.''
</P>
<P>
	   Negotiations at this college town 70 miles from Washington had stalled over
procedural issues.
</P>
<P>
	   Israel insisted committees on peace terms and border security meet first,
and they did. But Rubin said committees on the timetable of an Israeli
withdrawal on the Golan Heights and on water resources would meet before the
round ends.
</P>
<P>
	   The document, which Secretary of State Madeleine Albright had directed her
aides to prepare, details both the agreements and disagreements during
negotiations here, in Washington last month and before a breakdown four years
ago.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's certainly progress to have a document before the parties,'' Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
	   But he added, ``We have limited expectations (of) what can be completed with
one round.''
</P>
<P>
	   A source close to the Syrian delegation told The Associated Press that the
Syrian negotiating team was satisfied with the document ``because matters now
have become more well-defined, and we won't be going back to square one every
time we meet.''
</P>
<P>
	   There was no immediate reaction from the Israelis, but Rubin said, ``They
both regard this as a good way to move the process forward.''
</P>
<P>
	   Clinton said he is satisfied everyone is making a good-faith effort. ``They
are working hard and trying to find ways to resolve their differences,'' he
said,
</P>
<P>
	   Before boarding a U.S. Marine helicopter that took him back to the White
House, the president spent a few minutes window shopping on German Street, the
main thoroughfare in 239-year-old Shepherdstown.
</P>
<P>
	   Some 200 spectators lined the street to see him.
</P>
<P>
	   Albright stayed behind and planned to join the Israeli delegation for
traditional Shabat dinner Friday night at the Clarion Hotel, which is off-limits
to journalists. On Saturday, she will join the Syrians for their feast to mark
the end of Ramadan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
