<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Beach nightclub mogul to be released on $15 million bond  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEW YORK (AP) - A South Beach nightclub impresario accustomed to
partying with Madonna now has the trappings of a mob murder defendant: house
arrest, 24-hour surveillance and a bigger bond package than John "Junior" Gotti.
<P>
	   The defendant, Chris Paciello, won his freedom Friday by agreeing to the $15
million bond package - secured by property pledged by family and South Beach
scene-makers - during a hearing Friday in Brooklyn federal court.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors said Paciello would not be released from a Brooklyn jail for at
least another week. After that, he will be confined to his mother's home on
Staten Island, where an electronic anklet, wiretaps and video cameras will
monitor his every move.
</P>
<P>
	   "There are more conditions on this bond than I have ever seen," U.S.
Magistrate Joan Azrack commented before signing off on the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   Paciello, 28, is charged with felony murder in a racketeering indictment
along with Anthony Spero, identified as the former acting boss of the Bonanno
crime family, and seven family soldiers and associates. The indictment alleges
that as a member of the violent "Bath Avenue crew," he participated in a botched
push-in robbery that left a housewife dead in 1993 and in a $300,000 bank
robbery in 1992, both on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
	   Authorities also have accused Paciello of exporting mob money and strong-arm
tactics to South Beach, where he reinvented himself as the owner of trendy
nightspots like Liquid, Bar Room and Joia. He has been linked romantically to
comic Sandra Bernhard, supermodel Niki Taylor and Madonna, a close friend of his
business partner, Ingrid Casares.
</P>
<P>
	   Paciello, whose real name is Christian Ludwigsen, surrendered in Miami on
Dec. 1. He has denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
	   Casares and Latin television personality Sofia Vergara - the sultry
ex-girlfriend of Paciello who arrived at the Brooklyn courthouse in a white
stretch limousine - were among the supporters who signed papers backing his
bond. The stocky, dark-haired defendant, dressed in blue prison garb, smiled and
blew a kiss at Casares as he left the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
	   "Unfortunately, the way our society works is when someone becomes successful
or a high-profile person, they become a target," Paciello's attorney, Roy Black,
told reporters. "Rather than celebrating people for their success, they want to
bring them down."
</P>
<P>
	   But prosecutors allege Paciello led a double life. Last month, Assistant
U.S. Attorney James Walden filed transcripts of a tape - secretly recorded by an
undercover agent posing as a corrupt cop - in which he allegedly talked about
killing a business rival.
</P>
<P>
	   "I'm telling you the owner of the club, we got to get his head (expletive)
broken in," Paciello said on a tape recorded Sept. 29. "We got to get him beat
up. I got to get him whacked."
</P>
<P>
	   Under the conditions of his release, Paciello will be barred from using cell
phones and pagers. Authorities will screen all visitors. He will be allowed to
return to Miami on April 1. But even there, he will remain under house arrest
until returning to Brooklyn for trial on Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
	   Gotti, son of the notorious boss of the Gambino crime family, was released
on a $10 million bond package last year before pleading guilty to bribery,
extortion and other charges. He was sentenced to 6 1/2 years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
