<DOCNO> APW20000107.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bonds Rise Slightly After Retreat  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    NEW YORK (AP) -- Government bond prices rose slightly Friday, shaking off an
early setback as traders assessed the inflation risks of a fresh government
report of a tight labor market.
</P>
<P>
	   The Labor Department report of rising wages and a bigger-than-expected
increase in the number of jobs created kept traders betting the Federal
Reserve's inflation-fighters soon will begin raising interest rates again. But
analysts said the employment figures were not viewed as so strong that they
would encourage the Fed to be overly aggressive in efforts to cool off the
economy.
</P>
<P>
	   The price of the 30-year bond rose 3/32 point, or 93 3/4 cents per $1,000 in
face value. Its yield, which moves in the opposite direction, fell to 6.54
percent from 6.55 percent late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   The Labor Department said the economy added 315,000 jobs in December, above
expectations for an increase of 250,000. The average hourly earnings increased
0.4 percent in December, slightly above estimates. The unemployment rate
remained at a 29-year low of 4.1 percent in December, in line with economists'
expectations.
</P>
<P>
	   Bonds sold off sharply when the figures were released Friday morning, with
the 30-year Treasury losing over 1 point before recovering.
</P>
<P>
	   Bond prices have fallen in recent weeks amid concerns that the Federal
Reserve, which raised rates three times last year, plans to increase interest
rates again early this year now that fears of a Year 2000 computer disaster have
dissipated.
</P>
<P>
	   Rising interest rates hurt bonds, which pay a fixed rate of return.
</P>
<P>
	   In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities were
unchanged to up 1/32 point and intermediate maturities rose 1/32 to  1/8 point,
reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information service.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.38 percent as the discount fell
0.01 percentage point from Thursday to 5.23 percent. Six-month yields were 5.65
percent, as the discount fell 0.01 percentage point from Thursday to 5.42
percent. One-year yields were 5.99 percent as the discount fell 0.01 percentage
point from Thursday to 5.65 percent.
</P>
<P>
	   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the discount is the
interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
	   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between banks, was
5.68 3/4 percent, up from 5.50 percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
	   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer said the new contract for its index
of 40 actively traded municipal bonds rose  1/8 to 91 27/32. The average yield
to maturity fell to 6.26 percent from 6.27 percent on Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1839 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0251 </DOCNO>
