<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EchoStar Offers Free Satellite Dish  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    DENVER (AP) -- EchoStar Communications Corp. is dangling nearly $400 in
goods and services in front of cable television customers to get them to switch
to satellite service.
</P>
<P>
	   The Littleton-based operator of the Dish Network satellite service hopes to
lure some of the country's 67 million cable subscribers with the offer of a free
satellite dish and installation, EchoStar spokesman Marc Lumpkin said Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   "They're ripe fruit," Lumpkin said. "They hate their cable companies because
they have poor service, they raise their rates every year, they take off
channels or leave off channels."
</P>
<P>
	   He added: "We have the most channel choices for the lowest prices."
</P>
<P>
	   The promotion steps up the competition between cable and satellite providers
for control of viewers' sets. Last year Time Warner Cable announced an offer of
$100 to anyone who traded a satellite-TV dish for digital cable service.
</P>
<P>
	   EchoStar announced its nationwide deal Thursday at the Consumer Electronics
Show in Las Vegas. To get the free dish and installation, customers will have to
present a valid credit card and cable bill when purchasing equipment and commit
to a year of service at $39.98 a month. The offer expires March 31.
</P>
<P>
	   Non-cable customers would get reimbursed later for purchasing a dish.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
