<TEXT>
<P>
    NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- A Mercedes-Benz employee was denied a promotion because
he was 72 years old, the federal government alleged in an age discrimination
lawsuit against the car maker.
</P>
<P>
	   The lawsuit, filed Monday in federal court against Montvale-based
Mercedes-Benz of North America, seeks back wages and other damages for
Archangelo Passarello of Park Ridge.
</P>
<P>
	   Passarello, who still works as a secretary in the company's legal
department, applied in 1996 for the post of national customer assistance
representative after 11 years in the company and satisfactory evaluations, the
lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mercedes-Benz promoted two other applicants who were "substantially younger
and substantially less qualified," the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
	   Mercedes-Benz spokeswoman Donna Boland said the lawsuit had no merit. "We
have a long-standing policy of not discriminating on any basis," she said.
</P>
