<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Founder of Walter Industries Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- James W. Walter, founder of a company that grew into a
leading home builder and industrial company, has died. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
	   Walter, founder and chairman of Walter Industries Inc., died at home
Thursday of complications from lung cancer. He was diagnosed with the disease
last June and underwent extensive radiation and chemotherapy treatment.
</P>
<P>
	   "Our corporate family is mourning the loss of an inspiring leader and loyal
friend," said Kenneth Hyatt, chairman and CEO of Walter Industries. "Jim
Walter's character and personality are stamped indelibly on this company. His
extraordinary sense of fair play and basic integrity will forever serve as our
guiding standards."
</P>
<P>
	   Walter pioneered a new concept in affordable family homes when, at age 23,
he sold his first shell home for $895 in 1946. The home was finished and painted
on the outside but had only stud framing inside.
</P>
<P>
	   The Tampa-based business he formed out of that venture, Jim Walter Homes,
sold and financed more than 330,000 single-family houses in 24 states.
</P>
<P>
	   His company, later under the names Jim Walter Corp. and Walter Industries,
diversified into coal mining, paper distribution and aluminum products, becoming
one of Florida's largest companies and one of the 200 largest industrial
companies in the nation.
</P>
<P>
	   At its peak, the company had more than $2.4 billion in sales and 25,000
employees.
</P>
<P>
	   The conglomerate went through a five-year bankruptcy case in the early 1990s
as waves of lawsuits were filed alleging asbestos poisoning by a former
subsidiary, Celotex Corp. Walter and his management team emerged in control of
the company.
</P>
<P>
	   Walter was born in Lewes, Del., and moved to Florida as a baby and grew up
in Tampa. He never attended college but had a chair named for him at the
University of Florida's College of Business Administration.
</P>
<P>
	   Funeral services were set Tuesday at Sacred Heart Church in Tampa. Walter
was survived by his wife, Connie, two sons, a stepdaughter, grandson and three
step-grandsons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1903 </TRAILER>
