<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. OKs Death Penalty Overhaul  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) -- Florida lawmakers on Friday passed the second half
of a plan to overhaul the way the death penalty is administered, sending the
governor a bill to speed up executions.
</P>
<P>
	   Lawmakers said it will shorten the appeals process and cut the time between
death sentences and executions from an average of more than 10 years to five.
</P>
<P>
	   Executions in Florida have been on hold since October, when the U.S. Supreme
Court agreed to review claims that Florida's electric chair -- which has caused
fiery and bloody executions in the past decade -- is cruel and unusual
punishment.
</P>
<P>
	   Hoping to resume executions, lawmakers called a three-day special session
just to deal with the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   On Thursday, they passed a bill making lethal injection the state's primary
method of execution, although death row inmates would still have the option of
electrocution. Florida has used the electric chair since the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
	   Republican Gov. Jeb Bush said he would not approve that measure without
legislation speeding up the appeals process.
</P>
<P>
	   One killer has been on Florida's death row for 25 years, and dozens of
condemned men have lived under death sentences for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush said he would sign both bills within days.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We've had a year where the courts have made it clear they needed to see
some changes,'' the governor said. ``I believe today will clear the air.''
</P>
<P>
	   The appeals bill limits death row inmates to two appeals in state court in
most cases. The second appeal must be filed within six months of the first
appeal -- rather than the current one year -- and it can also be filed in the
state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
	   One of the exceptions is for prisoners who have new claims they are
innocent, rather than technical complaints. They may bring up those innocence
claims in additional appeals.
</P>
<P>
	   Supporters said the bill would stop frivolous cases and bring legitimate
claims to the attention of judges more quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   Democrats who opposed the bill warned that it would lead to the execution of
innocent people. They also said the bill usurps the authority of the judicial
branch.
</P>
<P>
	   The Senate voted 30-7 for the appeals bill, and the House passed it 80-35 --
just meeting the two-thirds vote needed to repeal court rules that dictate how
and when death penalty appeals are filed.
</P>
<P>
	   Some opponents complained that the Legislature was acting too quickly.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We really spent more time talking about a license plate last session than
we have about executing people,'' said Democratic Rep. Curt Levine.
</P>
<P>
	   If the governor signs the bills as expected, only three of the 38 states
with capital punishment will still require execution by electrocution --
Georgia, Alabama and Nebraska.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1917 </TRAILER>
