<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Church Supports Ecuador President  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's Roman Catholic Church on Friday said it was
not taking sides in the growing street demonstrations for President Jamil
Mahuad's resignation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We do not intervene in party politics,'' Monsignor Jose Eguiguren told
reporters. But in an indirect show of support for the embattled president, he
said, ``We maintain the principle that democracy is and always will be the best
road, no matter how imperfect.''
</P>
<P>
	   Eguiguren said he was responding to an invitation from the leftist-led
Popular Front to hear its proposal to replace Mahuad's centrist government with
one made up of workers and grassroots organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   The Popular Front was one of several leftist-led organizations to lead
demonstrations on Thursday in Ecuador's main cities. Police used tear gas to
disperse about 1,000 demonstrators who tried to march on the presidential
palace, and the government called a state of emergency, giving the armed forces
authority to maintain order and detain protesters.
</P>
<P>
	   The Red Cross said at least two people were injured in confrontations with
police, including a 17-year-old male student who suffered a bullet wound in the
neck. It was unclear who fired the shot, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the last six months, Mahuad has faced increasing calls to step down from
political rivals on both the left and right, as well as business leaders and
labor unions, who accuse him of incompetence in handling Ecuador's economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecuador is struggling through its worst financial crisis since the 1920s.
Last year, the economy shrank 7 percent and inflation topped 60 percent, and
Ecuador's currency has plunged to 23,000 sucres to the dollar from 7,000 sucres
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahuad has said he plans to finish his term, which runs until January 2003,
and the politically powerful armed forces have expressed their support for him.
</P>
<P>
	   But a poll released Thursday showed that 53 percent of Ecuadoreans would
like Mahuad to step down, and only 7 percent of those surveyed expressed support
for the Harvard-educated president.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll, conducted by the private firm Cedatos, surveyed 1,800 people and
had a margin for error of plus or minus 3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
