<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big political donor accused of shredding documents to thwart probe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A big political donor who was arrested last month
was indicted Friday, accused of working with an aide to shred 10 bags of
documents and delete computer files to obstruct an investigation by the Justice
Department of campaign finances.
<P>
	   David Chang, whose commodity trading companies are based in Bergen County,
also is charged with misleading a witness before he testified to the federal
grand jury, and instructing another witness to lie so that her testimony would
corroborate testimony already given by the aide.
</P>
<P>
	   Part of the grand jury probe dealt with an $11,000 check from one of those
companies, Bright &AMP; Bright Corp. A Bergen County lawyer who pleaded guilty to
campaign finance charges in May said he helped Chang illegally funnel that money
to Sen. Robert Torricelli's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The Democrat has not been charged. He has maintained he was unaware when
unlawful donations were made and that such money has now been donated to
charity.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang's aide, Audrey Yu, was indicted last month on charges that she lied to
a grand jury. This 11-count superseding indictment adds Chang as a defendant,
charging him in four counts: conspiracy, obstructing justice, and two counts of
witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
	   It added those four charges against Yu, as well as two charges of lying to a
grand jury. She already faced five counts of lying to a grand jury about
shredding.
</P>
<P>
	   The indictment does not name the witnesses, but said the man misled in
September by Chang and Yu was Bright &AMP; Bright's chairman. At the time, the
chairman was a retired admiral, Daniel J. Murphy, who was chief of staff for
George Bush when he was vice president, and a deputy director of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
	   Torricelli spokesman Richard McGrath said Friday, "We are saddened that Mr.
Chang and Ms. Yu continue to experience these legal difficulties. They have been
friends and supporters for many years. Because these charges involve private
business transactions, and have absolutely nothing to do with campaign
activities, it would be inappropriate for us to comment further."
</P>
<P>
	   Messages left for Yu's lawyers were not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang attorney David Schertler said his client is innocent, asserting that
the Justice Department has taken a "low-level felony allegation" about campaign
finance "and they've blown it out of proportion and attempted to create crimes
where there aren't any because of the highly charged atmosphere around campaign
finance contributions."
</P>
<P>
	   He questioned why the indictment did not charge Chang with making illegal
donations, as Berek Paul Don claimed when he pleaded guilty in May and agreed to
cooperate with investigators.
</P>
<P>
	   Don had been the Republican leader in Bergen County, which Torricelli
represented in the House before becoming a senator. Don pleaded guilty to
illegally donating $11,000 from a Bright &AMP; Bright check labeled "legal fees" by
cashing it and using the money to reimburse straw donors because Chang asked him
to get it into Torricelli's campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time, Bright &AMP; Bright was a client of Don's law firm.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal election law limits individual contributions to $1,000 per election
to a single candidate for federal office, and prohibits corporate donations to
candidates for federal office.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin could not immediately comment on
why no campaign finance charges were brought against Chang in light of the Don
plea.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang, 55, Cresskill, and Yu, 31, of Fort Lee, are free on bail, and are to
enter pleas to the indictment on a date to be scheduled in the next two weeks.
Yu's lawyer has said she no longer works for Chang.
</P>
<P>
	   The Chang indictment followed nearly three years of investigation,
culminating with government agents spending at least four months examining
Bright &AMP; Bright's garbage, according to court papers filed by the FBI. The
indictment expands on FBI charges of shredding brought last month with his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang was listed by Mother Jones, a left-leaning political magazine, as one
of the top 400 donors during the 1997-98 election cycle with contributions of
$41,586 to candidates and organizations of both parties.
</P>
<P>
	   Some donations he made in 1999 were returned after the Don plea.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang was linked several years ago to the problems that toppled former Rep.
Jay Kim, R-Calif. Court records show that Kim's campaign had taken more than
$250,000 in illegal contributions, including $12,000 in 1992 from Nikko
Enterprises Inc., a Chang company. Kim was sentenced to probation. Chang
cooperated with federal authorities and was not charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
