<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Co. To Recall Electric Heaters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- A Washington state company whose electric heaters have
been blamed for house fires and three deaths plans to recall 1.9 million heaters
next month and sell customers replacement units at reduced cost.
</P>
<P>
	   Cadet Manufacturing said Friday that the $12 million recall would begin as
soon as a federal bankruptcy judge and the Consumer Product Safety Commission
approve it, probably by the first week of February.
</P>
<P>
	   Cadet, a privately held company in Vancouver, Wash., filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection last January, citing financial pressure from a 1997 recall
and a class-action lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
	   The Consumer Product Safety Commission had sought the recall of Cadet- or
Encore-brand heaters, saying they had resulted in three deaths, four house
fires, two serious burn injuries and more than $1.2 million in property damage.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The first thing we want to do is apologize,'' Cadet's president, Hutch
Johnson, said Friday at a news conference in Portland, just across the Columbia
River from Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
	   The heaters are designed to be installed inside walls or baseboards. The
safety commission said that design flaws allowed flames, sparks or molten
particles to spew through the front grill cover of the heaters.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson said the commission and the company worked together to redesign the
heaters and make them ``the safest product available.''
</P>
<P>
	   The heaters were distributed mainly in six Western states -- California,
Idaho, Montana, Oregon, Washington and Wyoming -- but they also were sold
nationally.
</P>
<P>
	   Customers will have to seek the replacement heaters directly from Cadet, not
through retailers, and will have to install the units themselves -- or hire a
licensed electrician.
</P>
<P>
	   Johnson said the replacements will be sold nearly at cost, and many of the
heaters to be recalled are more than 12 years old, well beyond the eight- to
12-year service life of the units, so the upgrade will improve overall safety.
</P>
<P>
	   Cadet was founded 40 years ago. Sales were about $23 million in 1998, but
fell to $16 million last year with the bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
	   ------
</P>
<P>
	   Eds: The toll-free hotline for the recall is 1-800-567-2613, and its
Internet site is www.cadetco.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 1940 </TRAILER>
