<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> L.A. Times Promotes Veterans  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Times promoted newsroom veteran Leo
Wolinsky to executive editor Friday and created a new position to oversee the
relationship between the editorial and business departments.
</P>
<P>
	   Ardith Hilliard, editor of the San Fernando Valley edition, was named
associate editor. She's charged with implementing ethical guidelines adopted by
the paper in response to a much-criticized revenue-sharing deal with the city's
new Staples Center arena.
</P>
<P>
	   "The Staples Center incident and the subsequent analysis helped clarify the
need for these positions," Editor Michael Parks wrote in a staff memo. "Leo and
Ardie are great newsroom leaders with vision and drive."
</P>
<P>
	   Wolinsky and Hilliard will report to Parks.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolinsky, a member of two Pulitzer Prize-winning teams and one of four
managing editors at the Times, will oversee metro, business, photos and Los
Angeles Times-Washington Post News Service staffs. Times managing editors for
regional editions, projects and features will report to Wolinsky.
</P>
<P>
	   Many journalists criticized the deal involving the Oct. 10 edition of Los
Angeles Times Magazine as a violation of the journalistic principle that
reporters and editors must avoid financial dealing with the people and
institutions they write about.
</P>
<P>
	   The paper has said reporters and editors who worked on the magazine didn't
know of the revenue deal.
</P>
<P>
	   The paper printed a front-page apology to readers Dec. 19 for failing to
disclose the arrangement, and the next day ran an unprecedented 14-page section
examining the deal.
</P>
<P>
	   That report criticized Parks, Publisher Kathryn M. Downing and the policies
of Mark Willes, a former General Mills executive who was Downing's predecessor
and now is chairman and CEO of the newspaper's parent Times Mirror Co.
</P>
<P>
	   Willes has ordered closer cooperation between the paper's advertising and
news staffs.
</P>
<P>
	   With the apology, the Times published a newly formulated statement of
journalistic principles that included remaining "free of associations or
activities that might compromise our integrity or damage our credibility."
</P>
<P>
	   In announcing the promotions at a newsroom meeting, Parks began by saying he
would not resign. Staffers cheered when he announced the promotion of Wolinsky,
who led the effort to draw up the paper's new principles and guidelines.
</P>
<P>
	   Wolinsky joined the Times in 1977 as a staff writer. He was named assistant
bureau chief in Sacramento in 1987, assistant city editor in 1989, California
political editor in 1990, city editor in 1991, metropolitan editor in 1994 and
assistant managing editor in 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   Hilliard has been a part of three Pulitzer Prize-winning teams. She joined
the Times in 1989 after working at papers including The Press of Atlantic City,
N.J., St. Petersburg (Fla.) Times, Dallas Times Herald and San Jose Mercury
News. She became editor of the Times' San Fernando Valley edition in 1997. A
replacement wasn't named for that edition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
