<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Debate Again  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
said Friday night that South Carolinians should decide for themselves whether
the Confederate flag should fly atop their statehouse, finessing a
racially-tinged question in campaign debate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe the people of South Carolina can figure out what to do with this
flag issue,'' Bush said in the opening moments of the second Republican debate
in as many nights. The question itself drew a chorus of boos from South
Carolinians gathered to watch the six-man Republican field address the issues.
And when moderator Brian Williams pursued the issue, the booing grew louder.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain, who has campaigned hard in the state, defended anew the
letters he has written to federal agencies on behalf of campaign donors.
``Whenever a constituent of mine or a citizen ... can't get an answer ... I
believe that people like me should weigh in,'' said McCain, who wrote the
letters in his capacity as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator was addressing a question about an Associated Press story
detailing a letter he wrote last year on behalf of Ameritech, which was seeking
permission to merge with SBC, another phone company.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter-writing issue is a troubling one for McCain, whose candidacy has
flourished on the basis of his call for a ridding the nation's political system
of the influence of big-monied special interests.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wal-Mart Settles Bias Case  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
    TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) -- Wal-Mart will provide two deaf job applicants
employment and $132,500 to settle a discrimination case.
</P>
<P>
	   Jeremy Fass and William Darnell filed complaints with the Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission after they were both turned down for night jobs at a
Tucson Wal-Mart. Both men said they were refused jobs in the stocking and
unloading area because they are deaf.
</P>
<P>
	   "We realize that in this instance, we did something wrong at the local
level," said Mike Maher, a spokesman for the Bentonville, Ark.-based Wal-Mart.
</P>
<P>
	   The EEOC and the Arizona Center for Disability Law filed suit in federal
court in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
	   The settlement calls for them to be offered jobs with corporate service
dates of Sept. 1, 1995. In addition to the $66,250 each they will receive, Fass
and Darnell will be paid their share of profit-sharing and be reimbursed for
out-of-pocket expenses that would have been covered by Wal-Mart's health plan
had they been hired.
</P>
<P>
	   Wal-Mart will make a number of policy changes, including adding
closed-captioning on training videos and making other changes to reasonably
accommodate deaf employees.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2024 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0280 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Steals Plane, Dies in Crash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARYSVILLE, Wash. (AP) -- A man who stole a small plane with half a tank of
gas Friday was killed when it clipped power lines above Interstate 5, flipped
upside down and slid under an overpass.
</P>
<P>
	   No cars were hit on the freeway, and the pilot, the only person aboard, was
the sole casualty, said fire Lt. Jeff Thornton in Marysville, about 30 miles
north of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
	   The State Patrol identified the man as Randy Lee Yttri, 45.
</P>
<P>
	   The plane's owner said there was nothing of value aboard, and it was not
clear why Yttri stole the craft. A warrant had been issued for his arrest last
month for delivery of dangerous drugs, said Lt. Walt Fisch of the Washington
State Patrol.
</P>
<P>
	   Fisch said Federal Aviation Administration investigators found only a small
amount of gas in the 1966 single-engine Cessna 150G's tank, and they suspected a
power loss downed the plane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2029 </TRAILER>
