<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Debate Again  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
said Friday night that South Carolinians should decide for themselves whether
the Confederate flag should fly atop their statehouse, finessing a
racially-tinged question in campaign debate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe the people of South Carolina can figure out what to do with this
flag issue,'' Bush said in the opening moments of the second Republican debate
in as many nights. The question itself drew a chorus of boos from South
Carolinians gathered to watch the six-man Republican field address the issues.
And when moderator Brian Williams pursued the issue, the booing grew louder.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. John McCain, who has campaigned hard in the state, defended anew the
letters he has written to federal agencies on behalf of campaign donors.
``Whenever a constituent of mine or a citizen ... can't get an answer ... I
believe that people like me should weigh in,'' said McCain, who wrote the
letters in his capacity as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator was addressing a question about an Associated Press story
detailing a letter he wrote last year on behalf of Ameritech, which was seeking
permission to merge with SBC, another phone company.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter-writing issue is a troubling one for McCain, whose candidacy has
flourished on the basis of his call for a ridding the nation's political system
of the influence of big-monied special interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush, McCain and the other contenders, Steven Forbes, Alan Keyes, Gary Bauer
and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah, were meeting in South Carolina before that state
holds a primary on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
	   As he has numerous times in the campaign, Bauer stressed his unalterable
opposition to abortion, saying that even if a relative were raped, ``I would
explain she couldn't make right the terrible thing that happened to her by
taking the life of an unborn child.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes was passionate on the same subject. Asked whether he would rather face
another Democratic administration or live with a pro-choice Republican in the
White House, he said, ``I don't think that has to be out choice. ... This party
was born in principle. This party will die if it doesn't stand by its decision
of principle.''
</P>
<P>
	   The debate produced a flourish or two -- the contenders fielded questions
submitted by the internet, for example. And for the first time in their
campaign, they were asked about their own charitable giving.
</P>
<P>
	   Hatch said he and his wife give away about 11 percent of their income.
</P>
<P>
	   The hour-long debate came 24 hours after the GOP contenders met on stage in
New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
	   Thursday night, in a sometimes-raucous debate at the University of New
Hampshire, McCain defended his action as chairman of the Senate Commerce
Committee in prodding the Federal Communications Commission to act on a license
request from one of his campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
	   The Arizona senator has made campaign finance reform a cornerstone of his
presidential campaign, saying that money is corrupting the political process.
</P>
<P>
	   ``Most objective observers believe the FCC hasn't done their job,'' he told
a questioner. ``That's my obligation as a senator and as the chairman of a
powerful committee.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain has not only focused his campaign on New Hampshire, which holds the
nation's first primary election on Feb. 1, but also South Carolina, where voters
go to the polls on Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
	   A Nov. 27 survey by CNN/Time magazine showed Bush leading McCain 62 percent
to 15 percent in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and Forbes entered Friday's debate arguing over a new TV ad in which
the publisher contends Bush broke a 1994 tax pledge by supporting Texas
legislation that would have raised some business taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   Responding to the ad, Bush said he had cut taxes twice as Texas governor,
despite the legislation Forbes pointed out. Bush also trumpeted the five-year,
$483 billion tax-cut plan he has proposed as a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
	   ``The plan that I've laid out is the plan I'm campaigning on,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
	   Meeting with New Hampshire reporters before flying to South Carolina, the
governor said the ad was reminiscent of attack ads Forbes aired against Bob Dole
in the last presidential primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   He also said it was a sign that Forbes' ``political clock is ticking down.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``He's now reacting in the year 2000 like he did in '96,'' Bush said. ``He
must be beginning to feel that sense of gloom that affects a candidate who
cannot sell his message in a positive way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
