<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 'Hurricane' Fights Death Penalty  </HEADLINE>
   By PAUL NOWELL Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- While a movie about his 20-year battle to clear his
name plays in theaters, Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter would rather talk about the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   ``My life is dedicated to executing the death penalty,'' Carter said Friday
before making a speech at the sold-out Great Aunt Stella Center. ``It does not
belong in life.''
</P>
<P>
	   The ex-boxer, who never wavered in his claim that he was innocent of a
triple murder in a New Jersey bar in 1966, was wrongfully convicted and
sentenced to three life terms. He narrowly escaped the electric chair and spent
the next 19 years in prison until his case drew international attention from the
likes of songwriter Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
	   Dylan's 1975 song ``Hurricane'' made Carter a celebrity. Still, it would be
years before he was freed and his reputation was restored. Now, he is the
subject of ``The Hurricane,'' a new movie starring Denzel Washington.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I've had books written about me and movies made about me and songs written
about me,'' Carter said, his voice dropping to a near-whisper. ``If my life
isn't a miracle, there aren't any miracles anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
	   Carter, who lives in Canada, was in Charlotte to deliver the keynote speech
at a conference on criminal justice and the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   The conference comes as the number of executions is rising. The 98
executions in the U.S. last year represented a 30 percent increase over 1998 and
the highest total since 1951, when there were 105.
</P>
<P>
	   Carter has been joined by retired Archbishop Desmond Tutu, some members of
Congress and the American Bar Association in calling for a national moratorium
on executions.
</P>
<P>
	   He noted the irony in the conference's subtitle: ``Executions in a Civilized
Society.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``Any society that promotes the death penalty cannot be civilized, so it's
an oxymoron,'' he said. ``The United States is the only Western industrialized
nation in the world that refuses to do away with it. That makes the U.S.
uncivilized.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
