<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Pressed FCC on Phone Merger  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two weeks after Ameritech's chairman held a fund-raiser
for him, Sen. John McCain sent a stinging letter to federal regulators accusing
them of being unfair toward the phone giant's proposed merger with another Bell
company, memos show.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain's letter of last April 12 stated that the Senate Commerce Committee
chairman and some of his colleagues were ``extremely troubled'' by the Federal
Communications Commission's handling of the proposed merger between SBC
Communications and Ameritech.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter signed by the Arizona senator accused the commission of
``applying a different, and much stricter, burden of proof in this merger
proceeding than the commission has applied in evaluating other mergers.''
</P>
<P>
	   It also said, ``This letter expresses no view on the merits of any issues in
this proceeding and is not written to benefit any particular party.''
</P>
<P>
	   The letter followed on the heels of a $1,000-per-person fund-raiser hosted
March 30 at a Chicago hotel by Ameritech chief Richard Notebaert, a member of
McCain's fund-raising team.
</P>
<P>
	   At a debate Friday night, McCain was questioned about the Ameritech letter
and said ``all the times when I have weighed in, I have asked them to do their
duty and to expedite the procedures as they're laid out under the law and
according to existing regulations.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will continue to do that job, and when a constituent, a person of mine
who has trouble -- or a citizen of this country who can't get a reaction or an
answer from a bureaucracy that's paid for with their tax dollars -- I believe
that people like me should weigh in,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   The McCain letter, like one relating to a different FCC matter that surfaced
earlier in the week, came to light at a pivotal time for McCain in his bid for
the Republican presidential nomination. The Arizona senator has risen in the
polls while campaigning as an advocate of overhauling the campaign finance
system and ridding the nation's political system of what he calls the
``pernicious'' influence of money.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time, Ameritech, a Midwest phone giant, had been trying for months to
get FCC approval for its merger with SBC, which is based in the Southwest. The
deal, which eventually was approved, created the nation's largest local phone
company.
</P>
<P>
	   A flier for the fund-raiser hailed McCain as a ``leader in the most critical
issues facing the country'' and praised his efforts to deregulate the
telecommunications industry.
</P>
<P>
	   The letters and fund-raising fliers were obtained by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
	   Ameritech denied any connection between the fund-raiser and McCain's letter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This was totally Dick Notebaert's personal involvement as a member of the
host committee in Chicago,'' said spokesman Dave Pacholczyk. ``It was personal
for Mr. Notebaert.''
</P>
<P>
	   That campaign theme has struck a chord among independents, according to
public opinion polls, and has helped vault McCain into a highly competitive race
with Texas Gov. George W. Bush in New Hampshire, the nation's first primary
state.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain was hardly alone in his letter writing. The FCC said this week it had
received between 7,000 and 8,000 pieces of correspondence a year from lawmakers
in the past three years about issues pending before the agency. No figures were
available for other regulatory and administrative agencies of the government.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain acknowledges he often writes letters as a committee chairman to
regulatory agencies, and that some involve companies that donate to him.
</P>
<P>
	   He has suggested his campaign finance proposals, which would restrict
corporate donations to political parties, would help eliminate inevitable
appearance-of-conflict questions that arise under such circumstances.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Ameritech matter, FCC Chairman Bill Kennard sent letters to both
companies in the first part of April expressing ``serious concern'' about their
deal, which would create a company controlling one-third of the nation's phone
lines.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain responded April 12 in a letter to Kennard: ``Your improvisational
process will only kill more time and raise the chances of a legally flawed
decision.'' The letter also was signed by Sens. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., and Sam
Brownback, R-Kan.
</P>
<P>
	   A month later, McCain sent another letter to the FCC, criticizing agency
personnel for public statements about the merger and accusing the commission of
bias.
</P>
<P>
	   ``You must do whatever is necessary to remove the institutional unfairness
and prejudgment that has been permitted to taint this proceeding,'' McCain
wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   In September, Ameritech's Notebaert was host for a second fund-raiser for
McCain at a Chicago club.
</P>
<P>
	   Committee chairmen routinely are entertained at fund-raisers in their honor
or receive donations from executives of companies under their jurisdiction. And
lawmakers, particularly chairmen, write hundreds of letters a year on behalf of
companies and constituents involved in matters at federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
	   In this case, employees of Ameritech and their families and the company's
political action committee had contributed $16,000 to McCain's presidential
campaign through Sept. 30, his ninth most generous giver. SBC Communications
employees and their families and the company PAC had given a total of $9,750.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2052 </TRAILER>
