<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Big political donor accused of shredding documents to thwart probe  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
    	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A big political donor who was arrested last month
was indicted Friday, accused of working with an aide to shred 10 bags of
documents and delete computer files to obstruct an investigation by the Justice
Department of campaign finances.
<P>
	   David Chang, whose commodity trading companies are based in Bergen County,
also is charged with misleading a witness before he testified to the federal
grand jury, and instructing another witness to lie so that her testimony would
corroborate testimony already given by the aide.
</P>
<P>
	   Part of the grand jury probe dealt with an $11,000 check from one of those
companies, Bright &AMP; Bright Corp. A Bergen County lawyer who pleaded guilty to
campaign finance charges in May said he helped Chang illegally funnel that money
to Sen. Robert Torricelli's 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   The New Jersey Democrat has not been charged. He has maintained he was
unaware when unlawful donations were made and that such money has now been
donated to charity.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang's aide, Audrey Yu, was indicted last month on charges that she lied to
a grand jury. This 11-count superseding indictment adds Chang as a defendant,
charging him in four counts: conspiracy, obstructing justice, and two counts of
witness tampering.
</P>
<P>
	   It added those four charges against Yu, as well as two charges of lying to a
grand jury. She already faced five counts of lying to a grand jury about
shredding. Yu faces up to 70 years in prison if convicted on all counts, while
Chang's charges carry up to 35 years. The charges carry about $250,000 each in
fines.
</P>
<P>
	   The indictment does not name the witnesses, but said the man misled in
September by Chang and Yu was Bright &AMP; Bright's chairman. At the time, the
chairman was a retired admiral, Daniel J. Murphy, who was chief of staff for
George Bush when he was vice president, and a deputy director of the CIA.
</P>
<P>
	   Torricelli spokesman Richard McGrath said Friday, "We are saddened that Mr.
Chang and Ms. Yu continue to experience these legal difficulties. They have been
friends and supporters for many years. Because these charges involve private
business transactions, and have absolutely nothing to do with campaign
activities, it would be inappropriate for us to comment further."
</P>
<P>
	   Messages left for Yu's lawyers were not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang attorney David Schertler said his client is innocent, asserting that
the Justice Department has taken a "low-level felony allegation" about campaign
finance "and they've blown it out of proportion and attempted to create crimes
where there aren't any because of the highly charged atmosphere around campaign
finance contributions."
</P>
<P>
	   He questioned why the indictment did not charge Chang with making illegal
donations, as Berek Paul Don claimed when he pleaded guilty in May and agreed to
cooperate with investigators.
</P>
<P>
	   Don had been the Republican leader in Bergen County, which Torricelli
represented in the House before becoming a senator. Don pleaded guilty to
illegally donating $11,000 from a Bright &AMP; Bright check labeled "legal fees" by
cashing it and using the money to reimburse straw donors because Chang asked him
to get it into Torricelli's campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time, Bright &AMP; Bright was a client of Don's law firm.
</P>
<P>
	   Federal election law limits individual contributions to $1,000 per election
to a single candidate for federal office, and prohibits corporate donations to
candidates for federal office.
</P>
<P>
	   Justice Department spokesman Myron Marlin said he could not comment on why
no campaign finance charges were brought against Chang in light of the Don plea
because "the entire investigation is still under way."
</P>
<P>
	   Chang, 55, Cresskill, and Yu, 31, of Fort Lee, are free on bail, and are to
enter pleas to the indictment on a date to be scheduled in the next two weeks.
Yu's lawyer has said she no longer works for Chang.
</P>
<P>
	   The Chang indictment followed nearly three years of investigation,
culminating with government agents spending at least four months examining
Bright &AMP; Bright's garbage, according to court papers filed by the FBI. The
indictment expands on FBI charges of shredding brought last month with his
arrest.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang was listed by Mother Jones, a left-leaning political magazine, as one
of the top 400 donors during the 1997-98 election cycle with contributions of
$41,586 to candidates and organizations of both parties.
</P>
<P>
	   Some donations he made in 1999 were returned after the Don plea.
</P>
<P>
	   Chang was linked several years ago to the problems that toppled former Rep.
Jay Kim, R-Calif. Court records show that Kim's campaign had taken more than
$250,000 in illegal contributions, including $12,000 in 1992 from Nikko
Enterprises Inc., a Chang company. Kim was sentenced to probation. Chang
cooperated with federal authorities and was not charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-01-07-00 2058 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Tries to Soothe Powell  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore called Gen. Colin Powell Friday to
express his respect for the Gulf War hero after comments by his campaign manager
earlier in the week angered the Republican.
</P>
<P>
	   Campaign manager Donna Brazile said earlier this week that Republicans
``would rather take pictures with black children than feed them,'' saying they
use Powell and Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma, two of the most prominent blacks in
the GOP, to improve their image with minorities.
</P>
<P>
	   Powell wrote Gore Thursday to say that he was ``disappointed and offended''
about her comments.
</P>
<P>
	   Under mounting criticism, Gore called Powell to express his great respect
for the general.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We're friends of long standing ... it was a very friendly and warm
conversation,'' Gore said. ``I reaffirmed my total respect and regard for him as
an American hero, for him as a national leader and for him as a personal
friend.''
</P>
<P>
	   The vice president would not say whether he apologized to Powell for
Brazile's comment.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the day, Brazile had called Powell and let him know that she
personally and the Gore campaign consider him ``an American hero.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``The Republicans bring out Colin Powell and J.C. Watts because they have no
program, no policy,'' she said in an interview with Bloomberg.com. ``They play
that game because they have no other game. They have no love and no joy. They'd
rather take pictures with black children than feed them.''
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier in the day, Gore had stood by his campaign manager and publicly
praised Powell.
</P>
<P>
	   ``General Powell is a great hero, who I admire greatly,'' Gore said.
``Having General Powell and Congressman (J.C.) Watts in the Republican Party is,
in fact, no substitute for an agenda that supports all of our people, including
African-Americans. That is what Donna was trying to say.''
</P>
<P>
	   He defended Brazile, saying ``she's doing a great job and she will continue
doing a great job.''
</P>
<P>
	   Watts, an Oklahoma representative who is chairman of the House Republican
Conference, called the comments ``racist.'' Watts said he and Powell have
``worked hard to help African-Americans, especially children.''
</P>
<P>
	   GOP presidential front-runner George W. Bush called it ``slash-and-burn
politics'' and said he would ``watch and see how Vice President Gore handles
it.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``It will be an indication of the kind of administration he might have
should he win the vote,'' Bush said. ``It is unacceptable for her to have done
that to two good people.''
</P>
<P>
	   Powell has been very popular since his role as America's military leader in
the Persian Gulf War. He wrote that his involvement in numerous charities and
youth organizations is intended ``to help feed, educate and spiritually nourish
all of America's children, black and white, and not just for a photo op. And I
do so as a Republican.''
</P>
<P>
	   He asked that the Gore campaign ``not start the new century by playing the
polarizing 'race card' which immediately contaminates and destroys the
opportunity for open debate on issues of importance to our children.''
</P>
<P>
	   Brazile's blunt comments have ruffled feathers before.
</P>
<P>
	   She resigned from the presidential campaign of Democratic nominee Michael
Dukakis in October 1988 after telling reporters they should check out personal
rumors about then-Republican nominee George Bush, former president and father of
the current GOP front-runner.
</P>
<P>
	   Earlier this year, Brazile said ``the four pillars of the Democratic Party
are African-Americans, labor, women, and what I call other ethnic minorities.''
That comment prompted the moderate Democratic Leadership Council to caution the
Gore campaign that such a view risked alienating moderates and independents.
</P>
<P>
	   Sen. Edward Kennedy, who was campaigning with Gore in Iowa Friday, said that
congressional Republicans have not, by their record, ``been the voice of the
voiceless, the dispossessed, or the minority.''
</P>
<P>
	   But the Massachusetts Democrat said Brazile's comments were unfortunate in
terms of the ``individual references.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2058 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Debate Again  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Republican presidential front-runner George W. Bush
said Friday that he would ``liberate the (Panama) Canal if I have to'' to
protect American interests. The front-runner and Sen. John McCain also clashed
sharply over taxes in the second GOP debate in as many nights.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a
surplus that we might not have,'' McCain said to the Texas governor standing a
few feet away on a debate stage.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush retorted that his plan was better than McCain's for lower income
taxpayers, and added firmly: ``There is enough money to take care of Social
Security. There is enough money to take care of the basic services of
government, and there is enough money to give the people a substantial tax cut.
And that's what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing in a state with substantial military facilities and numerous
military retirees, the GOP contenders also sharply criticized Democratic
presidential contenders for saying they would make sure that gays can serve
openly in the military.
</P>
<P>
	   Gary Bauer and Alan Keyes led the attack, and Keyes said he would renew a
ban on gays in the military that was in effect until Bill Clinton won the White
House. He challenged McCain to join him, but the Arizona senator refused. He
said he would stick with the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2100 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0293 </DOCNO>
