<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Church Supports Ecuador President  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Ecuador's Roman Catholic Church on Friday said it was
not taking sides in the growing street demonstrations for President Jamil
Mahuad's resignation.
</P>
<P>
	   ``We do not intervene in party politics,'' Monsignor Jose Eguiguren told
reporters. But in an indirect show of support for the embattled president, he
said, ``We maintain the principle that democracy is and always will be the best
road, no matter how imperfect.''
</P>
<P>
	   Eguiguren said he was responding to an invitation from the leftist-led
Popular Front to hear its proposal to replace Mahuad's centrist government with
one made up of workers and grassroots organizations.
</P>
<P>
	   Meanwhile, Ecuadorean officials said President Clinton phoned Mahuad Friday
and delivered his vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
	   ``President Clinton has expressed in a firm manner his admiration and
support,'' Foreign Minister Benjamin Ortiz told reporters.
</P>
<P>
	   The Popular Front was one of several leftist-led organizations to lead
demonstrations on Thursday in Ecuador's main cities. Police used tear gas to
disperse about 1,000 demonstrators who tried to march on the presidential
palace, and the government called a state of emergency, giving the armed forces
authority to maintain order and detain protesters.
</P>
<P>
	   The Red Cross said at least two people were injured in confrontations with
police, including a 17-year-old male student who suffered a bullet wound in the
neck. It was unclear who fired the shot, it said.
</P>
<P>
	   For the last six months, Mahuad has faced increasing calls to step down from
political rivals on both the left and right, as well as business leaders and
labor unions, who accuse him of incompetence in handling Ecuador's economic
problems.
</P>
<P>
	   Ecuador is struggling through its worst financial crisis since the 1920s.
Last year, the economy shrank 7 percent and inflation topped 60 percent, and
Ecuador's currency has plunged to 23,000 sucres to the dollar from 7,000 sucres
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
	   Mahuad has said he plans to finish his term, which runs until January 2003,
and the politically powerful armed forces have expressed their support for him.
</P>
<P>
	   But a poll released Thursday showed that 53 percent of Ecuadoreans would
like Mahuad to step down, and only 7 percent of those surveyed expressed support
for the Harvard-educated president.
</P>
<P>
	   The poll, conducted by the private firm Cedatos, surveyed 1,800 people and
had a margin for error of plus or minus 3 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2131 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000107.0304 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Debate Again  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Friday night that
he would ``liberate the (Panama) Canal if I have to'' as president to safeguard
American interests. The Republican presidential front-runner and Sen. John
McCain also clashed sharply over tax cuts in the second GOP debate in as many
nights.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a
surplus that we might not have,'' McCain said to his rival, standing a few feet
away on a debate stage.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush retorted that his plan was more generous than McCain's for lower income
taxpayers, and added firmly: ``There is enough money to take care of Social
Security. There is enough money to take care of the basic services of
government, and there is enough money to give the people a substantial tax cut.
And that's what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing in a state with substantial military facilities and numerous
military retirees, the GOP contenders also sharply criticized Democratic
presidential contenders for saying they would only appoint officials to the
Joint Chiefs of Staff who would permit gays to serve openly in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
	   Alan Keyes led the attack, saying he would renew a ban on gays in the
military that was in effect until Bill Clinton won the White House. He
challenged McCain to join him, but the Arizona senator refused. He said he would
stick with the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
	   They attacked as Vice President Al Gore was backpedaling on comments he had
made earlier in the week, declaring he had not meant ``to imply that there
should ever be any kind of inquiry into the personal political opinions of
officers in the U.S. military,'' Gore told reporters at a hastily convened news
conference.
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP field of hopefuls -- Gary Bauer, Steven Forbes and Sen. Orrin Hatch
in addition to Bush,. McCain and Keyes -- met in a warehouse a few weeks before
the South Carolina presidential primary.
</P>
<P>
	   They were joined by an occasionally raucous audience that booed at questions
deemed to be impertinent.
</P>
<P>
	   One such question went to Bush in the opening moments, and concerned the
