<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Letters Spark Questions  </HEADLINE>
   By KALPANA SRINIVASAN Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) -- At least 15 times since 1997, Sen. John McCain wrote
federal regulators in his capacity as Commerce Committee chairman on behalf of
major donors from airlines to telephone companies, hundreds of memos obtained by
The Associated Press show.
</P>
<P>
	   In one such letter, McCain urged the Federal Communications Commission in
the fall of 1998 to give ``serious consideration'' to BellSouth's request to
offer long-distance service. BellSouth employees are the third-largest
contributor to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   And two weeks after Ameritech's chairman held a fund-raiser for him last
spring, McCain sent a stinging letter to federal regulators accusing them of
being unfair toward the phone company's proposed merger with another Bell
company.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter accused the commission of ``applying a different, and much
stricter, burden of proof in this merger proceeding than the commission has
applied in evaluating other mergers.''
</P>
<P>
	   It also said, ``This letter expresses no view on the merits of any issues in
this proceeding and is not written to benefit any particular party.''
</P>
<P>
	   At a debate Friday night, McCain was questioned about the Ameritech letter
and said, ``All the times when I have weighed in, I have asked them to do their
duty and to expedite the procedures as they're laid out under the law and
according to existing regulations.''
</P>
<P>
	   ``I will continue to do that job, and when a constituent, a person of mine
who has trouble -- or a citizen of this country who can't get a reaction or an
answer from a bureaucracy that's paid for with their tax dollars, I believe that
people like me should weigh in,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
	   He called on the other candidates to release letters showing their
intervention on behalf of donors.
</P>
<P>
	   The documents, which were provided to the AP by the Senate Commerce
Committee, were among more than 500 letters McCain has written to federal
agencies over the last three years as the panel's chairman. The committee plans
to make then public Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Fifteen letters reviewed by the AP were on behalf of companies the McCain's
staff identified as large contributors. Most of the rest were on behalf of
constituents, such as more than 20 travel agents who had complained their
commission fees were being capped by airlines.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain is hardly alone in his letter writing. The FCC said this week it had
received between 7,000 and 8,000 pieces of correspondence a year from lawmakers
in the past three years about issues pending before the agency.
</P>
<P>
	   The letters come to light at a pivotal time for McCain in his bid for the
Republican presidential nomination. The Arizona senator has risen in the polls
while campaigning to rid the nation's political system of what he calls the
``pernicious'' influence of money.
</P>
<P>
	   That campaign theme has struck a chord among independents, and has helped
vault McCain into a highly competitive race with Texas Gov. George W. Bush in
New Hampshire, the nation's first primary state.
</P>
<P>
	   But in recent days, he has been forced to answer questions about his role
helping donors.
</P>
<P>
	   In the Ameritech matter, McCain wrote April 12 that the Senate Commerce
Committee chairman and some of his colleagues were ``extremely troubled'' by the
Federal Communications Commission's handling of the proposed merger between SBC
Communications and Ameritech.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain wrote FCC chairman William Kennard: ``Your improvisational process
will only kill more time and raise the chances of a legally flawed decision.''
The letter also was signed by Sens. Conrad Burns, R-Mont., and Sam Brownback,
R-Kan.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter followed on the heels of a $1,000-per-person fund-raiser hosted
March 30 at a Chicago hotel by Ameritech chief Richard Notebaert, a member of
McCain's fund-raising team.
</P>
<P>
	   At the time, Ameritech, a Midwest phone company, had been trying for months
to get FCC approval for its merger with SBC, which is based in the Southwest.
The deal, which eventually was approved, created the nation's largest local
phone company.
</P>
<P>
	   In May, McCain sent another letter to the FCC, criticizing agency personnel
for public statements about the merger and accusing the commission of bias. In
September, Ameritech's Notebaert was host for a second fund-raiser for McCain at
a Chicago club.
</P>
<P>
	   Employees of Ameritech and their families and the company's political action
committee had contributed $16,000 to McCain's presidential campaign through
Sept. 30, his ninth most generous giver. SBC Communications employees and their
families and the company PAC had given a total of $9,750.
</P>
<P>
	   Ameritech denied any connection between the fund-raisers and McCain's
letter.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This was totally Dick Notebaert's personal involvement as a member of the
host committee in Chicago,'' spokesman Dave Pacholczyk said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the BellSouth matter, McCain urged FCC Chairman William Kennard to
consider wireless services, such as Sprint PCS, as competitors to BellSouth.
Such a ruling would remove a regulatory barrier the regional Bell companies
faced in their bids to provide long-distance service.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I encourage you to give serious consideration to whether PCS is providing
competition to the local exchange market,'' McCain wrote.
</P>
<P>
	   Senate Commerce Committee Republican staff director Mark Buse said McCain's
advocacy on behalf of the Baby Bells is consistent with his support for
telecommunications competition that would result in lower prices for customers.
</P>
<P>
	   BellSouth and their employees have contributed $30,000 to his presidential
bid through Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
	   In other letters on behalf of donors:
</P>
<P>
	   --At the behest of Global Crossing, McCain asked the FCC in March 1999 to
encourage the development of undersea cables for transmitting telecommunications
signals.
</P>
<P>
	   --In December 1998, McCain urged the FCC to make it easier for companies to
own more than one television station in a market. The letter's advocacy helps
local TV station owners like Paxson Communications and Sinclair Broadcasting,
two donors to McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
	   --In February 1998, McCain wrote Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater on
behalf of America West airlines, whose employees are contributors to his
campaign, and the city of Flagstaff, Ariz. The letter urged better routes to
surrounding cities.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
