<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Debate Again  </HEADLINE>
   By GLEN JOHNSON Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WEST COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush said Friday night that
he would ``liberate the (Panama) Canal if I have to'' as president to safeguard
American interests. The Republican presidential front-runner and Sen. John
McCain also clashed sharply over tax cuts in the second GOP campaign debate in
as many nights.
</P>
<P>
	   ``It's fiscally irresponsible to promise a huge tax cut that is based on a
surplus that we might not have,'' McCain said to his rival, standing a few feet
away.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush retorted that his plan was more generous than McCain's for lower income
taxpayers, and added firmly: ``There is enough money to take care of Social
Security. There is enough money to take care of the basic services of
government, and there is enough money to give the people a substantial tax cut.
And that's what I intend to do.''
</P>
<P>
	   Appearing in a state with substantial military facilities and numerous
military retirees, the GOP contenders also sharply criticized Democratic
presidential contenders for saying they would only appoint officials to the
Joint Chiefs of Staff who would permit gays to serve openly in the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
	   Alan Keyes led the attack, saying he would renew a ban on gays in the
military that was in effect until Bill Clinton won the White House. He
challenged McCain to join him, but the Arizona senator refused. He said he would
stick with the current ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy.
</P>
<P>
	   They attacked as Vice President Al Gore was backpedaling on comments he had
made earlier in the week, declaring he had not meant ``to imply that there
should ever be any kind of inquiry into the personal political opinions of
officers in the U.S. military.''
</P>
<P>
	   The GOP field of hopefuls -- Gary Bauer, Steven Forbes and Sen. Orrin Hatch
in addition to Bush, McCain and Keyes -- met in a warehouse at a party
fundraising dinner a few weeks before the South Carolina presidential primary.
They were joined by an occasionally raucous dinner crowd that booed at questions
deemed to be impertinent.
</P>
<P>
	   The debate topics ranged broadly, and touched briefly on a controversy
surrounding letters that McCain wrote to federal regulatory agencies on behalf
of political donors. For the second night in a row, McCain, chairman of the
Senate Commerce Committee, said he was merely trying to prod a sluggish
bureaucracy, and said after the debate that his office would release numerous
pieces of correspondence on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush was asked about the Panama Canal by Bauer, who said he opposed the
recent turnover of the waterway to Panama under a treaty ratified by the Senate
in 1977.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush noted that as a young congressional candidate at the time, he had
opposed the treaty. If elected president, he said he will uphold the treaty, but
added that he would do ``whatever it takes to keep the canal open. ... I'll
liberate the canal if I have to'' to maintain Americans trade and other
strategic interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush's father, former President George Bush, dispatched troops to Panama
while serving in the White House.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain jabbed Bush over taxes as part of a running disagreement between the
two men, and Bush returned fire on the subject of campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
	   He said, as he had in New Hampshire on Thursday night, that McCain's
proposal would hurt Republicans. Hatch said with his insistence on campaign
finance overhaul, McCain was beginning to remind him of ``an accordion player
who only knows one tune.''
</P>
<P>
	   McCain stood his ground, though, and said it was essential to rid the
country of the influence of interests.''
</P>
<P>
	   At times, the audience appeared to view the event more as an athletic
contest than a political debate.
</P>
<P>
	   Boos erupted early, in response to a question posed to Bush about the
Confederate flag, which flies atop the Statehouse.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I believe the people of South Carolina can figure out what to do with this
flag issue,'' the Texas governor replied, declining to take sides in a
racially-tinged issue. Moderator Brian Williams sought to pursue the issue, but
the crowd booed louder, and Bush merely repeated that he thought it was an issue
for South Carolinians to decide.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain also said it was an issue for the state's residents to decide.
</P>
<P>
	   McCain, who has campaigned hard in the state, defended anew the letters he
has written to federal agencies on behalf of campaign donors. ``Whenever a
constituent of mine or a citizen ... can't get an answer ... I believe that
people like me should weigh in,'' said McCain, who wrote the letters in his
capacity as chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
	   The senator was addressing a question about an Associated Press story
detailing a letter he wrote last year on behalf of Ameritech, which was seeking
permission to merge with SBC, another phone company.
</P>
<P>
	   The letter-writing issue is a troubling one for McCain, whose candidacy has
flourished on the basis of his call for a ridding the nation's political system
of the influence of big-monied special interests.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush and McCain were the only two asked about the Confederate flag, and the
two men both said it was up to residents of the state to decide.
</P>
<P>
	   Several of the contenders tackled another volatile South Carolina issue, a
proposed state-run lottery.
</P>
<P>
	   Bauer said he was opposed, adding, ``the gambling industry is corrupting our
culture.''
</P>
<P>
	   Forbes harkened back to the lessons learned in his home state of New Jersey,
saying intending to use a lottery to fund education improvements -- as proposed
in South Carolina -- is ``a false deal.''
</P>
<P>
	   Keyes was emphatic. ``If you solicit my advice I'll tell you this: All
governments everywhere -- federal, state, local -- should get out of the
business of putting a corrupting, regressive tax on the backs of their people,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
	   Bush used a post-debate interview with moderator Williams to criticize
commercials the Forbes campaign is preparing in New Hampshire attacking on the
subject of taxes.
</P>
<P>
	   ``I think it doesn't serve the Republican Party well,'' he said, and
predicted that the voters would turn against them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
