<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Speculation in Shipyard Killings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- A fired shipyard employee gunned down two men in a deliberate
act of revenge that was elaborately plotted, prosecutors alleged in filing
murder charges Friday.
</P>
<P>
	   Kevin William Cruz, 30, was charged with two counts of aggravated
first-degree murder and two counts of attempted murder in the Nov. 3 attack.
</P>
<P>
	   ``This is a horrible crime and it fits an alarming trend of incomprehensible
violence in our workplaces, schools and even in our churches,'' King County
Prosecutor Norm Maleng said Friday. Maleng declined to say whether he would seek
the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
	   Cruz was fired from the Northlake Shipyard in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors believe he harbored a grudge because he was fired soon after the
company's insurance company cut off his benefits for a work-related injury,
saying he wasn't really hurt.
</P>
<P>
	   Cruz was arrested Tuesday and was being held on $4 million bail.
</P>
<P>
	   He ``claims to have serious mental problems and states that he hears
voices,'' according to court documents. But Maleng said Cruz, who has an
extensive criminal record, has never been evaluated or treated by the state for
mental illness.
</P>
<P>
	   On Friday, prosecutors detailed a carefully crafted revenge plot.
</P>
<P>
	   They alleged that Cruz grew out his hair and beard to change his appearance,
then, wearing camouflage clothing, slipped into the shipyard's main building and
opened fire on the business office.
</P>
<P>
	   Prosecutors said the gunman first targeted Peter Giles, 27, the shipyard
owners' nephew and acting supervisor, and then shot the foreman, Russell James
Brisendine, 43. Both were killed.
</P>
<P>
	   Patrick Ming, 19, a receptionist, was shot in the arm, and Jaromir Moch, 58,
a customer, was shot at least once in the chest.
</P>
<P>
	   The day after the shootings, Cruz shaved his beard and had a new driver's
license photo taken, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   The insurance company alerted investigators after the shooting that Cruz
might have a grudge. But neither Moch nor Ming recognized a photo of Cruz, who
was then clean-shaven.
</P>
<P>
	   The break in the case came after a bicyclist on Sunday spotted a weathered
backpack hidden in blackberry bushes near the shipyard, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
	   In the pack was a Glock 9mm semiautomatic pistol and, among other things, a
United Airlines toiletry kit. Cruz's mother, who shares a home with her son near
Seattle-Tacoma International Airport, works for United Airlines, investigators
said.
</P>
<P>
	   Cruz acknowledged that the backpack was his, prosecutors said, and
ballistics tests determined the gun had been used in the shipyard
shootings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-01-07-00 2243 </TRAILER>
