<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
   By The Associated Press Rick Acton
<TEXT>
<P>
	   REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Rick Acton, a 27-year member of the Professional Golf
Association, died Thursday of liver cancer. He was 54.
</P>
<P>
	   Acton was an 11-time Hudson Cup Team member and played in nine PGA
championships and four U.S. Open championships. He had three top-five finishes
on the PGA tour.
</P>
<P>
	   From 1973 to 1980 he earned $9,670 on the PGA Tour before being seriously
injured when his car was broadsided by another in Florida.
William Andrew Bates
</P>
<P>
	   KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- William ``Bill'' Andrew Bates, a Kansas City
television pioneer and former WDAF-TV general manager, died Thursday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
	   Bates began his broadcasting career in 1937 at KWOC radio in Poplar Bluff.
Four years later, he joined WDAF radio.
</P>
<P>
	   Bates helped turn WDAF into Kansas City's first commercial TV station in
1949 and later served as manager until 1964. He later headed Mid-America
Television, a subsidiary of Kansas City Southern Industries, until his
retirement in 1986.
Curtis V. Cooper
</P>
<P>
	   SAVANNAH, Ga. (AP) -- Curtis V. Cooper, a community health care advocate who
was president of the Savannah NAACP for almost 24 years, died Wednesday. He was
67. The cause of death has not been determined.
</P>
<P>
	   Cooper moved up from vice president in 1976 when W.W. Law stepped down as
president of the NAACP. He was still head of the local branch at the time of his
death.
William Butterfield Decker
</P>
<P>
	   ASHLAND, Ore. (AP) -- William Butterfield Decker, a novelist and former New
York editor, died Thursday of complication from a stroke. He was 73.
</P>
<P>
	   Decker moved to New York in 1959 and began his career in the publishing
industry at McGraw-Hill. He later became an executive editor at Viking Press.
</P>
<P>
	   Decker edited such authors as Earnest Gaines (``The Autobiography of Miss
Jane Pittman''), Larry McMurtry (``The Last Picture Show''), and Pulitzer
prize-winner Wallace Stegner.
</P>
<P>
	   He wrote two novels: ``To Be A Man'' in 1967, which The New York Times named
one of the 10 best novels of the year, and ``Holdout'' in 1979, which won the
Western Writers Association's Golden Spur award for best Western novel.
Yehuda Ebstein
</P>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Yehuda Ebstein, a former executive of several Jewish
non-profit organizations, died of cancer Dec. 27. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
	   Ebstein spent more than 30 years working for Jewish groups, including the
Development Corporation for Israel, the American Friends of Hebrew University
and the World Jewish Congress, where he was executive director of its American
section.
</P>
<P>
	   In 1964, Ebstein joined the National Committee for Labor Israel, the United
States affiliate of the Israeli national labor organization. He retired in 1992
as executive vice president of the committee.
Makhmud Esambayev
</P>
<P>
	   MOSCOW (AP) -- Makhmud Esambayev, a renowned Chechen dancer who thrilled
audiences in the Soviet Union for decades, died Friday at 75, the news agency
ITAR-Tass reported.
</P>
<P>
	   The report, citing information from a Chechen cultural society, said
Esambayev died in Moscow of an unspecified ailment.
</P>
<P>
	   Esambayev studied music and choreography in the Chechen capital of Grozny
and made his first public appearance at age 14 with the republic's dramatic
theater and philharmonic orchestra.
</P>
<P>
	   Esambayev founded the Premier Ballet Theater in Moscow and won some of the
Soviet Union's top honors, including being named a Hero of Socialist Labor.
Thomas J. MacBride
</P>
<P>
	   SACRAMENTO (AP) -- Thomas J. MacBride, the former state assemblyman and
federal judge who presided over the trial of Lynette ``Squeaky'' Fromme, died
Thursday. He was 85.
</P>
<P>
	   MacBride was appointed to the U.S. District Court by President Kennedy in
1961 and later became chief judge of the Eastern District of California. He
transferred to senior status, a form of semi-retirement, in 1979.
</P>
<P>
	   MacBride was best known for presiding over the dramatic trial of Fromme, a
follower of Charles Manson who was convicted of attempting to kill President
Ford in 1975.
</P>
<P>
	   MacBride served in the Assembly from 1955 until 1960.
Don Martin
</P>
<P>
	   MIAMI (AP) -- Don Martin, the Mad magazine cartoonist whose hapless
characters met frying-pan-in-the-face fates punctuated by wacky sounds like
SHAGLOMP! and SHKLIP!, died Thursday of cancer. He was 68.
</P>
<P>
	   His jokes prompted the magazine to dub him ``Mad's Maddest Cartoonist.''
</P>
<P>
	   Martin's cartoons had a vocabulary all their own. ``SHKLIP'' was the sound
made when construction workers tossed concrete at each other. ``SPLOP''
described a surgeon throwing body parts into a doggie bag. ``FAGROON'' came from
a collapsing skyscraper.
</P>
<P>
	   Martin left Mad magazine in 1987 after a falling-out with its publisher, the
late William Gaines, and accepted a job at Cracked, a competitor.
</P>
<P>
	   His paperbacks of cartoons not published in the magazine sold more than 7
million copies.
Patrick O'Brian
</P>
<P>
	   LONDON (AP) -- Patrick O'Brian, whose celebrated novels of 19th century
seafaring won praise from critics and the loyalty of readers, has died. He was
85.
</P>
<P>
	   The cause of death was not given and there were conflicting reports of the
date. The British Embassy in Paris said O'Brian died Tuesday; his New York
publisher said O'Brian died Sunday.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Brian's major work was a 20-volume series set in the Royal Navy during the
Napoleonic wars.
</P>
<P>
	   The series, begun in 1969 with ``Master and Commander,'' is the story of the
friendship between an ambitious navy officer and the ship's surgeon, a
naturalist and secret agent who doesn't like sailing.
</P>
<P>
	   O'Brian also wrote biographies of Picasso and naturalist Sir Joseph Banks
and translated the work of French writers Simone de Beauvoir and Colette.
Alex Pitcher
</P>
<P>
	   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Alex Pitcher, a civil rights leader who helped prepare
legal briefs for the Supreme Court decision in Brown vs. Board of Education,
died Thursday. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitcher was named president of the San Francisco chapter of the NAACP in
1994.
</P>
<P>
	   He worked with Thurgood Marshall, then chief attorney for the NAACP, and in
1954, he helped Marshall prepare the briefs that helped determine the decision
in the historic school desegregation case.
</P>
<P>
	   The Supreme Court ruled that separating public schools in Topeka, Kan., by
race was inherently unequal. The ruling resulted in the desegregation of school
systems nationwide.
</P>
<P>
	   Pitcher moved to San Francisco in 1963 and continued his civil rights work.
James W. Walter
</P>
<P>
	   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- James W. Walter, founder of a leading home builder and
industrial company, died Thursday of lung cancer. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
	   Walter's Tampa-based business, Jim Walter Homes, sold and financed more than
330,000 single-family houses in 24 states.
</P>
<P>
	   The company, later under the names Jim Walter Corp. and Walter Industries,
diversified into coal mining, paper distribution and aluminum products, becoming
one of the 200 largest industrial companies in the nation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
