<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-01-07 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dominicans Aim To Keep Out Haitians  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- Dominican soldiers on Friday began
a 15-day mission on the border with Haiti to guard against the illegal entry of
Haitians and repatriate immigrants without documents.
</P>
<P>
	   The issue of Haitians repatriated from the Dominican Republic has caused
friction between the two countries, which share the Caribbean island of
Hispaniola. Haiti accused the Dominican Republic of expelling as many as 5,000
undocumented Haitians without allowing them to collect their belongings, but
Dominican officials claimed that they followed proper procedures.
</P>
<P>
	   Gen. Manuel de Jesus Florentino, secretary of the armed forces, said the
mission began early Friday morning for training purposes and to guard the border
from illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
	   Last month, the Dominican government promised to be more careful to protect
human rights when repatriating undocumented Haitian nationals. In turn, Haiti
promised to step up its own border patrols.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
